{ @@HeaderStart@@Key middlegame themes and pawn structures@@HeaderEnd@@This chapter illustrates a number of key middlegame and endgame themes that occur time and time again in the Ruy Lopez.  Understanding the strategic concepts outlined in this chapter will assist you in absorbing the material in the theoretical chapters and help you make better decisions in practical games. It is my hope that it will also improve your general chess understanding! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Pawn Structure | Closed Ruy Lopez"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/p4ppp/3p4/1p1Pp3/2p1P3/2P5/PP1N1PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Closed Ruy Lopez@@HeaderEnd@@The structure shown in the diagram is known as the Closed Ruy Lopez. The center is locked, meaning play will take place on the kingside and/or the queenside.   White's main plans   (1)  Start a kingside attack with g2-g4 and Nbd2-f1-g3-f5 or f2-f4;    (2)  Expand on the queenside with b2-b4 followed by a2-a4 intending to invade through the a-file and target Black's queenside pawns.  
Black's main plans   (1)  Expand on the queenside with ... a5 and ...b5-b4;    (2)  Start active operations on the kingside with ... f5-f4. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following model game illustrate how effective blocking up the queenside can be in enhancing the strength of White's kingside attack. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Na5 { Black opts for the Chigorin variation. } 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7
12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. d5
{ Karpov, with the White pieces, expands in the center going for the Closed Ruy Lopez structure. This is particularly timely given Black's c6 knight does not have a good square. }
13... Nd8
{ The knight may look silly on d8 but it can be re-routed to c5.   13...Na5  On a5, the knight would be effectively restricted by  14.b3± }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/2q1bppp/p1np1n2/1pp1p3/3PP3/2P2N1P/PPBN1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The following model game illustrate how effective blocking up the queenside can be in enhancing the strength of White's kingside attack. }
1. d5
{ Karpov, with the White pieces, expands in the center going for the Closed Ruy Lopez structure. This is particularly timely given Black's c6 knight does not have a good square. }
1... Nd8 { How should White continue? } 2. a4
{ A timely break, taking advantage of the fact that ...b4 would severely weaken the c4 square and allow White to jump in with Nc4. }
2... Rb8
{ Black maintains the tension @@StartBracket@@and control over the c4 square@@EndBracket@@ at the cost of giving up the a-file. }
3. axb5 axb5 4. b4
{ A fantastic move, severely restricting the d8 knight which will no longer be able to come to c5.  Black's queenside pawns are merely targets, which White can start to pressure with moves such as Nf1 followed by Be3 and Bd3. White's queen will then move up to d2, connecting the rooks which can be doubled on the a-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rbn1rk1/2q1bppp/3p1n2/1ppPp3/4P3/2P2N1P/1PBN1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

16. b4
{ A fantastic move, severely restricting the d8 knight which will no longer be able to come to c5. Black's queenside pawns are merely targets, which White can start to pressure with moves such as Nf1 followed by Be3 and Bd3. White's queen will then move up to d2, connecting the rooks which can be doubled on the a-file. }
16... Nb7 17. Nf1 Bd7 18. Be3
{ Karpov continues developing naturally. Qd2 is up next to connect the rooks. }
18... Ra8 { Black naturally challenges White's control over the a-file. } 19.
Qd2 Rfc8 20. Bd3 g6
{ Black is hinting at a possible kingside expansion with ...f5. } 21. Ng3
{ White completes the knight-tour and effectively rules out Black's ...f5 pawn break, which will be very hard to achieve with the bishop on d3 and White knight on g3. }
21... Bf8 { Onto the next puzzle! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r2bk1/1nqb1p1p/3p1np1/1ppPp3/1P2P3/2PBBNNP/3Q1PP1/R3R1K1 w - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How can White take control over the a-file? } 22. Ra2
{ White prepares to double-rooks on the a-file. } 22... c4
{ A commital move, releasing the tension which only eases White's task. The queenside is now blocked up, which will give White a free hand on the kingside later on.   Penetrating along the c-file after  22...cxb4  23.cxb4  Rxa2  24.Qxa2  Qc3  fails to accomplish anything. White can respond with the cool  25.Qb1  threatening Rc1 and meet  25...Qa3  with  26.Re2±  with the idea Ra2 to kick back Black's queen. }
23. Bb1
{ Karpov opts to maintain the bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal so as to keep control over the f5 square. }
23... Qd8 24. Ba7
{ A fantastic move, which you will find in many strategy books on chess. White blocks up the queenside, which will enable the first player to @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ double on the a-file uncontested and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ expand on the kingside without giving Black any queenside counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1rq1bk1/1n1b1p1p/3p1np1/1p1Pp3/1Pp1P3/2P1BNNP/R2Q1PP1/1B2R1K1 w - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

24. Ba7
{ A fantastic move, which you will find in many strategy books on chess. White blocks up the queenside, which will enable the first player to @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ double on the a-file uncontested and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ expand on the kingside without giving Black any queenside counterplay. }
24... Ne8 25. Bc2 Nc7
{ 25...Ng7  to try to get in f5 is no good.  26.Rea1  f5?  only weakens Black's kingside. Following  27.exf5  gxf5  28.Be3  White now puts his attention firmly on the kingside.  28...Rxa2  29.Rxa2  Ra8  30.Bg5  Qb8  31.Rxa8  Qxa8  32.Bf6+-  Qg5 as well as Nh4 are coming. Black's king is in big trouble. }
26. Rea1 Qe7 27. Bb1 Be8
{ Black has no active plan and is relegated to shuffling his pieces aimlessly. Onto the next puzzle! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r2bk1/Bnnbqp1p/3p2p1/1p1Pp3/1Pp1P3/2P2NNP/R2Q1PP1/RB4K1 b - - 0 27"]
[SetUp "1"]

27... Be8
{ Black has not active plan and is relegated to shuffling his pieces aimlessly. With full control over the a-file, it's time to open another front of attack. How can White achieve this? }
28. Ne2
{ The knight has done its job on g3. Karpov now prepares the f4 break. } 28...
Nd8 29. Nh2 Bg7 30. f4
{ Notice how the locked up queenside gives White a free hand on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1rnb1k1/B1n1qpbp/3p2p1/1p1Pp3/1Pp1P3/2P4P/R2QNPPN/RB4K1 w - - 0 30"]
[SetUp "1"]

30. f4 f6
{ Black is trying to keep the position closed but his passivity will eventually lead to defeat.   30...exf4  31.Nxf4  f6±  intending ...Nf7-e5 was a better try. }
31. f5 g5
{ Black continues trying to keep the position closed, hoping White won't be able to break through. Onto the next puzzle! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1rnb1k1/B1n1q1bp/3p1pp1/1p1PpP2/1Pp1P3/2P4P/R2QN1PN/RB4K1 b - - 0 31"]
[SetUp "1"]

31... g5
{ Which is White's least active piece? Can you find a way to activate it while exchanging one of Black's key minor pieces? }
32. Bc2
{ The start of a beautiful manoever seeking to exchange the light-squared bishops. Black will then have no way of preventing an invasion along the light-squares. }
32... Bf7 33. Ng3 Nb7 34. Bd1 h6 35. Bh5
{ The bishop has made it's way to h5, aiming to exchange one of Black's key defenders. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #9"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r3k1/Bnn1qbb1/3p1p1p/1p1PpPp1/1Pp1P3/2P3NP/R2Q2PN/R2B2K1 w - - 0 35"]
[SetUp "1"]

35. Bh5
{ The bishop has made it's way to h5, aiming to exchange one of Black's key defenders. }
35... Qe8 36. Qd1 Nd8 37. Ra3 Kf8 38. R1a2 Kg8 { Onto to the next puzzle! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #10"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1rnq1k1/B1n2bb1/3p1p1p/1p1PpPpB/1Pp1P3/R1P3NP/R5PN/3Q2K1 w - - 0 39"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White's knight on h2 is doing next to nothing. Can you find a way to bring it into the game? }
39. Ng4 { A nice way of activating the h2-knight. } 39... Bxh5
{ Capturing the knight fails tactically to... } 40. Nxh5 Qxh5 41. Nxf6+ Bxf6
42. Qxh5 { wins the queen and soon the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes"]
[Black "Blocking the queenside #11"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1rnq1k1/B1n2bb1/3p1p1p/1p1PpPpB/1Pp1P3/R1P3NP/R5PN/3Q2K1 w - - 0 39"]
[SetUp "1"]

39. Ng4 { A nice way of activating the h2-knight! } 39... Kf8
{ Unzicker realized taking the knight loses and instead shuffled the king.   39...Bxh5  fails to  40.Nxh5  Qxh5  41.Nxf6+  Bxf6  42.Qxh5+- }
40. Ne3 Kg8 41. Bxf7+ Nxf7 42. Qh5 Nd8 43. Qg6
{ Black now finds himself in zugzwang. } 43... Kf8 44. Nh5
{ Black threw in the towel as there's no saving his position.   44....Qxg6  Any other move and White will play Bb6 to take over the a-file.  45.fxg6+-  Next up is Nf5 when Black's position will collapse.  1-0 @@StartBracket@@4@@EndBracket@@ Anatoly Karpov - Wolfgang Unzicker Nice Olympiad 1974. }
*

