{ Black tries to keep the position closed, hoping White won't be able to break through. }
32. Bc2
{ The start of a beautiful maneuver seeking to exchange the light-squared bishops. Black will then have no way of preventing an invasion along the light-squares. }
32... Bf7 33. Ng3 Nb7 34. Bd1 h6 35. Bh5
{ The bishop has made its way to h5, aiming to exchange one of Black's key defenders. }
35... Qe8 36. Qd1 Nd8 37. Ra3 Kf8 38. R1a2 Kg8 39. Ng4
{ A nice way of activating the h2-knight! } 39... Kf8
{ 39...Bxh5  fails to  40.Nxh5  Qxh5  41.Nxf6+  Bxf6  42.Qxh5+- } 40. Ne3 Kg8
41. Bxf7+ Nxf7 42. Qh5 Nd8 43. Qg6 { Black now finds himself in zugzwang. }
43... Kf8 44. Nh5
{ Black threw in the towel as there's no saving his position. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@4@@EndBracket@@ Anatoly Karpov - Wolfgang Unzicker Nice Olympiad 1974. A great example of how effective blocking up the queenside can be in enhancing the strength of White's kingside attack.   44...Qxg6  Any other move and White will play Bb6 and take over the a-file.  45.fxg6+-  Next up is Nf5 when Black's position will collapse. }
