[SetUp "1"]

{ Black captured the d4 pawn with the knight. White must now be precise to maintain the upper hand. How should the first player continue? }
1. Nxd4 { Nothing spectacular here, Black's d4 pawn had to be eliminated. }
1... Bxd4 2. Ne7+
{ This is White's only chance to put pressure on Black's position. } 2... Kh8
3. Qd3
{ White vacates the c2 square for the b3 bishop with tempo. Despite being two pawns up, Black is dead lost. }
3... h6
{ 3...Be5  fails to  4.Bc2  threatening Bxf6 followed by mate on h7.  4...g6  5.Rxe5  dxe5  6.Bxf6  is all she wrote. }
4. Bxf6
{ Ironically, even h3-h4 was good enough to win the game. The text is the most direct option. }
4... Bxf6 5. Bc2 { White threatens mate on h7, forcing } 5... g6
{ Every move thus far has been forced. And yet again White must follow up in the most energetic way! }
6. Nxg6+ { It's all about precise calculation from hereon. } 6... fxg6 7. Qxg6
Qd7 8. Qxh6+ Kg8 9. Ra3
{ The ROVER @@StartBracket@@rook and up over!@@EndBracket@@ will now decide the game. }
9... Rf7 { is Black's last attempt to mount any resistance. } *

