[SetUp "1"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Exchange Spanish structure@@HeaderEnd@@The Exchange Spanish structure is one of the most important pawn formations in our repertoire. It features most prominently in the Berlin chapter.  This is very similar to the true Exchange Spanish structure where White usually trades off the d-pawn for the e5 pawn and tries to create a kingside majority. Here, we usually opt for d3-d4 but not to create a kingside majority. Instead, we're aiming to establish a strong central pawn duo with c2-c3 + d3-d4.   White's Typical Ideas:     (1)   The e5-pawn is usually a target. White’s kingside knight can target it from f3 and the d2 knight frequently pops out to c4 to increase the pressure. It’s also possible to include the dark-squared bishop with either b2-b3 followed by Bb2 or Bd2-c3.    (2)    Black can play ...Be6 to prevent Nd2-c4. In this case, White usually puts the d2 knight on b3. Black is more than welcome to chop on b3, which would open the a-file. If he opts to keep the two bishops advantage, he’ll have to contend with the annoying Nb3-a5 incursion.    (3)   If Black’s dark-squared bishop abandons the a7-g1 diagonal, White can expand with f2-f4. If the light-squared bishops are exchanged, this advance can even be prepared with g2-g3.    (4)    If Black is fast enough with ...Nd7, ...f7-f6, and Nf8  (without castling)  , White can turn his attention to the queenside with c2-c3, b2-b4, a2-a4, and a timely d3-d4 break!     (5)    There is a point behind 'without castling' above. If Black castles short early on, White has the additional option of starting a kingside attack. This can be done by sending our king to the queenside and then pushing g2-g4-g5. This pawn advance is especially effective when Black creates a hook with ...f7-f6.     (6)    White can forego immediate castling to retain as much flexibility as possible.    (7)    The f5 square is usually vulnerable in Black’s camp. White can consider maneuvers like Nc4-e3-f5 and Nh4-f5 to anchor a knight on this outpost.  Black's Typical Ideas    (1)    Black will typically consolidate his center with ...f7-f6.    (2)    The d7 knight can be rerouted with ...Nd7-f8-e6. Alternatively, posting the knight on g6 runs into h4-h5 ideas.  Tense struggle  All in all, both sides have their trumps with a tough positional battle on the board. Small, strategic nuances play a key role and it’s more important to be familiar with the typical ideas rather than memorizing tons of variations. That said, White usually has a very slight but safe edge due to his space advantage. This means Black can never relax and always risks being slowly outplayed. While it’s very hard to break down Black’s position, the lines recommended in the theory section were chosen to put maximum pressure on the second player. }
1. -- *

