{ The following is a model game between Dominguez and Aronian from the Saint Louis Rapid & Blitz leg of the 2019 Grand Chess tour. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Be6 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nb3 a5
{ White's knight was headed to prime real estate on a5. In light of this, Black decided to put his own pawn on a5 to stop it. }
9. Qe1 a4 10. Na5 { The knight ended up making its way to a5! } 10... Qb8 11.
b4
{ secures the knight on a5. Moreover, the c1 bishop can pop out to b2 to pressure the e5 pawn. }
11... Bg4 12. Nh4 O-O 13. Nc4 Be6 14. Nxd6
{ Recognizing when and which pieces to trade is a crucial skill in chess. Here, White goes for opposite colored bishops which will help create attacking chances on the kingside @@StartBracket@@particularly along the dark-squares@@EndBracket@@. }
14... cxd6 15. f4 { White starts active play on the kingside! } 15... exf4 16.
Bxf4 Re8 17. a3 Nh5 18. Bd2 d5 19. Qe2 Nf6
{ 19...Qe5!  was necessary and would have a put a big dent on White's attacking ambitions. }
20. Rxf6
{ Boom goes the dynamite! This sacrifice shatters Black's kingside and weakens a bunch of dark squares. The d2 bishop couldn't be happier! }
20... gxf6 21. Rf1 { Don't forget to invite everyone to the party! } 21... dxe4
22. Bc3 Qd6 23. Bxf6
{ Black's king barely has any defenders and all the dark-squares are compromised. White has a decisive attack and quickly won: }
23... h6 24. Qh5 Kh7 25. Nf5 Qf8 26. dxe4 Rad8 27. Rf4
{ Here comes the ROVER @@StartBracket@@rook up and over@@EndBracket@@! Black's king is toast. }
27... Rd2 28. Rg4 Rd1+ 29. Kf2 Rd2+ 30. Ke1 Rxc2 31. Bg7
{ Black was about to get checkmated and resigned in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Dominguez Perez,L  @@StartBracket@@2763@@EndBracket@@-Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019. }
