{ This position arose from the 6.d3 Spanish variation in a game between two strong engines. White has the upper hand, but care is needed to remain in the drivers seat. The first task White needs to figure out is how to reply to Black's last move in ...Nb4, hitting the light-squared bishop. Should it go to b3 or b1? }
22. Bb1
{ 22.Bb3  is far worse given Black can chase the bishop down with  22...a5 }
22... Nc6
{ a3 was on the agenda so Black decides to re-route the knight to c4 via a5. }
23. a3
{ A logical follow up, taking control over the b4 square and opening up a window for the light-squared bishop on a2. If Black isn't fast enough with ...c5, White can create a bind on the queenside with Rc1 and b2-b4. }
23... Na5 24. a4
{ Now that Black's knight has moved away and can no longer access the b4 square, White switches gears and undermines Black's structure with a4! }
24... Nc4 { Onto to the next puzzle! } *

