[Black "Classical defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ The Classical defense is quite possibly the oldest line in the Ruy Lopez. It was occasionally played by Boris Spassky and Boris Gulko. }
4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5
{ A strong intermezzo, gaining space and dislodging the knight! } 6... Ne4 7.
O-O
{ White is now threatening to take full control over the center with cxd4. }
7... d5 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Be3
{ is actually just an extra tempo for White over a theoretical variation in the Italian @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bc4  Bc5  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4  exd4  6.e5 }
9... O-O 10. Bxc6
{ Compromises Black's structure. White will now target the weak c6 pawn. }
10... bxc6 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Nfd2 f5 13. f4
{ By going f2-f4, White prevents Black from creating couterplay on the kingside with ...f4 and ...g5. Black's knight on e4 is pretty but has no targets while the bishop on b6 is completely restricted. Conversely, White will exploit the weaknesses along the c-file with Nc3-a4 and Rac1. All in all, White is clearly better. }
