[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Smyslov"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ This variation is typically called the Smyslov variation. Some authors have referred to 3...g6 as the Fianchetto or Pillsbury defense. This is because there's more than one variation in the Ruy Lopez complex named after the 7th World-Champion Vasily Smyslov. This line was popular in the 1980s but is rarely seen nowadays in classical time controls given that White can count on a sizeable advantage after both 4. c3 and 4. d4. }
4. c3
{ Preparing to take over the center with d2-d4 is the simplest route towards an edge.   The immediate  4.d4  exd4  5.c3  is another interesting line I considered recommending. }
4... Bg7 5. d4 exd4
{ 5...Nge7  allows  6.d5±  gaining a lot of space and pushing back Black's knight. }
6. cxd4 a6
{ 6...Nge7  allows White to push ahead with  7.d5  Following  7...a6  8.Be2  Ne5  9.Nxe5  Bxe5  10.O-O±  followed by f2-f4 gives White a clear edge thanks to the big space advantage. }
7. Ba4 b5
{ Mamedyarov has played this line with Black several times. Black is, however, far from equalizing given that White has full control over the center. }
8. Bb3 Nge7 9. a4
{ A very rare and interesting move, played by two strong Indian GMs Sasikiran and Vishnu as well as Spanish superstar David Antón. White immediately undermines Black's overextended queenside structure. }
9... b4
{ is Black's most natural move. The second player takes the c3 square away from our knight but weakens the c4 square in the process.   9...Bb7  occurred in the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Sasikiran,K  @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@-Romanov,E @@StartBracket@@2614@@EndBracket@@ Sitges 2018 where White played 10. O-O. Here I like the novel  10.h4Ν  launching Harry down the board.  10...O-O  11.h5→  with a strong attack. }
10. O-O O-O 11. h3
{ White should first take control over the g4 square before expanding on the kingside with a4-a5.   Note that  11.a5  is strongly met by  11...d5!  Now  12.e5?  is a big mistake since it allows  12...Bg4!  @@StartBracket@@11. h3 rules this out@@EndBracket@@  13.Be3  f6∓  when White's central construction collapses. Black is already significantly better. }
*

