1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 f5
{ The Deferred Schliemann has a very dubious reputation and for good reason. The inclusion of ...a6 and Ba4 favors White, as the bishop is less exposed on a4, and allows the first player to immediately strike in the center with }
5. d4
{ opening up the center to exploit the slight lead in development.    It turns out the bishop is safer on a4 than on b5. For comparison, consider d2-d4 after the actual Schliemann with   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f5  4.d4?!  fxe4  5.Nxe5  Nxe5  6.dxe5  c6  , and now White has to sacrifice the bishop because moving it runs into ...Qa5+ and ...Qxe5. }
5... fxe4
{ 5...exd4  allows White to push ahead with  6.e5  After  6...Bc5  7.O-O  Nge7  8.c3!  dxc3  9.Nxc3  O-O  10.Nd5±  Black is in big trouble with Bb3 and Bg5 in the cards. }
6. Nxe5
{ White jumps into the center and threatens to play Bxc6 followed by Qh5+, exploiting the drawback of ...f5. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O Bd6 8. Ng4
{ is very strong, intending to swap off the knight on f6 which will leave Black's e4 pawn chronically weak. }
