[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Schliemann"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann Defense, also known as the Jaenisch Gambit, is one of the sharpest variations in the Ruy Lopez. Black immediately challenges the e4 pawn, seeking to play ...fxe4 which would open the f-file and leave him with a central pawn majority. He often sacrifices a pawn @@StartBracket@@or even two@@EndBracket@@ to try and take over the initiative. Despite not having the best reputation, this gambit scores reasonably well at the club level and is sometimes even played at the very top level as a surprise weapon. Radjabov and Aronian played several times against super-GM opposition in the 2000s. Recently, it was recommended in the Chessable course The Thrilling Jaenisch Gambit by GM Sethuraman, who came up with a lot of very interesting and novel ideas. }
4. d3
{ Reinforcing the e4 pawn with 4. d3 is our recommendation and currently considered to be the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit.   4.exf5?!  runs into  4...e4  This is the reason we start with 4. d3, when we're actually threatening to take on f5 as Black can no longer play ...e4. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O
{ is White's best move, completing development of the kingside.  The natural   6.Nc3  allows  6...Bb4  when Black can spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3 and is ready to castle short on the next turn with good play along the f-file. }
6... Bc5 { is Black's most common and active option. } 7. Bxc6
{ is the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit. White gives up the bishop pair to win the e5 pawn. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nd3
{ is White's most popular continuation and arguably the most challenging option as detailed in the followinginformational line. }
10... Bd4
{ Worse is  10...Bb6  11.Bf4  Ba6  12.Re1±  White is a pawn up and can go after Black's bishop with Na4 next. }
11. Ne2
{ is an important move as Black was threatening to spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3. }
11... Bb6 12. Bg5 { is White's best way of covering the e4 pawn. } 12... Qe8
13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. Ng3
{ Consolidates the extra pawn. Black now has to be very accurate to get compensation for the pawn deficit.   For more details, refer to therespective theoretical chapter of the course. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Cozio"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ is known as the Cozio defense, the most established alternative to 3...a6 and a serious move that was recommended by GM Erwin l'Ami on Chessable.   With  3...Nge7  Black reinforces the knight so as to be able to meet  4.Bxc6  with  4...Nxc6  and thus avoid having to double the queenside pawns. This comes at the cost of the g8 knight being less active on e7 than f6 and restricting the f8 bishop, which will typically be fianchettoed after ... g6. }
4. d4
{ Immediately striking in the center with 4. d4 is arguably White's best shot at an opening advantage.   4.Nc3  is also interesting and given as analternative recommendation in the main theoretical section of the course.   4.c3  isn't nearly as good here because of  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  dxe4=  Black is doing very well with ...Qd5 coming next. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 g6
{ This is Black's most popular move but not a particularly good one. White emerges with a comfortable edge after swapping on c6 and developing naturally. }
6. Nxc6 Nxc6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Be3
{ Coming up are Qd2 and O-O to complete development. In case of ...a6, White can simply drop the light-squared bishop back to e2. }
8... a6 9. Be2 O-O 10. Qd2
{ White will castle on the next turn and can then expand on the kingside with f2-f4. Black, on the other hand, has less space and will find it hard to come up with an active plan.   In the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@73@@EndBracket@@ Krzywda,A @@StartBracket@@2110@@EndBracket@@-Diermair,A @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@ Katowice 2021, which you can find in thereferences game chapter, White quickly got a very big advantage and ended up beating an opponent rated nearly 400 points higher. }
*

