[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Steinitz"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ The most challenging and logical continuation is to go for } 4. d4
{ immediately gaining space and putting pressure on Black's center. } 4... exd4
5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3
{ White develops the minor pieces to the most active and natural squares. Next up is O-O. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nxc6
{ is the simplest option, compromising Black's queenside structure. } 8... Bxc6
{ 8...bxc6  9.Bd3⩲  we retreat to d3 again, this time because the e4 pawn is vulnerable. White will push the f-pawn up to f4 next. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. f4 O-O 11. Qf3
