[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Deferred Steinitz "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Steinitz Defense Deferred, also known as the Modern Steinitz, is one of the most interesting sidelines in the Ruy Lopez complex. By starting with 4...d6 and delaying the development of the g8 knight, Black retains a great deal of flexibility and the option of playing ...f7-f5 and even ....g7-g5 in many cases. }
5. O-O
{ is the first important crossroad.   5.c3  allows the Siesta variation with  5...f5  which leads to very sharp and messy positions. White does best in avoiding this swamp.   Coversely  5.O-O !  rules out  5...f5  due to  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4!  A powerful central strike. With our king already on g1 and Black's king still on e8, the second player is ill-equipped to deal with the opening of the e-file. }
5... Bd7
{ This is the so-called Modern Steinitz variation. Black delays ...b7-b5 for as long as possible and keeps the knight on g8 flexible. }
6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1
{ White covers the e4 pawn and is now ready to expand in the center with d2-d4. }
7... g6 8. d4 Bg7 9. h3 O-O { is the main tabiya of the Deferred Steinitz. }
10. Bc2
{ is my preferred move order. The plan is to develop the bishop to e3 before bringing out the b1 knight.   10.Nbd2  is White's main move, but it allows  10...exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  a rather annoying move, threatening jump into d3. 10. Bc2 rules this out given that with the knight still on b1, the d3 square is safely guarded.   10.d5  Ne7  11.Bxd7  Nxd7  12.c4  a5  13.Nc3  h6  followed by ...f5 gives Black good counterplay. }
10... Re8
{ The good news is White played 11. Nbd2 in all of them, but the simplest is to just close the position with }
11. d5 Ne7 12. c4 b5
{ Makes perfect sense, trying to at least gain some space on the queenside. }
13. b3 c6 14. Nc3
{ Black is solid but passive. White is at least slightly better with good pressure on the c6 and b5 pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Norwegian"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This early knight sortie is known as the Norwegian variation, also dubbed the Taimanov or Wing variation in some chess circles. Its name derives from the fact that it was introduced by Svein Johannasen in 1957 and later popularized by several Norwegian players, most notably Simen Agdestein.   Black's idea is to eliminate our light-squared bishop, gaining the bishop pair in the process. If the second player can survive the opening, he'd then be able to reach a favorable middlegame with the two bishops.   The main drawback of 5...Na5 is that it wastes a lot of time, which we'll exploit by countering in the center. }
6. O-O
{ Popular and principled. White secures his king and is now ready to blast open the center with d2-d4. }
6... Nxb3 7. axb3 d6 8. d4
{ As usual, we take over the center at the earliest opportunity. } 8... f6
{ Black is trying to keep his center together. White must play energetically to emerge with an advantage. }
9. Nc3 { 9.c4  is well met by  9...b4! } 9... Bb7
{ is the most logical square for the bishop.   9...Bg4?!  makes little sense as the bishop can be promptly kicked back with  10.h3  Bh5  11.dxe5  fxe5  12.g4  Bg6  13.Ng5  The knight now moves in!  13...Qd7  14.Nd5±  gives White a clear advantage. The first player can look to to hunt down Black's king with f4 or disturb Black with another cheeky knight jump in the form of Ne6.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/2p3pp/p2p1p2/1p2p3/3PP1b1/1PN2N1P/1PP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b k@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxf3  is no improvement. After  11.Qxf3  exd4  12.Ne2  c5  13.Nf4  is close to winning. Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
10. Qd3
{ is the best square for the queen. White reinforces the e4 pawn while clearing the d1 square for the rook. }
10... Ne7 11. Rd1
{ White is undoubtedly better. The second player will struggle to complete development while all of White's pieces have good squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Berlin 4...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ The Berlin defense is one of the best lines against the Spanish. It was used to great effect by Vladimir Kramnik to put an end to Kasparov's dominant reign in their 2000 World Championship match. Ever since it's only gained in popularity and is now a staple in the repertoire of the world's elite. }
4. d3
{ This variation, known as the Anti-Berlin, has been gaining in popularity given that White has failed to show an edge in the Berlin endgame.   4.O-O  is White's other major option.  4...Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Thousands upon thousands of games have been played in this fascinating endgame. Black has been doing very well here and has more than one way to equalize. }
4... Bc5
{ This is Black's main move, developing the bishop to its most active square. }
5. Bxc6
{ immediately going for the Exchange Ruy Lopez structure - a good way of challenging the Berlin without having to learn tons of theory. This is an opportune moment to take on c6 as Black is forced to recapture with the d7-pawn. This leads to a superior pawn structure for the first player who only has one pawn island compared to Black's two. In turn, the second player gets the bishop pair but it won't be easy to make use of them given the closed nature of the position. }
5... dxc6 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. Nc4 Re8 { is one of Black's most testing lines. } 8.
a4
{ is my preferred approach when Black hasn't yet committed to ...f6. This semi-useful move discourages ...b5 and maintains maximum flexibility.   8.Qe2  preparing to castle long is not as effective as Black will quickly be able to mobilize the queenside pawns. If instead White goes to the kingside, Black will regroup with ...f6 and ... Nd7-f8-e6 with a good game. }
8... Nd7
{ A typical regrouping, overprotecting the e5 pawn and likely heading to e6. }
9. Bd2 { is another useful developing move that avoids committing our king. }
9... b6 10. b4 Bd6 { 10...Bf8  is similarly met by  11.O-O } 11. O-O
{ After gaining space on the queenside, White's king naturally heads to the kingside. }
11... Nf8
{ 11...f6  once again allows White to gain space with  12.h4!?  Nf8  13.h5  with a space advantage on both flanks of the board. }
12. h3
{ White has the better side of equality with extra space on the queenside. We can look to expand with a5 and can chop on d6 at an opportune moment. Anytime Black goes ...f6, Nh4-f5 becomes an option. }
*

