[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Berlin 4...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ The Berlin defense is one of the best lines against the Spanish. It was used to great effect by Vladimir Kramnik to put an end to Kasparov's dominant reign in their 2000 World Championship match. Ever since it's only gained in popularity and is now a staple in the repertoire of the world's elite. }
4. d3
{ This variation, known as the Anti-Berlin, has been gaining in popularity given that White has failed to show an edge in the Berlin endgame.   4.O-O  is White's other major option.  4...Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Thousands upon thousands of games have been played in this fascinating endgame. Black has been doing very well here and has more than one way to equalize. }
4... d6
{ Black opts to keep the bishop inside the pawn chain, hoping to quickly develop with ...Be7, ...O-O and then look to break in the center with ...d5 later on. }
5. O-O Be7 { This is Black's main move, clearing the way for ...O-O. } 6. c3
O-O 7. Re1
{ This is the tabiya of the 4...d6 Berlin, especially if Black is heading towards the Closed Ruy Lopez or the 6.d3 variation.   Here  7...a6  transposes into the 6...d6 line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2
{ Compared to the standard Closed Spanish position, White has played Bc2 in one go and hasn't yet committed to h3 @@StartBracket@@note that ...Bg4 is only ever a concern when White has played d2-d4, putting pressure on the center@@EndBracket@@.   Another difference is that we've played d2-d3 as opposed to d2-d4. This does allow ...d6-d5, but White is also far more flexible. In this move-order, playing à la Chigorin or à la Breyer is imprudent.   For example, the Breyer-like  9...Nb8  would be too slow as after  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  we already have our bishop on c2, and we haven't committed to h3, which is not useful at the moment. Hence, White is a tempo ahead over the actual Breyer move-order  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bpnbppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc2  .   The Chigorin knight sortie  9...Na5  is also senseless as we have our bishop on c2 already.   In the Yates variation, White also doesn't waste a tempo on h3, but the difference is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bg4  10.d5  Na5  White has to spend time retreating the bishop to c2, ending up down a tempo compared to our move-order. }
9... d5
{ This has to be the best approach, taking advantage of the fact that White went Bc2 in one go. The downside of having the bishop on c2 instead of b3 is that White has lost control over the d5 square. }
10. Nbd2 d4
{ has been played several times by Aronian and thus warrants some attention. }
11. cxd4
{ It's important to first flick in cxd4 before going Nb3. The reason is that after   11.Nb3  Bg4  12.h3  Bh5  13.cxd4  We have been following Anand, V - Aronian, L 2017, where Aronian missed  13...Bxf3!  14.Qxf3  Funnily enough, there was another game that reached this position, Annaberdiev, M - Pantzar, M 2019, and once again Black missed his chance to equalize with  14...Nxd4  15.Nxd4  Qxd4=  with no problems whatsoever. }
11... exd4 12. Nb3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5
{ We have transposed back to the Anand, V - Aronian, L game.   13...Bxf3  14.Qxf3  is better for White. A sample line runs  14...Nd7  15.Bf4  a5  16.a4  Nb4  17.Bd1  bxa4  18.Rxa4  c5  19.Nd2⩲  White is clearly for choice with the two bishops and Black's shaky queenside. }
14. Bd2
{ An important move, clearing the way for Rc1. White's bishop can also pop out to a5 in certain variations to pressure the c7 pawn.  In the game Anand played   14.Bf4  after which Black could have equalized with  14...Bd6!  15.e5  Nd5  16.Bh2  Bb4=  Breaking White's coordination. }
14... Bd6 15. Rc1
{ Simple, solid, and good enough for a comfortable advantage. White is ready to drop the bishop back to b1 when Black will feel the heat down the c-file. The d4 pawn is particularly a big target. }
