1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy Lopez is a first rate variation in the Spanish. Anand brought it into the limelight when he essayed it in the 1995 PCA Candidates against Kamsky and in the 1995 World Championship match versus Kasparov. Nowadays, this defense is played by a large subset of the world's elite such as Carlsen, So and Mamedyarov. With perfect play, Black is objectively equal everywhere but this doesn't mean White cannot pose problems in practical games. Black's main idea is to use use the time White will take to regain the pawn to gain a foothold in the center. }
6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. Nxe5
{ is a very interesting alternative to the super theoretical mainline with  8.dxe5  .  Black is objectively fine after both moves and the mainline comes with a lot more theory. This led us to recommend the text, which is far more practical and your opponent is much less likely to be booked up in this rarer line.   The advantage of playing Nxe5 is that the knight is no longer in the way of f4-f5, which oftentimes results in a strong kingside attack. The downside is that Black can create a stronger center by expanding with ...c7-c5 later on. }
8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 c6 10. Nd2
{ immediately undermining Black's knight is four times less popular than  10.Be3  but far more testing. It was not considered in the Chessbase Fritztrainer The flexible Open Spanish by GM Sipke Ernst and is likely to catch your opponents by surprise. }
10... Nxd2 11. Qxd2
{ is half as popular as  11.Bxd2  but far stronger. This rare move was one of the main reasons I decided to recommend 8. Nxe5. What's the point? The idea is that White now has the option of targeting Black's kingside with c3, Bc2 and Qd3 - an attacking scheme that would not be available had the bishop been developed to d2.   11.Bxd2  I failed to find any way of putting pressure on Black's position in this variation. The mainline of my analysis went  11...Be7!  12.Qh5  Be6  13.c3  Qd7  14.Bg5  Bg4!  15.Qh4  Bc5=  when Black has no problems. }
11... Bc5 { Black's previous move is dubious on account of } 12. Qc3
{ getting ready to scoot the queen over to g3 with a tempo on Black's bishop. White is clearly for choice with further details discussedhere. }
