1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3
{ This is the well-known Closed Spanish tabiya from which thousands upon thousands of games have been played. Many top players have ventured these waters and champions have been decided in the complexities of these structures. Mastering this structure is guaranteed to improve your chess understanding.   Black’s top three choices in this position are the Chigorin with  9...Na5  , the Breyer with  9...Nb8  and the Zaitsev with  9...Bb7  . In this chapter, we’ll examine all of Black’s other options on move 9. does have some other choices, which will be covered in this chapter. }
9... Nd7
{ The Karpov variation bears the last name of the 12th World Champion. It featured most prominently in Karpov's 1990 World-Championship match versus Kasparov. Black vacates the f6 square for the bishop to pressure White's center. }
10. d4 Bf6
{ is the main point behind ...Nd7 and Karpov's preference. By immediately pressuring the d4 pawn, Black prevents White's Nbd2-f1 knight tour. }
11. a4 Bb7 12. d5
{ A timely pawn push. White locks up the position before Black gets a chance to open it. }
12... Ne7 13. Bc2
{ 13.axb5  is the most popular move, but I don't think it's necessary to immediately define the queenside structure. Instead, we can slowly gain space on this side of the board. }
13... Qb8 14. c4
{ Technically a novelty, although not overly special. There was nothing wrong with b3 followed by c4, but the text is more direct and gives Black more chances to go wrong. }
14... bxc4
{ 14...c6  would be met with  15.b3⩲  when White enjoys the nice space advantage. }
15. Na3
{ followed by Nc4 gives White a solid advantage. Black's pieces are very passive.   15...c6  trying to open up the game is well met by  16.dxc6  Bxc6  17.Nxc4  Black now needs to push ahead with  17...d5  or else the d6 pawn will be critically weak.  18.exd5  Bxd5  19.Ng5↑  is a nice shot that guarantees White an advantage. The h7 pawn is under fire and Black's kingside can quickly come under attack. }
