[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Zaitsev"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Bb7
{ The @@StartBracket@@Flohr@@EndBracket@@-Zaitsev variation is named after Igor Zaitsev, who was Anatoly Karpov's trainer for many years. The 12th World Champion was a great specialist of this defense and can be credited to making the Zaitsev one of the most important variations in the Closed Spanish complex. Theory has developed in leaps and bounds since the variation was first discovered in the 1970s with today's analysis stretching well into the middlegame. As such, precise knowledge of the variations is required to fight for an opening advantage. Exciting, complex, and dynamic lines await you! Let's get started! }
10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8
{ This is the main tabiya in the Zaitsev. Black's main ideas are to play ...g6 or ...h6 and/or ... Nb8-d7. }
12. a3
{ is the modern mainline and my suggestion.   It's both far calmer and objectively stronger than the alternatives  12.a4  ,  12.d5  and  12.Bc2  .  With the text, White covers the b4 square and creates a square for the bishop on a2. This rules out many of Black's chances for counterplay, usually connected with ...exd4, ...Nb4, and a quick ...c5 to undermine White's center. }
12... h6
{ Stopping any Ng5 business is by far Black's most popular and logical move. }
13. Bc2
{ With Ng5 ruled out, the bishop isn't doing much on the a2-g8 diagonal. As such, it makes sense to drop it back to c2 in order to reinforce the e4 pawn. }
13... Nb8 { A Breyer-like retreat to increase the pressure on the e4 pawn. }
14. b3
{ is a slower alternative to the mainline with 14. b4. After extensive analysis, I found the text to be easier to play and yield White a solid advantage. The idea is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop while retaining maximum flexibility on the queenside.   For further analysis, please refer to themain theoretical section of the course. }
