[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ Here comes the Marshall, arguably one of Black's best defenses against 1. e4!   Rather than head for a solid line in the closed variations, Black meets  8.c3  with  8...d5  sacrificing a pawn in return for fantastic piece activity, drastically changing the character of the game. Thousands of games have been played in these lines with reams of theory and no White advantage in sight.   Instead of trying to navigate this labyrinth of variations, I've chosen to recommend the practical  8.a4  Anti-Marshall variation. }
8. a4
{ is an interesting way of preventing the Marshall Gambit. The idea is to clarify the queenside pawn structure at an early stage and gain control over the c4 square, which can become a possible outpost for one of White's knights. }
8... Bb7 9. d3 d6 10. Bd2
{ 10.Nbd2  is White's most popular option, which has been played in thousands of games. I was unable to find any trace of a White advantage in those lines and thus opted to recommend this rarer move, which asks some interesting practical questions and is likely to surprise your opponents. The point of 10. Bd2 is to prevent ...Na5. }
10... Qd7
{ is a logical move, developing the last remaining piece and waiting for White to play Nc3 when ... Na5 will then be possible. The drawback is that the typical Marshall maneuver ...Bc8-e6 is no longer available. }
11. Nc3 Na5
{ Worse is  11...Nd4?!  12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Ne2  c5  14.Ng3⩲  There's no doubt White is better here. Black's d4 pawn can be undermined with c2-c3 while .. .d6-d5 is well met by e4-e5. }
12. Ba2 b4 13. Ne2
{ While Black is objectively fine, White's position is easier to play with ideas of Ng3 and Nh4-f5. The lopsided 6/8 score in practice is good evidence. For more details, please refer to themain theoretical section of the course. }
