1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4
{ The so-called Bird's defense, named after the late 19th-century player Henry Bird. He did not have much success with it, only scoring +9 =3 −13. This variation is considered to be subpar and is rarely played in serious games. Notably, Magnus Carlsen played it with black in the 2014 Chess Olympiad against Ivan Šarić and lost.  While arguably not terrible, the Bird's defense certainly does not come anywhere close to equalizing. Moving an already developed piece a second time is seldom a good idea with this being no exception. }
4. Nxd4 exd4 5. O-O
{ Taking a snapshot of the current position, White is significantly ahead in development and has the superior pawn structure.   We're now going to cover Black's three main moves, namely  5...g6  ,  5...c6  and  5...Bc5  . }
