4. Nxd4 exd4 5. O-O g6
{ is third most common and not particularly good. Developing the bishop to g7 is way too slow. }
6. d3
{ White has many good options but the text is the simplest route towards a sizeable advantage. }
6... Bg7 7. f4
{ There's no reason not to gain space and increase our central control. Black now has to constantly watch out for f4-f5. }
7... a5 8. f5 { Here comes Harry! } 8... gxf5 9. Bc4
{ A very strong move, aiming at the f7 pawn. There's no need to take back on f5 right away. Black now has to be wary of Bxf7 and Qh5 tactics. }
9... c6 { Threatening both ... d5 and ...b5 is met by a crushing tactic. } 10.
Bxf7+ { Boom goes the dynamite! Black's king is forced out into the open. }
10... Kxf7 11. Qh5+ Ke7
{ 11...Kf8  doesn't help. Simply  12.Rxf5+  Nf6  13.Bh6+-  wins. } 12. Bg5+ Bf6
13. e5
{ White is about to recoup the piece with an ongoing attack. Black is busted. }
