1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4
{ This is called Bird's defense, named after the late 19th-century player Henry Bird. He did not have much success with it, only scoring +9 =3 −13. This variation is considered to be subpar and is rarely played in serious games. Notably, Magnus Carlsen played it with black in the 2014 Chess Olympiad against Ivan Šarić and lost. }
4. Nxd4 exd4 5. O-O Bc5 6. Bc4
{ White is threatening Bxf7 followed by Qh5+.   6.d3  is White's most popular move but it gives Black the option of playing  6...c6  7.Bc4  and now  7...d5!  gives Black a solid position.   6.Bc4  The point of the text is that  6...c6  is ruled out due to  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Qh5+  recouping the c5 bishop with a huge advantage. }
6... d6
{ is Black's most common move, more than 10 times as popular as the alternatives. }
7. d3 Ne7
{ 7...Nf6?!  allows White to simply build up a strong position with  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  g5  10.Bg3⩲  All Black achieved was significantly weakening his position. He now needs to watch out for the e4-e5 break.   7...c6  is well met by  8.a3  d5  9.Ba2  Nf6  10.Bg5±  likely followed by Nbd2 and exd5, which will leave Black with doubled d-pawns. }
8. Qh5
{ The pressure on the f7 pawn forces Black to castle kingside. From h5, the queen also prevents the ...d5 break, thus condemning Black to passivity. }
8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ is the most active post for the bishop. There's no way Black is getting in ...d5 now. }
9... Be6 10. Qh4
{ is stronger than the immediate Bxe6. It's better to first force ...Re8 and only then play Bxe6. }
10... Re8
{ Only now that ...Re8 has been played should White chop on e6 as Black no longer has control over the f-file: }
11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. f4
