1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ The Classical defense is quite possibly the oldest line in the Ruy Lopez. It was occasionally played by Boris Spassky and Boris Gulko. Black's main idea is to play ...Nd4 to exchange a pair of knights. }
4. c3
{ Not only stops ...Nd4 but also prepares to gain space in the center with d2-d4. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ With Black's knight on f6 as opposed to e7, we can go for   5.d4  right away instead of 5. O-O. The difference is that  5...exd4  can now be met by  6.e5!  with a tempo on the knight on f6. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ A strong intermezzo, gaining space and dislodging the knight! } 6... Nd5
{ The knight may look active on d5 but it is merely a liability. } 7. O-O
{ There's no stopping cxd4 now. The d4 pawn is pinned given the d5 knight is unprotected. }
7... Be7 8. cxd4 d6 9. exd6 cxd6
{ 9...Qxd6  is not a good square for the queen as it's exposed to Nc3-e4.  10.Nc3  O-O  11.Re1  Be6  12.Ne4± }
10. Qb3 { Once again, Black's knight is under attack. } 10... a6
{ 10...Nc7  is strongly met by  11.d5!  Nxb5  12.Qxb5  a6  13.Qe2± } 11. Qxd5
axb5 12. Qxb5
{ Black has less space and his structure is compromised. White can look to complete development with Rd1, Be3/f4, and Nbd2-c4. }
