1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ The Classical defense is quite possibly the oldest line in the Ruy Lopez. It was occasionally played by Boris Spassky and Boris Gulko. Black's main idea is to play ...Nd4 to exchange a pair of knights. }
4. c3
{ Not only stops ...Nd4 but also prepares to gain space in the center with d2-d4. }
4... Nf6 5. d4
{ With Black's knight on f6 as opposed to e7, we can go for   5.d4  right away instead of 5. O-O. The difference is that  5...exd4  can now be met by  6.e5!  with a tempo on the knight on f6. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ A strong intermezzo, gaining space and dislodging the knight! } 6... Ne4 7.
O-O
{ White is now threatening to take full control over the center with cxd4. }
7... dxc3 8. Qd5 { The double-attack forces Black to take on f2. } 8... Bxf2+
9. Rxf2 Nxf2 10. Nxc3
{ is a strong novelty. Rather than capture the knight on f2, as played in all the previous games to reach this position, we bring our pieces into the game. We have one clear target: Black's king on e8. }
10... Ng4 11. Qe4 O-O
{ is practically forced. Black must give back the knight in order to get his king to safety.   11...d5?!  is no good. After  12.exd6+  Kf8  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.h3  Nf6  15.Qxc6  Bd7  16.Qxc7±  White's pieces are just far too active. }
12. Qxg4 d6 13. Qg3 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Be3
{ Black has a rook and three pawns for the two bishops. However, White is firmly in the driver's seat due to the huge advantage in activity.   A sample continuation is  15...c6  16.Bc4  Bf5  17.Qxe5  Re8  18.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  19.Qxf5+  Kg8  20.Rd1  Qe7  21.Bc5±  The two minor pieces are far superior to Black's rook. }
