1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ This variation is typically called the Smyslov variation. Some authors have referred to 3...g6 as the Fianchetto or Pillsbury defense. This is because there's more than 1 variation in the Ruy Lopez complex named after the 7th World-Champion Vasily Smyslov. This line was popular in the 1980s but is rarely seen nowadays in Classical time controls given that White can count on a sizeable advantage. }
4. c3
{ Preparing to take over the center with d4-d4 is the simplest route towards an edge.   4.d4  exd4  5.c3  is another interesting line I considered recommending. }
4... Nge7
{ Black delays the development of the f8 bishop in order to engineer the ...d7-d5 break. }
5. d4
{ After playing 4. c3, expanding in the center with d2-d4 is a no brainer. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 a6 7. Ba4
{ This position has arisen in practice via different move orders such as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.c3  Nge7  6.d4  exd4  7.cxd4  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  5.c3  g6  6.d4  exd4  7.cxd4 }
7... b5 8. Bc2 d5 9. e5
{ is the correct reaction, bypassing Black's d-pawn and gaining a lot of space. }
9... Bg7 10. Nbd2
{ White develops naturally. O-O followed by Re1 are coming next. } 10... O-O
{ 10...f6  11.O-O  fxe5  12.dxe5  O-O  13.Re1  transposes to the text. } 11.
O-O f6 12. Re1 fxe5 13. dxe5
{ The strong e5 pawn and the resulting space advantage give White the upper hand.   A sample continuation is  13...Qe8  14.h3  Qf7  15.Qe2  intending Nb3-d4 gave White a clearly better out of the opening inFirat,B @@StartBracket@@2405@@EndBracket@@-Delchev,A @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ Plovdiv 2012. }
*

