1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ This variation is typically called the Smyslov variation. Some authors have referred to 3...g6 as the Fianchetto or Pillsbury defense. This is because there's more than 1 variation in the Ruy Lopez complex named after the 7th World-Champion Vasily Smyslov. This line was popular in the 1980s but is rarely seen nowadays in Classical time controls given that White can count on a sizeable advantage. }
4. c3
{ Preparing to take over the center with d4-d4 is the simplest route towards an edge.   4.d4  exd4  5.c3  is another interesting line I considered recommending. }
4... Bg7 5. d4 exd4
{ 5...Nge7  allows  6.d5±  gaining a lot of space and pushing back Black's knight. }
6. cxd4 a6
{ 6...Nge7  once again allows White to push ahead with  7.d5  Following  7...a6  8.Be2  Ne5  9.Nxe5  Bxe5  10.O-O±  followed by f2-f4 gives White a clear edge thanks to the big space advantage. }
7. Ba4 b5
{ Mamedyarov has played this line with Black several times. Black is, however, far from equal given that White has full control over the center. }
8. Bb3 Nge7 9. a4
{ A very rare and interesting move, played by two strong Indian GMs Sasikiran and Vishnu as well as Spanish superstar David Antón. White immediately undermines Black's overextended structure. }
9... Na5 10. O-O
{ White continues development and invites Black to capture the b3 bishop, which will only develop the d1 queen. This natural move was not considered in the Chessable course The Smyslov Ruy Lopez 3...g6 by IM Irina Bulmaga. }
10... Nxb3 11. Qxb3 bxa4 12. Qxa4 O-O 13. h3
{ White has full control over the center and a sizeable advantage. Up next are Nc3 and Be3 to complete development. }
