[White "3...f5 | Schliemann"]
[Black "3...f5 4...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann Defense, also known as the Jaenisch Gambit, is one of the sharpest variations in the Ruy Lopez. Black immediately challenges the e4 pawn, seeking to play ...fxe4 which would open the f-file and leave him with a central pawn majority. The second player often sacrifices a pawn @@StartBracket@@or even two@@EndBracket@@ to try and take over the initiative.   Despite not having the best reputation, this gambit scores reasonably well at the club level and is sometimes even played at the very top level as a surprise weapon. Radjabov and Aronian played several times against super-GM opposition in the 2000s.   Recently, it was recommended in the Chessable course The Thrilling Jaenisch Gambit by GM Sethuraman, who came up with a lot of very interesting and novel ideas. }
4. d3
{ Reinforcing the e4 pawn with 4. d3 is our recommendation and currently considered to be the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit.   4.exf5?!  runs into  4...e4  This is the reason we start with 4. d3, when we're actually threatening to take on f5 as Black can no longer play ...e4. }
4... Nf6 { is both rare and bad on account of } 5. exf5
{ There's no reason not to take this free pawn! } 5... Nd4
{ is Black's main point.  Worse is   5...Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.Bxc6  dxc6  8.Nxe5  Bxf5  9.Re1Ν  leaves White with an extra pawn and a clear advantage.   5...Ne7  is very passive. After  6.O-O  c6  7.Bc4  d6  8.Bg5  Nxf5  9.Re1±  White is clearly better with d4 coming next. }
6. Ba4 c6
{ Black is trying to create a big center with ...d5. The problem is he's far too behind in development. After }
7. O-O d5 8. Re1 { Black is already in trouble. Best is } 8... Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3
Bd6
{ 9...Be7!?  runs into  10.c4!  e4  11.Qh3±  followed by Nc3. Black's center is about to crumble. }
10. c4
{ gives White a big advantage. Nc3 and Bb3 are coming next when Black's center will soon collapse. }
*

