1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann Defense, also known as the Jaenisch Gambit, is one of the sharpest variations in the Ruy Lopez. Black immediately challenges the e4 pawn, seeking to play ...fxe4 which would open the f-file and leave him with a central pawn majority. He often sacrifices a pawn @@StartBracket@@or even two@@EndBracket@@ to try and take over the initiative. Despite not having the best reputation, this gambit scores reasonably well at the club level and is sometimes even played at the very top level as a surprise weapon. Radjabov and Aronian played several times against super-GM opposition in the 2000s. Recently, it was recommended in the Chessable course The Thrilling Jaenisch Gambit by GM Sethuraman, who came up with a lot of very interesting and novel ideas. }
4. d3
{ Reinforcing the e4 pawn with 4. d3 is our recommendation and currently considered to be the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit.   4.exf5?!  runs into  4...e4  This is the reason we start with 4. d3, when we're actually threatening to take on f5 as Black can no longer play ...e4. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O
{ is White's best move, completing development of the kingside.  The natural   6.Nc3  allows  6...Bb4  when Black can spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3 and is ready to castle short on the next turn with good play along the f-file. }
6... d6
{ is not as common as 6...Bc5 but with over 1000 OTB games it certainly deserves serious attention.   6...Nxe4?  is a blunder. The e4 pawn is untouchable as  7.Re1  d5  8.Nxe5  Qf6  9.Rxe4  dxe4  10.Qd5+-  is winning. }
7. Bc4
{ is an important move, pioneered by Caruana in high-profile games vs Aronian in 2018 and Carlsen in 2019. Now that Black has reinforced the e5 pawn with ...d6, the bishop is no longer doing much on b5 and stands much better on the a2-g8 diagonal, threatening Ng5 and making it hard for Black to castle short.   7.Nc3  is most common but after  7...Be7  8.Bc4  Na5  Black successfully pushes our bishop off the a2-g8 diagonal, allowing him to castle short. }
7... Bg4 { is the most popular and sensible move, stopping Ng5. } 8. h3 Bh5
{ 8...Bxf3?!  gives away the bishop pair and only helps White develop with  9.Qxf3±  when Black's position is riddled with light-squared weaknesses. }
9. Nc3 Qd7 10. Nd5
{ is a natural move that contains a hidden threat of Nxe5 followed by Nxf6 and Qxh5, winning a pawn.   10.Be3  was successfully played by Caruana against Carlsen but concrete analysis shows Black is fine after  10...Be7  11.a4  h6=   10.Be2  is another good option, threatening Nxe5.  10...Bg6  11.Nh4  Bf7  12.Be3  Be7  13.Nf5⩲  with a better game. }
10... O-O-O
{ 10...Be7?  runs into the aforementioned  11.Nxe5!  Nxe5  12.Nxf6+  Bxf6  13.Qxh5+±  which nets White a pawn.   Similarly  10...Nxe4?!  11.Nxe5!  Bxd1  12.Nxd7  Kxd7  13.Rxd1±  is also much better for White thanks to the bishop pair. }
11. Qd3 Kb8 12. a4
{ starts active operations on the queenside. The text also gives White the possibility of lifting the rook along the third rank with Ra3-b3.   The kings are castled on opposite wings so an attack against the opposing king is the natural plan. Black's problem is that he can hardly reach White's king on g1, giving the first player the better chances.   Best play by both sides continues  12...Bg6  pinning the e4-pawn such that after ...Nxd5 White is forced to recapture with a piece.  13.Re1  Nxd5  14.Qxd5  Be7  15.Ra3  White's about to start a deadly attack and Black has to play like an engine to not get destroyed. First, Black must find  Nb4!  and meet  16.Qd2  with  Rhf8!  noting that  17.Qxb4  allows  d5  Good luck finding that over the board! A forced sequence now follows  18.Qc3  Bxa3  19.Bb5  c6  20.Nxe5  Qd6  21.bxa3  cxb5  22.Nxg6  Qxg6  23.axb5  Qb6!   23...dxe4  24.Be3  gave White a healthy, risk-free advantage in the correspondence game T.Mosconi-G. Ziese corr. 2020.  24.Qg3+  Ka8  25.exd5  is more challenging that 25. e5, which led to a draw in the correspondence game ½-½ Faridani-Hrubcík email 2019.  Qxb5  26.d6  Qc6  27.Bf4  In the book A Disreputable Opening Repertoire for Black, Jonathan Tait recommends  g5!  28.Be5!  White should hold onto the strong d6 passer.   28.Qxg5??  blunders  28...Rg8  when White gets mated on g2.   Taking with the bishop  28.Bxg5?!  is also no good as the d6 pawn drops to  28...Rxd6  28...Qxc2  29.Qe3  Qc6  Now Tait only considered the immediate 30. Rc1, failing to mention the important finesse  30.Qd2!  ⩲  first taking control over the d5 square before playing Rc1 so as not to allow ...Qd5. Getting here already required Black to play several only moves and the resulting position is no fun! White is effectively playing for two results and can look to slowly improve his position with moves like Rc1, Qd4, Kh2 and f2-f3. }
