4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O
{ is White's best move, completing development of the kingside.  The natural   6.Nc3  allows  6...Bb4  when Black can spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3 and is ready to castle short on the next turn with good play along the f-file. }
6... Bc5 { is Black's most common and active option. } 7. Bxc6
{ is the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit. White gives up the bishop pair to win the e5 pawn. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 d6
{ This is Black's main move, simply kicking the knight away from its active post. }
10. Nd3
{ is White's most popular move and arguably the most challenging option as detailed in the followinginformational line. }
10... Bd4
{ Worse is  10...Bb6  11.Bf4  Ba6  12.Re1±  White is a pawn up and can go after Black's bishop with Na4 next. }
11. Ne2
{ is an important move as Black was threatening to spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3. }
11... Bb6 12. Bg5 { is White's best way of covering the e4 pawn. } 12... Qe8
13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. Ng3
{ Consolidates the extra pawn. Black now has to be very accurate to get compensation for the pawn deficit. }
14... Ba6
{ is the most popular 14th move but not a very good one. White can get a big advantage with }
15. a4 { intending to go after Black's bishop with Qd2 and a5. } 15... Qf7 16.
Kh1 { The point is that } 16... Bxf2 { runs into 17. Nh5. } 17. Nh5 Rh6 18.
Nxg7 Qxg7 19. Rxf2
{ when White is a pawn up and Black's king is also exposed. The next logical set of moves are Qd2 and Re1 when White can consider breaking with e5. }
