1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann Defense, also known as the Jaenisch Gambit, is one of the sharpest variations in the Ruy Lopez. Black immediately challenges the e4 pawn, seeking to play ...fxe4 which would open the f-file and leave him with a central pawn majority. He often sacrifices a pawn @@StartBracket@@or even two@@EndBracket@@ to try and take over the initiative. Despite not having the best reputation, this gambit scores reasonably well at the club level and is sometimes even played at the very top level as a surprise weapon. Radjabov and Aronian played several times against super-GM opposition in the 2000s. Recently, it was recommended in the Chessable course The Thrilling Jaenisch Gambit by GM Sethuraman, who came up with a lot of very interesting and novel ideas. }
4. d3
{ Reinforcing the e4 pawn with 4. d3 is our recommendation and currently considered to be the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit.   4.exf5?!  runs into  4...e4  This is the reason we start with 4. d3, when we're actually threatening to take on f5 as Black can no longer play ...e4. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O
{ is White's best move, completing development of the kingside.  The natural   6.Nc3  allows  6...Bb4  when Black can spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3 and is ready to castle short on the next turn with good play along the f-file. }
6... Bc5 { is Black's most common and active option. } 7. Bxc6
{ is the critical test of the Jaenisch Gambit. White gives up the bishop pair to win the e5 pawn. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 d6
{ This is Black's main move, simply kicking the knight away from its active post. }
10. Nd3
{ is White's most popular move and arguably the most challenging option as detailed in the followinginformational line. }
10... Bd4
{ Worse is  10...Bb6  11.Bf4  Ba6  12.Re1±  White is a pawn up and can go after Black's bishop with Na4 next. }
11. Ne2
{ is an important move as Black was threatening to spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3. }
11... Bb6 12. Bg5 { is White's best way of covering the e4 pawn. } 12... Qe8
13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. Ng3
{ Consolidates the extra pawn. Black now has to be very accurate to get compensation for the pawn deficit. }
14... d5
{ is Black's only way of obtaining compensation for the pawn and an OTB novelty, which was recently recommended by GM Sethuraman. }
15. Qh5 Ba6 { is a better option. A forced sequence now follows } 16. exd5 Qxh5
17. Nxh5 Rf5 18. Ng3 Bxd3 { is a key intermezzo. } 19. cxd3 Rxd5 20. Rfd1
{ is very logical, protecting the d3 pawn. This pawn will drop but in doing so Black will have to exchange off a pair of rooks, which significantly reduces his chances for counterplay.   20.Rfc1  was the only move considered by GM Sethuraman in the Chessable course The Thrilling Jaenisch Gambit but it's inferior to the text as after  20...Rxd3  Black restores material equality and threatens ...Rd2. White should play  21.Rc2  but after  21...Rf8  it's not easy to make progress given Black is quite active. }
20... Rad8
{ 20...Bd4  fails to achieve sufficient counterplay after  21.Rd2  Rb8  22.Rb1  keeping everything together. White can now improve his pieces with Ne4 and Rc2.  22...a5  23.Ne4  Rdb5  24.Rc2  Rxb2  25.Rbxb2  Rxb2  26.Rxb2  Bxb2  27.f4±  White has excellent chances to win in this endgame. He can post the knight on c4 and then set his kingside pawn majority in motion. }
21. Kf1 { Ke2 is coming so Black is forced to play } 21... Rxd3 22. Rxd3 Rxd3
23. Ke2 Rd5 24. Ne4
{ We've reached an endgame where White is not only slightly better but is also the only one that can win. White has a kingside pawn majority while Black's queenside majority is crippled. While Black can hold with precise play, it's certainly no fun to defend this endgame OTB. This is the best Black can achieve in the Schliemann and he needs to know a lot to reach this position, which can only be characterized as unpleasant for the second player. }
