1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ is known as the Cozio defense, arguably the most established alternative to 3...a6 and a serious move that was recommended by GM Erwin l'Ami on Chessable.   With  3...Nge7  Black reinforces the knight so as to be able to meet  4.Bxc6  with  4...Nxc6  and thus avoid having to double the queenside pawns. This comes at the cost of the g8 knight being less active on e7 than f6 and restricting the f8 bishop, which will typically be fianchettoed after ... g6. }
4. d4
{ After extensive analysis, I concluded that immediately striking in the center with 4. d4 is White's best shot at an opening advantage.   4.Nc3  also gives White good practical chances of getting an edge and is given as analternative recommendation.   4.c3  isn't nearly as good here because of  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  dxe4=  Black is doing very well with ...Qd5 coming next.   Finally, the delayed Cozio defense after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  4.Ba4  Nge7  is nowhere as good for Black and gives the first player enough time to prepare a coordinated expansion in the center after  5.c3  . This variation is analyzed in thenext chapter. }
*

