[Black "3...Nge7 4. d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ is known as the Cozio defense, the most established alternative to 3...a6 and a serious move that was recommended by GM Erwin l'Ami on Chessable.   With  3...Nge7  Black reinforces the knight so as to be able to meet  4.Bxc6  with  4...Nxc6  and thus avoid having to double the queenside pawns. This comes at the cost of the g8 knight being less active on e7 than f6 and restricting the f8 bishop, which will typically be fianchettoed after ... g6. }
4. d4
{ After extensive analysis, I concluded that immediately striking in the center with 4. d4 is objectively White's best shot at an opening advantage.   4.Nc3  is also interesting and given as analternative recommendation.   4.c3  isn't nearly as good here because of  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  dxe4=  Black is doing very well with ...Qd5 coming next. }
4... exd4
{ 4...Nxd4  5.Nxd4  exd4  6.Qxd4  c6  7.Bc4  d5  8.Bb3  transposes to the4.d4 #3 variation. }
5. Nxd4 Ng6
{ Black brings out the knight to g6, opening up the dark-squared bishop which would love to come to ... c5. However, we're simply not going to allow it! }
6. Be3 Bc5
{ 6...Bb4+  makes little sense with White's knight still on b1. After  7.c3  Ba5  8.Na3±  Black only wasted valuable tempi and his dark-squared bishop will soon be exchanged off after Nc4. }
7. Nc3 O-O
{ This careless move loses instantly but illustrates why Black cannot afford to get the bishop out to c5.   7...Nf4  8.Qg4  would force Black's knight right back. }
8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc5
{ White grabs the bishop and hits the rook on f8, ensuring the first player will end up with at least an extra exchange. }
