1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ is known as the Cozio defense, the most established alternative to 3...a6 and a serious move that was recommended by GM Erwin l'Ami on Chessable.   With  3...Nge7  Black reinforces the knight so as to be able to meet  4.Bxc6  with  4...Nxc6  and thus avoid having to double the queenside pawns. This comes at the cost of the g8 knight being less active on e7 than f6 and restricting the f8 bishop, which will typically be fianchettoed after ... g6. }
4. d4
{ After extensive analysis, I concluded that immediately striking in the center with 4. d4 is objectively White's best shot at an opening advantage.   4.Nc3  is also interesting and given as analternative recommendation.   4.c3  isn't nearly as good here because of  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  dxe4=  Black is doing very well with ...Qd5 coming next. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 c6
{ Black wants to get d5 in but won't be doing so under good conditions. } 7.
Bc4 d5 8. Bb3
{ While rarely played, this retreating move is far stronger than taking on d5. }
8... Be6
{ 8...Qb6  trying to get out of the pin has yet to be played OTB. White maintains a comfortable advantage after  9.Qd1  noting that altough  9...dxe4  wins a pawn, it'll soon be recaptured following  10.Nc3  Ng6  11.O-O  ⩲  White will soon play Nxe4 with a healthy advantage. In particular, White's light-squared bishop on b3 is far more active than Black's counterpart on c8. }
9. Nc3 Qb6 10. Be3
{ White has all the minor pieces out and good pressure on the d5 pawn. Conversely, Black's minor pieces are passive and have no good prospects.   A sample line goes  10...Qxd4  11.Bxd4  b6  Black is forced to compromise the queenside structure in order to get castled.  12.O-O-O  O-O-O  13.Be3  g6  14.exd5  Nxd5  15.Nxd5  cxd5  16.Rd2±  with strong pressure on the d5 pawn, better minor pieces and a superior pawn structure. What more could White want? }
