1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ is known as the Cozio defense, the most established alternative to 3...a6 and a serious move that was recommended by GM Erwin l'Ami on Chessable.   With  3...Nge7  Black reinforces the knight so as to be able to meet  4.Bxc6  with  4...Nxc6  and thus avoid having to double the queenside pawns. This comes at the cost of the g8 knight being less active on e7 than f6 and restricting the f8 bishop, which will typically be fianchettoed after ...g6. }
4. d4
{ After extensive analysis, I concluded that immediately striking in the center with 4. d4 is objectively White's best shot at an opening advantage.   4.Nc3  is also interesting and given as analternative recommendation.   4.c3  isn't nearly as good here because of  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  dxe4=  Black is doing very well with ...Qd5 coming next. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3
{ The queen is best placed on e3. While this may look counterintuitive at first sight @@StartBracket@@since we temporarily block in the c1 bishop@@EndBracket@@ it's more important to prevent ...Bc5. This ensures Black will be forced to develop the dark-squared bishop to a passive square on e7. }
7... Be7 8. Nc3 { White continues developing naturally. O-O is up next. } 8...
O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ 9...d6?!  is inaccurate given it allows White to jump straight in with  10.Nd5  and grab the bishop pair. The two bishops combined with the extra space add up to a sizeable, long-lasting edge. }
10. Rd1
{ An interesting novelty back in 2022, first unleashed by the two-time Swedish champion Eric Erik Blomqvist versus the Indian superstar Sarin Nihal. Erwin l'Ami did not consider this option in the Chessable course Erwin's Opening Lab: The Cozio Defense. }
10... d6
{ 10...Ne5  is well met by  11.a4  preventing Black from easily expanding on the queenside.  11...c6  12.Be2  d6  13.Qd4⩲  followed by Bf4 is at least slightly better for White. The extra space and superior pawn structure are very pleasant to play with. }
11. Nd5 Bd7
{ 11...Bh4  hoping to provoke g2-g3 can simply be ignored. The prophylactic  12.a4  gives White a comfortable advantage after  12...a6  13.Bf1  Ne7  14.Nc3  White keeps all the minor pieces on the board, which makes sense given the first player's space advantage. It's unclear what Black's knight on e7 and bishop on h4 are doing. }
12. Bf1 Ne5 { 12...Bf8  13.c4⩲  White has a pleasant space advantage. } 13.
Nxe7+
{ Now that Black has moved the knight to e5, it's a good moment to take on e7. This is stronger than 13. a4, played in the game½-½ @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Blomqvist,E @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@-Nihal,S  @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ Fagernes 2022. }
13... Qxe7 14. f3
{ White has more space and the two bishops. While they may currently look unimpressive, the dark-squared bishop is poised to become a force to be reckoned with after b3 and Bb2. }
