Qxg5 hxg5 20. h6
{ Threatens to win pretty much on the spot with hxg7 followed by f6+. } 20...
d6 { Hitting both e5 and f5 is Black's best option. } 21. hxg7 Kxg7 22. f6+
{ Forces Black's king out into the open. } 22... Kg6 23. Bh5+ Kf5 24. exd6 c5
{ is Black's only way of keeping the balance. His plan is to play ... Ke5xd6, the d6 square being a safe haven for the king. }
25. Kd2 Ke5 { 25...Kxf6  26.Rae1±  followed by Rhf1 is problematic for Black. }
26. Rhe1+
{ is the correct rook to bring to the e-file.  And not   26.Rae1+  which runs into  26...Kxd6  27.Re7  Rh8!  placing White under a very awkward pin along the h-file. }
26... Kxd6 27. Re7 Be6 28. Re1
{ Erwin L'Ami only mentioned 28. Rxb7 but the text is slightly more testing. While I agree with him that Black is objectively fine, I'd take White any day of the week. We have a monster rook on e7, the b7 and a4 pawns are weak and we can also undermine Black's d4 pawn with c3 and Re4. }
