4. Nc3
{ This natural move gives White good practical chances of getting an opening advantage. The plan is to expand in the center with d2-d4 on the next turn.   4.c3  isn't nearly as good here because of  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  dxe4=  Black is doing very well with ...Qd5 coming next. }
4... g6
{ After examining the alternatives, it's now time to turn our attention to Black's main move. }
5. d4 { As usual, we take over the center at the earliest opportunity. } 5...
exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Nxc6
{ is a key novelty, leading to a White advantage in every single line. } 8...
Nxc6 9. Qd2 d6 10. h4
{ Starts immediate operations on the kingside. Our king will gladly head to the queenside, resulting in an opposite sides castling position where we'll be the only ones attacking. }
10... h5
{ 10...Be6  does nothing to stop  11.h5  a6  12.Be2  b5  13.Bg5!  Qd7  14.O-O-O  b4  15.Nd5±  gives White a big advantage. }
11. O-O-O
{ White has the extremely straightforward plan of exchanging the dark-squared bishops, which will critically weaken the dark-squared around Black's king. A pawn assault with f3 and g4 will then follow. }
11... Be6 12. Bh6 Qf6 13. Bxg7 Qxg7 14. Be2
{ The bishop comes back to support the g4 pawn break. } 14... Ne5 15. f3
{ Next up is Rg1 when there'll be no stopping g4. Black's king is surely sweating right now. }
