[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Steinitz Defense Deferred, also known as the Modern Steinitz, is one of the most interesting sidelines in the Ruy Lopez complex. By starting with 4...d6 and delaying the development of the g8 knight, Black retains a great deal of flexibility and the option of playing ...f7-f5 and even ....g7-g5 in many cases.   The Modern Steinitz complex contains everything from solid and positional lines to highly dynamic variations, full of sacrifices and vicious attacks. Objectively, Black is doing fairly well everywhere. White needs to be well prepared and employ cunning move orders to put the second player under pressure. Worry not, we've done all the work for you! }
5. O-O
{ is the first important crossroad.   5.c3  allows the Siesta variation with  5...f5  which leads to very sharp and messy positions. White does best in avoiding this swamp.   Coversely  5.O-O  rules out  5...f5  due to  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4!  A powerful central strike. With our king already on g1 and Black's king still on e8, the second player is ill-equipped to deal with the opening of the e-file.   Finally  5.d4?!  is to be avoided due to  5...b5!  6.Bb3  Nxd4  when recapturing twice on d4 loses a piece, i.e.  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4?  c5−+  followed by ...c4 wins the bishop. }
5... g5 { is premature on account of 6. d4. } 6. d4
{ We all know the best response to a flank attack is a counterattack in the center. This position is no exception. }
6... g4 7. Bxc6+ { is an important intermezzo, spoiling Black's structure. }
7... bxc6 8. Ne1
{ Black won't be able to maintain the pawn on e5. White's extra space, superior central control, and lead in development all add up to a significant advantage.   The following game is a good illustration of White's superiority:  8...exd4  9.Qxd4  Qf6  10.Qa4  Ne7  11.Qa5  Ra7  12.Nd3  Bg7  13.Nc3  c5  14.e5!  A powerful central strike, after which Black's position collapses.  14...Qf5  15.Nb5  Nc6  16.Nxc7+  Kf8  17.Qb6  Qd7  18.exd6  c4  19.Nb4  Qxd6  20.Ncd5  Rd7  21.Be3  Kg8  22.Qxc6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Sychev,K @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@-Moiseenko, V @@StartBracket@@2554@@EndBracket@@ Yerevan 2018 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...a6 4...d6 | Deferred Steinitz "]
[Black "5...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bg4
{ This early bishop sortie is objectively quite dubious but can be tricky to face if you've never encountered it before, especially in short time controls. Black's main idea is that 6. h3 to try and break the pin can be met with 6...h5. }
6. h3 h5
{ Black's main idea is that  7.hxg4?  opens up the h-file with disastrous consequences. For example  7...hxg4  8.Ne1??  Qh4−+  and White is suddenly getting checkmated.   6...Bh5  is way too cooperative. 18-year old Fischer gained a huge advantage against Geller in their famous 1961 encounter at the International Jubilee Grandmaster Tournament in Bled following  7.c3  Qf6  8.g4!  Bg6  9.d4  after which Black's center quickly collapsed.  9...Bxe4  10.Nbd2  Bg6  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Nxe5!  The knight is immune to capture due to Re1. Black didn't last long:  13...Bd6  14.Nxg6  Qxg6  15.Re1+  Kf8  16.Nc4  h5  17.Nxd6  cxd6  18.Bf4  d5  19.Qb3  hxg4  20.Qb7  gxh3+  21.Bg3  Rd8  22.Qb4+  1-0 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Fischer,R-Geller,E Bled 1961 }
7. Bxc6+
{ Playing ...h5 made the g4 bishop immune to capture. However, in doing so, Black neglected the center of the board which we're about to exploit with d2-d4. To do so, we first eliminate the c6 knight. }
7... bxc6 8. d4
{ Logical and powerful. White follows the old adage that an attack on the flank should be countered with play in the center. }
8... exd4
{ is a big mistake. By giving up the f4 square, White can now safely capture the g4 bishop without worrying about Black's queen showing up on h4. }
9. hxg4 hxg4 10. Nh2 Qh4 { Black's careless 8th move in 8...exd4 enabled } 11.
Bf4
{ covering the h2 knight. Black has no way of continuing the attack and is essentially down a full piece. }
