1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bg4
{ This early bishop sortie is objectively quite dubious but can be tricky to face if you've never encountered it before, especially in short time controls. Black's main idea is that 6. h3 to try and break the pin can be met with 6...h5. }
6. h3 h5
{ Black's main idea is that  7.hxg4?  opens up the h-file with disastrous consequences. For example  7...hxg4  8.Ne1??  Qh4−+  and White is suddenly getting checkmated. }
7. Bxc6+
{ Playing ...h5 made the g4 bishop immune to capture. However, in doing so, Black neglected the center of the board which we're about to exploit with d2-d4. To do so, we first eliminate the c6 knight. }
7... bxc6 8. d4
{ Logical and powerful. White follows the old adage that an attack on the flank should be countered with play in the center. }
8... Qf6
{ Black brings the queen into the attack and pressures the f3 knight. } 9. Nbd2
g5
{ This aggressive kingside expansion has been played by Swedish GM Jonny Hector in several games. His results with this move have, however, not been great. The main reason is that Black has a very hard time bringing in more attackers onto the kingside.   For example, trying to get the knight into the attack with  9...Ne7  is well met by  10.Re1  when  10...Ng6?  already allows  11.hxg4!  hxg4  12.Nh2  Qh4  13.Ndf1+-  safely covering the h2 knight when Black's attack is dead. }
10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nc4
{ targeting both the e5 and g5 pawns is simple and effective. Black does not have a good response.   For example  11...Bxf3  12.Qxf3  Qxf3  13.gxf3  is a very advantageous endgame for White. Yes, White has doubled f-pawns but Black has no real way to attack them. Conversely, Black's queenside pawns are very exposed and can be targeted with moves like Na5. }
