1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bg4
{ This early bishop sortie is objectively quite dubious but can be tricky to face if you've never encountered it before, especially in short time controls. Black's main idea is that 6. h3 to try and break the pin can be met with 6...h5. }
6. h3 h5
{ Black's main idea is that  7.hxg4?  opens up the h-file with disastrous consequences. For example  7...hxg4  8.Ne1??  Qh4−+  and White is suddenly getting checkmated. }
7. Bxc6+
{ Playing ...h5 made the g4 bishop immune to capture. However, in doing so, Black neglected the center of the board which we're about to exploit with d2-d4. To do so, we first eliminate the c6 knight. }
7... bxc6 8. d4
{ Logical and powerful. White follows the old adage that an attack on the flank should be countered with play in the center. }
8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 exd4 10. e5
{ A powerful central strike! White blows up the center, opening up lines against Black's monarch. Notice how 10 moves into the game all of Black's pieces are still on their initial squares.   The slower  10.Re1  with ideas of e5 and c3 is also great for White. }
10... d5 { 10...dxe5??  11.Qxc6+  Ke7  12.Re1+-  is lights out. } 11. c3
{ Quick development and forcing play are the name of the game when the opponent's king is stuck in the center. }
11... Bc5
{ 11...dxc3  is inadvisable as after  12.Nxc3↑  White has a huge lead in development. White will rapidly get the bishop out and centralize the rooks while Black will find it very hard to complete development. }
12. Nd2
{ improves over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Zhigalko, S @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ -Fressinet,L @@StartBracket@@2662@@EndBracket@@ Katowice 2017. Next up is Nb3, which will recoup the d4 pawn, and give White a big advantage. Black's pawn structure is compromised and his king will have a hard time finding a safe haven. }
