[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...a6 4...d6 | Deferred Steinitz "]
[Black "5...Nf6 [Why not 6. c3]"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Nf6
{ Highlights the drawback of the 5. O-O variation. Black immediately attacks the e4 pawn ruling out the option of d2-d4. White has several choices:   6.Re1  and  6.c3  are the most popular continuations. I've opted to recommend the rare  6.c4!?  , which is 90x less common than 6. Re1 and thus far more likely to surprise your opponent. }
6. c3
{ Let's go on a slight detour and check on the theoretical status of 6. c3. }
6... Nxe4 7. d4 Bd7 8. Re1 Nf6 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+
{ This complex endgame arises pretty much by force. While White's position is easier to play and in many cases for two results, Black is doing well objectively speaking. }
11... Kxd8
{ is the correct recapture. The king should step out of the e-file.   11...Rxd8?!  It's inferior to leave the king on e8, where it's very exposed.  12.Nxe5  Be4  is the only way to continue.  13.Nd2  Be7  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Bh6!  This bolt from the blue gives White a big advantage. The double-attack on the g7 pawn and the knight on e4 forces Black to compromise the kingside structure.  15...gxh6  16.Rxe4±  gives White a clear advantage. }
12. Nxe5
{ There are two ways of covering the f7 pawn. The first is 12...Be8, played by both Artemiev and Rapport, and the other option is 12... Bd5. One of the advantages of 6. c4!? is now revealed - this move rules out the latter option. }
12... Be8
{ We'll follow two top level games where Black held his own:½-½ @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2763@@EndBracket@@-Rapport,R @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2019 and½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@-Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2711@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2020. }
13. Bg5 h6 { is a key move, forcing White to immediately take on f6. } 14.
Bxf6+ gxf6 15. Ng4 Be7 16. Nd2 Bd7 17. Ne3
{ is a very interesting endgame. Black's two bishops offer sufficient compensation for the compromised structure and the weakness on  f6  . Rapport played  17...Be6  while Artemiev opted for  17...c6  , with both games ending in a draw. White can naturally play on, but to win this position you'll have to play like Magnus! And that is certainly no easy feat :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...a6 4...d6 | Deferred Steinitz "]
[Black "5...Nf6 6. c4 Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Nf6
{ Highlights the drawback of the 5. O-O variation. Black immediately attacks the e4 pawn ruling out the option of d2-d4. White has several choices:   6.Re1  and  6.c3  are the most popular continuations. I've opted to recommend the rare  6.c4!?  , which is 90x less common than 6. Re1 and thus far more likely to surprise your opponent. }
6. c4 { A strong, rare and, extremely underrated continuation! } 6... Nxe4
{ With the pawn on c4 instead of c3, things turn out quite differently for Black. }
7. d4 Bd7 8. Re1 Nf6 9. Nbd2
{ The first difference is that White foregoes the immediate Bxc6 in favor of the text. It's aimed at preventing the exchange of queens.   9.Bxc6  It's instructive to understand why we discarded this option.  9...Bxc6  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Qxd8+  Now there's a big difference in having the pawn on c4 instead of c3.  11...Rxd8  You might recall this recapture was no good in the 6. c3 variation but it works out here.  12.Nxe5  Bb4!  This is the point. Having the pawn on c4, as opposed to c3, gives Black this extra option and guarantees the second player a good game. This is why we don't go for 9. Bxc6! }
9... Be7 10. Bxc6 { Now and only now! } 10... Bxc6 11. dxe5 Bxf3 { After } 12.
Qxf3
{ both f6 and b7 are hanging, ensuring White will emerge at least up a pawn.   For example  12...dxe5  13.Rxe5  O-O  14.Qxb7  Bd6  Now the rook does best in retreating to  15.Re2±  where it can be supported by Qf3 in case of ...Re8. Black has little to show for the pawn deficit. This line can be optionally trained in the nextalternative variation. }
