[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...a6 4...d6 | Deferred Steinitz "]
[Black "8...h5 10...d5 [Why not 11. Nd3]"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. c3 g5 7. d4 g4 8. Ne1 h5
9. f4
{ A key move to remember. We all know to meet a flank attack with a central reaction. This one is especially strong and tears down Black's center. }
9... exd4
{ The only plausible recapture, as taking the f4-pawn either way would open up the f-file and render Black's kingside expansion senseless. }
10. cxd4 d5
{ The machine likes  11.Nd3!?  but  11.e5  is not far behind and far easier to play. Let's briefly explore the theoretical status of  11.Nd3  in this informational line. }
11. Nd3 { leads to a very messy position, which I'd rather avoid. Here's why: }
11... dxe4 12. Ne5 f5 { Black isn't afraid of sacrificing a piece. } 13. Nxd7
{ I consider this to be the most challenging continuation.   For reference  13.Nc3  was another option I considered but Black can hold with precise play. The mainlines in my file go  13...Nf6  14.Qb3  Rh7  15.Nxd7   15.Be3  is well met by  15...b5  16.Bxb5  axb5  17.Nxc6  Bxc6  18.Qe6+  Be7  19.Qxc6+  Kf7  20.Qxb5  h4∞  15...Rxd7  16.Be3!  b5  17.Qe6+  Ne7  18.Qxf6  bxa4  19.Qg5  Rd6  20.d5  White may look to be doing well, but things aren't at all easy after  20...Kf7  21.Qxh5+  Kg8  22.Bc5  Rf6∞ }
13... Qxd7 14. d5 b5 15. dxc6 Qxc6 16. Bb3 Bc5+ 17. Kh1 Rd8 18. Qc2 Ne7
{ Black has two pawns for a piece and aren't those pawns scary! Precise play from both sides leads to an endgame following... }
19. Nd2
{ A cheeky idea, trying to bring the knight into the defense indirectly with Nc4-e3/e5. }
19... h4
{ 19...Kf8?!  is no good due to the stunning  20.Nxe4!!  Boom goes the dynamite!  20...fxe4  21.f5+-  With f6 coming next, there's no way Black is getting out of this one alive. }
20. Nc4 Bd4 21. Be3 h3 22. g3 Rh6
{ Sacrificing the queen is the way to go. I did warn you this line was really messy. }
23. Rfd1 bxc4 24. Ba4 Bxe3 25. Rxd8+ Kxd8 26. Bxc6 Rxc6
{ White is supposedly winning after all these complications, but converting this position is far from trivial. Arriving here is already extremely hard with non-intuitive lines that can be easily mixed up. If this were straight up winning, one could make a case for entering this labyrinth. As it stands, I'd rather avoid this mess entirely. }
