[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Steinitz Defense Deferred, also known as the Modern Steinitz, is one of the most interesting sidelines in the Ruy Lopez complex. By starting with 4...d6 and delaying the development of the g8 knight, Black retains a great deal of flexibility and the option of playing ...f7-f5 and even ....g7-g5 in many cases.   The Modern Steinitz complex contains everything from solid and positional lines to highly dynamic variations, full of sacrifices and vicious attacks. Objectively, Black is doing fairly well everywhere. White needs to be well prepared and employ cunning move orders to put the second player under pressure. Worry not, we've done all the work for you! }
5. O-O
{ is the first important crossroad.   5.c3  allows the Siesta variation with  5...f5  which leads to very sharp and messy positions. White does best in avoiding this swamp.   Coversely  5.O-O  rules out  5...f5  due to  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4!  A powerful central strike. With our king already on g1 and Black's king still on e8, the second player is ill-equipped to deal with the opening of the e-file.   Finally  5.d4?!  is to be avoided due to  5...b5!  6.Bb3  Nxd4  when recapturing twice on d4 loses a piece, i.e.  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4?  c5−+  followed by ...c4 wins the bishop. }
5... Bd7
{ This is the so-called Modern Steinitz variation @@StartBracket@@while 5...Nf6 is known as the Steinitz Deferred@@EndBracket@@. Black delays ...b7-b5 for as long as possible and keeps the knight on g8 flexible. }
6. c3 g5
{ is an enterprising attempt that should not be taken lightly. White needs to be precise to neutralize Black's attack, but accurate play will pay dividends. }
7. d4
{ The standard reaction to a flank attack is @@StartBracket@@you guessed it!@@EndBracket@@ a central counterattack. }
7... g4 8. Ne1 h5 9. f4
{ A key move to remember. We all know to meet a flank attack with a central reaction. This one is especially strong and tears down Black's center. }
9... exd4
{ The only plausible recapture, as taking the f4-pawn either way would open up the f-file and render Black's kingside expansion senseless. }
10. cxd4 d5
{ is the best attempt to muddy the waters. It occurred in a single game, namely Stijve, T - Horvath, D Mitropa Cup 2019. The machine likes 11. Nd3!? but 11. e5 is not far behind and far easier to play. }
11. e5
{ is far more practical than  11.Nd3  , whose theoretical status is discussedhere. At first glance, it seems like White is just weakening the light squares. However, once White regroups, the c-file will become an important asset and Black will constantly have to watch out for f4-f5. }
11... Nge7 12. Nc2 Nf5 13. Nc3 Be6
{ All very logical. Black occupies the weak light squares while White is regrouping his pieces. }
14. Ne3
{ with the idea Bc2 to displace the knight from f5. If Black's light-square blockade falls, f4-f5 will come with devastating effect.   14.Qd3  is a safe alternative.  14...Qd7  15.Bd2  This avoids any Black attack, not that we should be scared. }
14... g3
{ is Black's only chance. Slow play is not good enough, muddying the waters is the only way to go. }
15. hxg3
{ Ruthless.   15.h3  is also possible, locking up the position rather than gaining material. But there is no need to worry about opening the kingside. }
15... Qd7
{ Black prepares ... h5-h4 while ensuring the g4 square will be under his control.   15...Nxg3?  is a serious mistake on account of  16.f5!! }
16. Ne2 h4
{ In for a penny, in for a pound. Black has no option but to go for it.   16...O-O-O  is too slow.  17.Qd3±  sets Black big problems. Bxc6 to distract the queen from the defense of the f5 knight is a big threat. }
17. gxh4 Be7 18. Bd2
{ Cold-blooded and very strong, preparing Rc1. There's simply nothing to worry about on the kingside. }
18... O-O-O 19. Rc1 { A forced sequence now follows: } 19... b5 20. Bc2 Nxe3
21. Bxe3
{ It's move 21 and a good moment to stop. White will start a vicious attack with a4 and Bd3 very soon not to mention the immediate threat of f4-f5. Black has a lot of problems to solve.   21...Bg4  is practically forced as White was threatening f4-f5. After  22.Bd3  Rxh4  23.Qd2  Rdh8  24.Ng3±  adequately covers the h1 square. Black's attack is over before it even started and his queenside is about to come under serious pressure. }
