{ is a common move order that is likely to transpose to the mainline. } 7. d4
Bg7 8. h3 Nge7
{ is the only independent option.   8...Nf6  transposes to the mainline after  9.Re1  O-O }
9. d5
{ is my preferred option with 9. Be3 being far more popular. I believe it's better to delay this bishop move since in most lines we'll head for a KID structure. In such cases, the bishop on e3 would be subject to tempo gaining moves like ...f5-f4. }
9... Nb8 10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 h6
{ Black decides to keep the bishop on the board for the moment. He covers the g5 square in order to prepare ... f7-f5 @@StartBracket@@without allowing Ng5-e6@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Bc2
{ Bring it on says White!  In King's Indian structures, White seeks to exchange the light-squared bishops which often slows down or even completely nullifies Black's kingside attack. However, in this particular position, the d7 bishop is misplaced preventing the b8 knight from easily coming into the game. Moreover, Black is unable to mount an effective kingside attack with ...f7-f5.   For example  12...f5  13.Rb1  f4  14.b4  g5  15.c5  g4  only helps White secure an outpost for the knight on h4. After  16.Nh4  gxh3  White can play  17.g3!  when Black's attack is stalled. Following  17...Bf6  18.Nf5  Nxf5  19.exf5  It'll be White to attack on the kingside after Kh2 and Qh5.   If instead of the immediate @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1ppbn1b1/p2p3p/2PPp1p1/1P2Pp2/2N2N1P/P1B2PP1/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...g4  Black resorts to @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1ppbn1b1/p2p3p/2PPp1p1/1P2Pp2/2N2N1P/P1B2PP1/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Ng6  White has two good options, namely the prophylactic  16.Nh2  or  16.a4  g4  17.Nh2  gxh3  18.g3!  which once again completely neutralizes Black's attack. }
12... a5
{ This was played in an online tournament, where White reacted perfectly with }
13. a3
{ Intending to slowly prepare b2-b4. This is highly effective against Black's typical plan of ...Na6-c5. }
13... Na6
{ 13...f5  is well met by the cool and collected  14.Bd2±  If Black goes ... f4 and ...g5-g4, White will simply play Nh2 controlling all the light-squares around Black's pawns. Meanwhile, White will direct his attention to the queenside. }
14. Rb1 f5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4
{ This was all seen in the game0-1 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Steinberg,N @@StartBracket@@2542@@EndBracket@@ -Andriasian, Z @@StartBracket@@2611@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020.   Black ended up winning, but this position is certainly in White's favor. Black's attack is a ways away and White can break with c4-c5 at an opportune moment, likely supported by Ba3. }
