[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...a6 4...d6 | Deferred Steinitz "]
[Black "10...b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Steinitz Defense Deferred, also known as the Modern Steinitz, is one of the most interesting sidelines in the Ruy Lopez complex. By starting with 4...d6 and delaying the development of the g8 knight, Black retains a great deal of flexibility and the option of playing ...f7-f5 and even ....g7-g5 in many cases.   The Modern Steinitz complex contains everything from solid and positional lines to highly dynamic variations, full of sacrifices and vicious attacks. Objectively, Black is doing fairly well everywhere. White needs to be well prepared and employ cunning move orders to put the second player under pressure. Worry not, we've done all the work for you! }
5. O-O
{ is the first important crossroad.   5.c3  allows the Siesta variation with  5...f5  which leads to very sharp and messy positions. White does best in avoiding this swamp.   Coversely  5.O-O  rules out  5...f5  due to  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4!  A powerful central strike. With our king already on g1 and Black's king still on e8, the second player is ill-equipped to deal with the opening of the e-file.   Finally  5.d4?!  is to be avoided due to  5...b5!  6.Bb3  Nxd4  when recapturing twice on d4 loses a piece, i.e.  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4?  c5−+  followed by ...c4 wins the bishop. }
5... Bd7
{ This is the so-called Modern Steinitz variation @@StartBracket@@while 5...Nf6 is known as the Steinitz Deferred@@EndBracket@@. Black delays ...b7-b5 for as long as possible and keeps the knight on g8 flexible. }
6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1
{ White covers the e4 pawn and is now ready to expand in the center with d2-d4. }
7... g6 8. d4 Bg7 9. h3 O-O { is the main tabiya of the Deferred Steinitz. }
10. Bc2
{ is my preferred move order. The plan is to develop the bishop to e3 before bringing out the b1 knight.   10.Nbd2  is White's main move, which allows  10...exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  a rather annoying move, threatening jump into d3. 10. Bc2 rules this out given that with the knight still on b1, the d3 square is safely guarded. }
10... b5
{ The point of our previous move now becomes clear. White need not start the d2-f1-g3 knight tour right away and can instead start with }
11. Be3
{ The bishop comes out before the knight. This saves us from having to drop the knight back to f1 @@StartBracket@@had it been developed to d2@@EndBracket@@ in order to bring out the dark-squared bishop. }
11... Re8 12. Nbd2 Nh5
{ featured in the gameTer Sahakyan - Janaszak, Dawid Chess.com INT 2020. } 13.
Rc1
{ A simple improvement over the aforementioned game. White is slowly preparing the c3-c4 break @@StartBracket@@likely preceded by Bd3@@EndBracket@@. This is a good moment to stop. White has a simple plan while it's not at all clear what Black should do.   For example  13...a5  can be met with  14.a4  not to mention Black needs to constantly be on the lookout for d4-d5. }
*

