[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...a6 4...d6 | Deferred Steinitz "]
[Black "10...Nh5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Steinitz Defense Deferred, also known as the Modern Steinitz, is one of the most interesting sidelines in the Ruy Lopez complex. By starting with 4...d6 and delaying the development of the g8 knight, Black retains a great deal of flexibility and the option of playing ...f7-f5 and even ....g7-g5 in many cases.   The Modern Steinitz complex contains everything from solid and positional lines to highly dynamic variations, full of sacrifices and vicious attacks. Objectively, Black is doing fairly well everywhere. White needs to be well prepared and employ cunning move orders to put the second player under pressure. Worry not, we've done all the work for you! }
5. O-O
{ is the first important crossroad.   5.c3  allows the Siesta variation with  5...f5  which leads to very sharp and messy positions. White does best in avoiding this swamp.   Coversely  5.O-O  rules out  5...f5  due to  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.d4!  A powerful central strike. With our king already on g1 and Black's king still on e8, the second player is ill-equipped to deal with the opening of the e-file.   Finally  5.d4?!  is to be avoided due to  5...b5!  6.Bb3  Nxd4  when recapturing twice on d4 loses a piece, i.e.  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4?  c5−+  followed by ...c4 wins the bishop. }
5... Bd7
{ This is the so-called Modern Steinitz variation @@StartBracket@@while 5...Nf6 is known as the Steinitz Deferred@@EndBracket@@. Black delays ...b7-b5 for as long as possible and keeps the knight on g8 flexible. }
6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1
{ White covers the e4 pawn and is now ready to expand in the center with d2-d4. }
7... g6 8. d4 Bg7 9. h3 O-O { is the main tabiya of the Deferred Steinitz. }
10. Bc2
{ is my preferred move order. The plan is to develop the bishop to e3 before bringing out the b1 knight.   10.Nbd2  is White's main move, which allows  10...exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4  a rather annoying move, threatening jump into d3. 10. Bc2 rules this out given that with the knight still on b1, the d3 square is safely guarded. }
10... Nh5
{ is very logical, clearing the way for an eventual ...f5 break. Black can prepare it with ...Qe8 and ...Kh8. }
11. Be3 Qe8
{ Black can also start with   11...Kh8  but this will transpose to the text as after  12.Nbd2  Qe8  Black should put his queen on e8 to support the h5 knight. }
12. Nbd2 Kh8
{ White has several options at his junction: 13. Nc4, 13. a4!? and even 13. Bb3. It largely comes down to a matter of preference with transpositions between several of these also being possible, }
13. Nc4
{ was played in a top-level correspondence game and is practically speaking also very good.   13.a4  is another interesting possibility. }
13... f5 { Black gets this typical break at just the perfect time! } 14. exf5
{ is the way to go.   In the correspondence game½-½ Demakov, V @@StartBracket@@2436@@EndBracket@@ -Tyulenko, Y @@StartBracket@@2441@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2014 White played  14.dxe5  which gave Black the chance to equalize with  14...f4  15.Bd4  dxe5  16.Bc5  now Black has the additional option of putting the rook in a better square with  16...Rg8  Black is objectively ok. }
14... Bxf5
{ 14...e4  allows  15.d5  exf3  16.dxc6  Bxc6  17.Bg5±  and White is just clearly better. }
15. dxe5 Bxc2 16. Qxc2 Rxf3
{ is Black's only chance to make something out of his position. Anything else gives White a pleasant advantage. }
17. exd6
{ Chess is not checkers and White is under no obligation to capture the rook on f3!   17.gxf3  Black's idea was to meet this move with  17...d5  18.Nd2  Qe6∞  with pretty decent compensation. }
17... Rf7 { 18.Bb6  is also possible but far messier than } 18. dxc7
{ White is now threatening both  19.Nd6  , winning material, as well as  19.Bb6  to hold onto the c7 knight.   Best play by both sides continues  18...Rxc7  when  19.Nb6  is the start of a forced sequence of moves:  19...Rd8  20.Bg5  The double-attack on the rook and queen forces the knight to go back.  20...Ne7  21.Qe4  Nf6  22.Bxf6  Bxf6  23.Nd5  Rxd5  24.Qxd5  Nxd5  25.Rxe8  Kg7  26.Rg1⩲  The smoke has cleared and White has the upper hand in this very interesting endgame. While it's not easy to convert it into a full point, White has the extremely straightforward plan of slowly pushing the kingside pawns. The c3 + b2 pawn chain can be supported by Re2 if need be. Both Lc0 and Stockfish give White a slight advantage and I'm not one to overrule the engine. Practically speaking, I'd take White any day here. If you're up for memorizing this entire sequence, you can do so in the followingalternative line. }
