14. Bd4 dxe5
{ Not allowing any trades and thus keeping the position as complicated as possible. }
15. Bc5 Rf6 16. Bb3+ Kh8 17. Bd5
{ White is doing very well here. The following sample lines, which you don't need to remember, should give you a good feeling of how the game may proceed.   17...h6  intending ...g6-g5-g4.  18.Nh2!  An excellent resource, taking control over the light-squares on the kingside.  18...g5  19.a4⩲  A great example of the 'Total Chess' concept from the book Think Like a Machine - controlling the whole board! White is without a doubt better, the only question is how much better. Black's attack is a ways away and White should only take to not allow ...f4-f3. White can look to slowly improve his position, for example by pushing the queenside pawns.   17...b6  is not worrisome. We can simply tuck our bishop away on a3.  18.Ba3  Rd8  19.Nf1  intending to put the knight on h2 which will do a good job preventing any ... g5-g4 ideas. For example  19...Na7  20.N1h2  c6  21.Bc4  Bxh3  22.Qb3+-  The queenside is far more important than the h3 pawn. Black is busted.   Finally  17...g5  is a pawn White can and should grab  18.Nxg5  not fearing  18...Qg6  which is strongly met by  19.Ngf3  Bxh3  20.Nh4!  Qg4  21.Qxg4  Bxg4  22.Ndf3±  with a big advantage. }
