1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This early knight sortie is known as the Norwegian variation, also called the Taimanov or Wing variation. Its name derives from the fact that it was introduced by Svein Johannasen in 1957 and later popularized by several Norwegian players, most notably Simen Agdestein.   Black's idea is to eliminate our light-squared bishop, gaining the bishop pair in the process. If the second player can survive the opening, he'd then be able to reach a favorable middlegame with the two bishops.   The main drawback of 5...Na5 is that it wastes a lot of time, which we'll exploit by countering in the center. }
6. O-O
{ Popular and principled. White secures his king and is now ready to blast open the center with d2-d4. }
6... Nxb3 7. axb3 d6 8. d4
{ As usual, we take over the center at the earliest opportunity. } 8... f6
{ Black is trying to keep his center together. White must play energetically to emerge with an advantage. }
9. Nc3 { 9.c4  is well met by  9...b4! } 9... Bb7
{ is the most logical square for the bishop.   9...Bg4?!  makes little sense as the bishop can be promptly kicked back with  10.h3  Bh5  11.dxe5  fxe5  12.g4  Bg6  13.Ng5  The knight now moves in!  13...Qd7  14.Nd5±  gives White a clear advantage. The first player can look to to hunt down Black's king with f4 or disturb Black with another cheeky knight jump in the form of Ne6.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/2p3pp/p2p1p2/1p2p3/3PP1b1/1PN2N1P/1PP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b k@@EndFEN@@  10...Bxf3  is no improvement. After  11.Qxf3  exd4  12.Ne2  c5  13.Nf4  is close to winning. Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
10. Qd3
{ is the best square for the queen. White reinforces the e4 pawn while clearing the d1 square for the rook. }
10... Ne7 11. Rd1
{ White is undoubtedly better. The second player will struggle to complete development while all of White's pieces have good squares. }
