1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This early knight sortie is known as the Norwegian variation, also called the Taimanov or Wing variation. Its name derives from the fact that it was introduced by Svein Johannasen in 1957 and later popularized by several Norwegian players, most notably Simen Agdestein.   Black's idea is to eliminate our light-squared bishop, gaining the bishop pair in the process. If the second player can survive the opening, he'd then be able to reach a favorable middlegame with the two bishops.   The main drawback of 5...Na5 is that it wastes a lot of time, which we'll exploit by countering in the center. }
6. O-O
{ Popular and principled. White secures his king and is now ready to blast open the center with d2-d4. }
6... d6 { is Black's most popular continuation. } 7. d4
{ This central strike is the critical test of the Norwegian defense. It's very logical, following the old-age rule that flank attacks @@StartBracket@@like ...Na5@@EndBracket@@ are well met by counterattacks in the center.   7.c3  is way too slow. Black is doing well after  7...Nxb3  8.axb3  Bb7  9.d4  Nf6=   7.Re1  is possible but allows Black to create a mess with  7...g5!? }
7... exd4 8. Re1
{ is the best move in the position. Black has to be very accurate not to go down in flames. }
8... Ne7
{ is way too slow. Inarkiev quickly got a winning position against Moiseenko after }
9. Nxd4 c5 10. Nf5
{ Up the board is the only way forward! We're more than happy to sacrifice a piece to blast open the e-file. }
10... Bxf5 11. exf5 c4
{ Yes, our bishop is trapped but we couldn't care less. Black is about to come under a vicious attack. }
12. Nc3 f6
{ was the move played in the only game to reach this position so far.   12...cxb3Ν  13.axb3  Despite being up a piece, Black can hardly move. Case in point:  13...Nac6  14.Bf4  Ne5  15.Bxe5  dxe5  16.Qf3+-  White is threatening f6, Rxe5, and Nxb5 which are just way too many threats. Black is busted. }
13. a4 { puts Black's queenside under severe pressure. } 13... cxb3 14. axb5
Kf7 15. Qe2
{ improves over the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Inarkiev,E @@StartBracket@@2693@@EndBracket@@-Moiseenko,V @@StartBracket@@2523@@EndBracket@@ Konya 2019 where White played bxa6. White has a decisive advantage, the immediate threat being Qe6+. }
