1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This early knight sortie is known as the Norwegian variation, also called the Taimanov or Wing variation. Its name derives from the fact that it was introduced by Svein Johannasen in 1957 and later popularized by several Norwegian players, most notably Simen Agdestein.   Black's idea is to eliminate our light-squared bishop, gaining the bishop pair in the process. If the second player can survive the opening, he'd then be able to reach a favorable middlegame with the two bishops.   The main drawback of 5...Na5 is that it wastes a lot of time, which we'll exploit by countering in the center. }
6. O-O
{ Popular and principled. White secures his king and is now ready to blast open the center with d2-d4. }
6... d6 { is Black's most popular continuation. } 7. d4
{ This central strike is the critical test of the Norwegian defense. It's very logical, following the old-age rule that flank attacks @@StartBracket@@like ...Na5@@EndBracket@@ are well met by counterattacks in the center.   7.c3  is way too slow. Black is doing well after  7...Nxb3  8.axb3  Bb7  9.d4  Nf6=   7.Re1  is possible but allows Black to create a mess with  7...g5!? }
7... exd4 8. Re1
{ is the best move in the position. Black has to be very accurate not to go down in flames as occurred in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Inarkiev,E @@StartBracket@@2693@@EndBracket@@-Moiseenko,V @@StartBracket@@2523@@EndBracket@@ Konya 2019. }
8... Nxb3
{ is Black's only logical continuation. We've seen how damaging Bd5 can be so Black does best in chopping on b3. After all, the point of ...Na5 was to grab the bishop. }
9. axb3 c5
{ There's no better move than to try and hang onto the pawn. White will soon get it back though. }
10. c3
{ Regains the pawn right away. Black is far too underdeveloped to get away with taking on c3. }
10... Be7
{ 10...dxc3  is suicidal. After  11.Nxc3  Black has big issues. There's no way to simultaneously deal with the threats of Nxb5 and e4-e5. }
11. cxd4 Nf6 12. Nc3
{ The knight comes out with tempo, threatening to chop on b5. } 12... Bb7
{ is the only sensible move, neutralizing the threat to the b5 pawn.   12...Be6?!  is a far worse square for the bishop, where it's exposed to d4-d5 and e4-e5.  13.h3!  White first takes control over the g4 square and only then pushes the d-pawn.  13...O-O  14.d5  Bd7  15.e5↑  White is clearly in the driver's seat. }
13. Nh4
{ Black's bishop abandoned the c8-h3 diagonal, surrendering control over the f5 square. As such, White immediately directs the cavalry to this outpost. }
13... b4
{ is practically forced. Anything else and White's knight just anchors itself on f5 with devastating consequences for the second player. }
14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5
{ White's knight is about to land on f5 with a firm advantage.   Two sample lines run  15...O-O  , which is practically forced to get the king out of the center.  16.Nf5  Bf6   Worse is  16...Re8  17.Bf4  Bf8  18.dxc5  dxc5  19.Rxe8  Qxe8  20.Ne3  with a big positional bind.  17.Bf4  cxd4!  18.Qf3!  is an important move, securing the d5 pawn before taking on d6.  18...Re8  19.Nxd6  Rxe1+  20.Rxe1  Qd7  21.h4!  with the idea Nxb7 followed by Bg5 gives White the upper hand. }
