[White "4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part I"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ The Berlin defense is one of the best lines against the Spanish. It was used to great effect by Vladimir Kramnik to put an end to Kasparov's dominant reign in their 2000 World Championship match. Ever since it's only gained in popularity and is now a staple in the repertoire of the world's elite. }
4. d3
{ is my recommendation. This variation, known as the Anti-Berlin, has been gaining in popularity given that White has failed to show an edge in the Berlin endgame.   4.O-O  is White's other major option.  4...Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Thousands upon thousands of games have been played in this fascinating endgame. Black has been doing very well here and has more than one way to equalize. }
4... Bc5
{ This will be the main topic of the current chapter.   4...d6  and other 4th moves are covered in theBerlin without 4...Bc5 chapter. }
5. Bxc6
{ In this course, I've decided to immediately go for the Exchange Ruy Lopez structure - a good way of challenging the Berlin without having to learn tons of theory.   This is an opportune moment to take on c6 as Black is forced to recapture with the d7-pawn. This leads to a superior pawn structure for the first player who only has one pawn island compared to Black's two. In turn, the second player gets the bishop pair but it won't be easy to make use of them given the closed nature of the position.   5.Nc3!?  Transposing to the Spanish four knights is another interesting option.   5.c3  is White's most popular move. }
5... dxc6 { 5...bxc6?  blunders the e5 pawn to  6.Nxe5± } 6. Nbd2
{ Black now has several moves at his disposal: } 6... O-O
{ seen in 500+ OTB games.   Other options include  6...Be6  played in 400+ games   6...Nd7  featured in 300+ games.   6...Bg4  was essayed in 100+ games.   6...Qd6  ,  6...Bd6  and  6...Ng4  are far rarer with only a few dozen games in the database.  This chapter is dedicated to Black's sidelines while the three most popular moves, namely 6...O-O, 6...Be6, and 6...Nd7 are covered in thenext chapter. }
*

