[White "4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part I"]
[Black "6...Ng4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ The Berlin defense is one of the best lines against the Spanish. It was used to great effect by Vladimir Kramnik to put an end to Kasparov's dominant reign in their 2000 World Championship match. Ever since it's only gained in popularity and is now a staple in the repertoire of the world's elite. }
4. d3
{ is my recommendation. This variation, known as the Anti-Berlin, has been gaining in popularity given that White has failed to show an edge in the Berlin endgame. }
4... Bc5
{ This is Black's main move, developing the bishop to its most active square.   4...d6  and other 4th moves are covered in thenext chapter. }
5. Bxc6
{ immediately going for the Exchange Ruy Lopez structure - a good way of challenging the Berlin without having to learn tons of theory. This is an opportune moment to take on c6 as Black is forced to recapture with the d7-pawn. This leads to a superior pawn structure for the first player who only has one pawn island compared to Black's two. In turn, the second player gets the bishop pair but it won't be easy to make use of them given the closed nature of the position. }
5... dxc6 6. Nbd2
{ Heading to c4 is one of White's two mainlines.   6.O-O  is the other major continuation. }
6... Ng4 { is a nonsensical move, almost exclusively seen in blitz. } 7. O-O
{ White easily covers the f2 pawn, when the knight on g4 is simply misplaced. The only thing White should avoid is taking on g4 after h3 ...h5. }
7... h5 8. Nb3
{ White doesn't even need to play h3. Instead, it's stronger to go after Black's dark-squared bishop. }
8... Bb6 9. a4 { Threatening a4-a5, which Black must do something about. } 9...
a5
{ 9...a6  is also possible, but we can just play  10.Qe1  with the idea Qe1-c3 to attack the e5 pawn. Bd2-c3 with the same goal is also possible. At some point, h3 will come and Black's knight will be booted. }
10. Qe1
{ Overprotects the f2 pawn and takes aim at the a5 pawn. Bd2 will soon follow to pressure this weakness. }
10... Be6 11. Ra3
{ covering the b3 knight is an important reaction. White is at least slightly better with Bd2-c3 on the way. This will place the e5 and a5 pawns under significant pressure. }
