11. f4
{ White must act quickly and get this break in before Black's knight lands on e6. This timely pawn break gives White the upper hand.   A sample continuation is  11...exf4  12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Bxf4  It's important to note that  13...g5?!  is no good due to  14.Bxg5!  fxg5  15.Qh5+  Kd8  16.Ng6+-  Black will end up with two pieces for a rook but his remaining pieces are awfully placed. White has a huge advantage. }
