1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Protecting the e5 pawn with the queen is a sensible move. However, the queen isn't particularly well placed on e7, which is why this 6th move is pretty rare. Concretely, it can easily become the target of a future Nf5. }
7. Nc4 { is a logical reply, upping the pressure on the e5 pawn. } 7... Nd7
{ is by far Black's main move and most logical way of covering the e5 pawn.   7...Ng4  has been tried in a handful of games.  8.O-O  b5  has been played almost exclusively to date. White should jump in with  9.Na5!  Bb6  and now the simple  10.Qe1⩲  protecting the knight and preparing a later Qc3 to attack the e5 pawn is very logical. White has the better game and will likely follow up with h3, Qc3 and a2-a4. }
8. O-O
{ Logical and principled, completing kingside development and securing the king.   8.Qe2  fails to impress after the relatively new and strong  8...b6!?  as seen in Sjuigirov, S. - Andreikin, D. Titled Tuesday Chess.com 2020, where Black got a very decent game and even managed to win. }
8... f6
{ is Black's best move-order, maintaining a great deal of flexibility. } 9. c3
{ White has two pawn push ideas in mind: d4 and b4+a4.   9.Ne3  would be met with  9...Nf8  when Black is faster in controlling d4, and still can decide whether to castle kingside or queenside. }
9... O-O
{ White will start pushing his queenside pawns, and some sample variations will run:   9...Qf7  stops d4 but fails to address  10.b4  Play may continue  10...Be7  11.Be3  c5  12.a3  O-O  13.Nfd2⩲  when White will slowly prepare d4 while it's not clear what Black should do. }
10. b4 Bd6 11. a4
