[White "4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part I"]
[Black "6...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Bg4
{ Developing the light-squared bishop to its most active post is Black's 4th most popular move. It comes with an interesting plan, namely to finish development with ...Nd7, ...f6 and eventually drop the bishop back to f7. Black's king typically castles long and then the second player aims to reroute the knight to e6. We're naturally not going to allow all this! }
7. h3
{ 7.Nb3  is also possible but it gives Black the extra option of  7...Bb6  8.h3  Be6  and taking on b3. The text is a more accurate move order. }
7... Be6 { By holding back Nb3, we can jump in with } 8. Ng5
{ since Black does not have the typical reply ...Bxb3. } 8... Qe7 9. Nxe6 Qxe6
10. Qe2
{ is most flexible. We want to see where Black's king is headed before committing ourselves to a particular setup. }
10... O-O-O 11. Nc4 Nd7 12. a4
{ White will slowly push his queenside pawns to create weaknesses. While Black is quite solid, White has the better chances. }
