[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Bg4
{ Developing the light-squared bishop to its most active post is Black's 4th most popular move. It comes with an interesting plan, namely to finish development with ...Nd7, ...f6 and eventually drop the bishop back to f7. Black's king typically castles long and then the second player aims to reroute the knight to e6. We're naturally not going to allow all this! }
7. h3 Bh5
{ is by far Black's most popular bishop move. The bishop is most active on this square and can later drop back to f7 after ...f6.   7...Bxf3  Going ...Bg4 just to give up the bishop on f3 makes little sense. White obtains a comfortable advantage after the following sample continuation  8.Qxf3  Nd7  9.Nc4  Qe7  10.Bd2  Nb6  11.Ne3⩲  The knight is headed to f5 with a firm advantage. White went on to win in1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Zvjaginsev,V @@StartBracket@@2666@@EndBracket@@-Stojanovic,D @@StartBracket@@2466@@EndBracket@@ Rogaska Slatina 2011. }
8. Nb3
{ This early knight sortie is an interesting possibility. Grischuk used it to defeat Carlsen in a blitz game and Caruana later beat Swiercz in the PRO League so we're certainly in good company!   8.g4  Bg6  9.Nxe5?  is impossible due to  9...Qd4-+  with the dual threat of ...Qxf2# and ...Qxe5. }
8... Bb6 { Blunders the e5 pawn after } 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxe5
{ With the knight on b3, there's no ...Qd4 to hit e5 and f2. Black is therefore a full pawn down. }
