[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White " 4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part II"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ The Berlin defense is one of the best lines against the Spanish. It was used to great effect by Vladimir Kramnik to put an end to Kasparov's dominant reign in their 2000 World Championship match. Ever since it's only gained in popularity and is now a staple in the repertoire of the world's elite. }
4. d3
{ is my recommendation. This variation, known as the Anti-Berlin, has been gaining in popularity given that White has failed to show an edge in the Berlin endgame.   4.O-O  is White's other major option.  4...Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Thousands upon thousands of games have been played in this fascinating endgame. Black has been doing very well here and has more than one way to equalize. }
4... Bc5
{ This will be the main topic of the current chapter.   4...d6  and other 4th moves are covered in thenext chapter. }
5. Bxc6
{ In this course, I've decided to go for the Exchange Ruy Lopez structure.   5.Nc3!?  Transposing to the Spanish four knights is another interesting option.   5.c3  is White's most popular move. }
5... dxc6 { 5...bxc6?  blunders the e5 pawn to  6.Nxe5± } 6. Nbd2
{ This chapter is dedicated to Black's three most common continuations in this position, namely }
6... O-O
{ seen in 500+ OTB games,   6...Be6  played in 400+ games,   and  6...Nd7  which featured in 300+ games.   Less common alternatives such as  6...Bg4  ,  6...Qd6  ,  6...Bd6  and  6...Ng4  were covered in theprevious chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White " 4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part II"]
[Black "6...Be6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Be6
{ is a solid and arguably Black's safest 6th move option. The second player brings the light-squared out, intending to follow up with ...Nd7 and ... f6 to create a harmonious setup. The drawback is that Black has to forego the bishop pair in several variations. }
7. O-O Bd6 8. d4
{ is a timely break, taking advantage of the fact that ...exd4 is impossible due to e5. }
8... Nd7 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. f4
{ White establishes a strong, central pawn duo and is ready to grab even more space with f5 and e5. }
11... Qd4+
{ Black lunges the queen into d4, where it's quite vulnerable, in an attempt to create weaknesses in White's camp.   11...Bd4+  12.Kh1  White is now threatening f5 which forces Black to make room for the light-squared bishop. For example  12...f6  13.c3  Be3  14.f5  Bf7  15.Qf3  Bxd2  16.Rd1  Qe7  17.Rxd2!  is the best recapture, stopping queenside castling. White has a stable advantage. }
12. Kh1 Bd6 { 12...Bf6  is met the same way with  13.e5  Be7  14.f5 } 13. e5
{ is an improvement over the games Nakamura, H. - Aronian, L. Zurich Blitz 2016; Malakhov, V. - Dominguez, L. RUS-chT Sochi 2019; and Leko, P. - Wang, H. Hengshui 2019.   13.Qe2?!  was played in the three aforementioned games. Dominguez played the strong  13...f6↑  which gave Black an excellent game. }
13... Bc5 14. f5
{ White has a dangerous initiative with e5-e6 and c2-c3 coming up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White " 4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part II"]
[Black "6...Be6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Be6
{ is a solid and arguably Black's safest 6th move option. The second player brings the light-squared out, intending to follow up with ...Nd7 and ... f6 to create a harmonious setup. The drawback is that Black has to forego the bishop pair in several variations. }
7. O-O Bd6 8. d4
{ is a timely break, taking advantage of the fact that ...exd4 is impossible due to e5. }
8... Nd7 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. f4 Bd4+
{ Arguably more natural than 11...Qd4 is to remove the bishop from danger with check. }
12. Kh1 { White is now threatening to push back Black's bishop with f4-f5. }
12... f5
{ 12...f6  is another way to create space for the light-squared bishop. White emerges with the better chances after  13.c3  Be3  14.f5  gaining space and putting yet another pawn on light-squares, further restricting Black's unopposed bishop.  14...Bf7  15.Qf3  Bxd2  16.Rd1  Qe7  17.Rxd2!  is the best recapture, stopping queenside castling. White has a stable advantage. }
13. Qh5+ { White provokes the pawn to g6, further weakening Black's kingside. }
13... g6 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Nf3 Bf6
{ Black does best in preserving the dark-squared bishop given all the weaknesses on this color complex. }
16. e5 Be7 17. Rd1
{ White is objectively slightly better and, importantly, has scored 2.0/3.0 in top-level games - a clear indication that Black's position is hard to handle. In particular, White has a considerable space advantage and better coordination. Conversely, Black's position is cramped and, despite the absence of any obvious weaknesses, the second player will have a hard time coming up with an active plan.   A likely continuation is  17...Qe8  18.Nd4  Qf7  19.Nxe6  Qxe6  This was all covered in Lifetime Repertoires: Berlin Defense by GM Sam Shankland, who admitted White is objectively slightly better. Indeed, Vishy Anand went on to beat Wesley So from this position in the 2019 Grand Chess Tour Rapid & Blitz tournament after  20.Be3⩲  This game is analyzed in-depth in thekey middlegame themes section. }
