[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White " 4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part II"]
[Black "6...Be6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Be6
{ is a solid and arguably Black's safest 6th move option. The second player brings the light-squared out, intending to follow up with ...Nd7 and ... f6 to create a harmonious setup. The drawback is that Black has to forego the bishop pair in several variations. }
7. O-O Nd7 { is Black's most popular move. } 8. Nb3
{ Not only displaces Black's bishop but also gives White the option of jumping into a5 in the future. }
8... Be7
{ has proven to be a worse square for the bishop than b6. From e7, the bishop stops Ng5 but fails to control the a5 square and the important a7-g1 diagonal. }
9. d4
{ Exploits another drawback of ...Be7, that is Black weakened his control over the d4 square.  The immediate knight sortie   9.Na5  was tried by Nisipeanu all the way back in 2014. It's a tad premature and Black obtained good counter-chances after  9...Rb8  10.Bd2  O-O  11.h3  f5  12.exf5  Rxf5=  1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Nisipeanu,L @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@-Wagner,D @@StartBracket@@2499@@EndBracket@@ Baden-Baden 2014 Nisipeanu went on to win, but Black had a good game out of the opening. }
9... f6
{ 9...Bf6  is well met by  10.Re1  O-O  11.Na5!  Rb8  12.c3⩲  establishing a strong center. White has a slight and stable edge. }
10. Na5
{ Here comes the knight sortie, hitting b7 and thus tying up Black's rook to the defense of this pawn. }
10... Rb8
{ 10...Qc8  was played by Nakamura against Wesley So in a 2020 online blitz game. It's inferior to the text as after the relatively forced sequence  11.dxe5  fxe5  12.Ng5  Bxg5  13.Qh5+  Bf7  14.Qxg5  O-O  15.Rd1±  White was clearly better. His pieces are far more active and Black has many weaknesses in his camp. }
11. dxe5 fxe5 { 11...fxe5 allows White to jump in with } 12. Ng5
{ causing Black big problems. } *

