1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Be6
{ is a solid and arguably Black's safest 6th move option. The second player brings the light-squared out, intending to follow up with ...Nd7 and ... f6 to create a harmonious setup. The drawback is that Black has to forego the bishop pair in several variations. }
7. O-O Nd7 { is Black's most popular move. } 8. Nb3
{ Not only displaces Black's bishop but also gives White the option of jumping into a5 in the future. }
8... Bb6
{ is the best square for the bishop, keeping control over the a7-g1 diagonal and the a5 square. }
9. Ng5
{ is an important knight sortie to neutralize Black's bishop pair advantage. The drawback of the early light-squared bishop development is now evident. }
9... Bxb3
{ 9...Qe7?!  is answered by  10.Nxe6  Qxe6  11.a4⩲  with a solid edge. } 10.
axb3 Qe7 11. Nf3
{ The knight has done its job on g5 and is now headed to c4.   11.Bd2  featued inGiri, A. - Carlsen, M. Norway Masters Blitz 2016 where Black played the careless  11...O-O-O ?!  castling straight into an attack after  12.b4!  Instead  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pppnqppp/1bp5/4p1N1/4P3/1P1P4/1PPB1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f6  would have been far stronger. }
11... a6
{ is an interesting, prophylactic move. Black reads White's idea of Nd2-c4 and thus creates a square on a7 for the bishop. }
12. Nd2 { The knight is headed to c4 anyhow. } 12... Ba7 13. Nc4 O-O-O 14. Qe1
{ A subtle semi-useful waiting move, slightly improving the queen and seeing what Black is up to.   14.Kh1  is premature on account of  14...g5!  ruling out f4. Without this break, Kh1 merely wasted a tempo. }
14... g5
{ With the kings castled on opposite wings, Black logically starts advancing the kingside pawns. This attacking move, however, weakens the f5 square.   14...Kb8  If Black insists on playing the waiting game, we can continue with  15.Be3  Bxe3  16.Qxe3  f6  17.f4  gave White the better game in1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. }
15. Ne3 Bxe3
{ is basically forced. Black cannot allow our knight to sit on f5. } 16. Bxe3
{ 16.Qxe3  with the idea Qa7 is playable. Nevertheless, Black has enough defensive resources to meet this queen sortie with  16...Rhg8!  is the right rook to place on g8.   16...Rdg8  is a mistake as after  17.Qa7  Qc5  18.Qa8+  Nb8  19.Be3  Qxc2  20.Rfc1  Qxb3  21.Ra3  Qb4  White can now play  22.Rcc3+-  With the d8 rook on g8, Black does not have the countershot .. .Rxd3!  The point is that after  17.Qa7  Qc5  18.Qa8+  Nb8  19.Be3  Qxc2  20.Rfc1  Qxb3  21.Ra3  Qb4  22.Rcc3  Black now has the countershot  22...Rxd3!  Very subtle but it makes all the difference! }
16... h5 17. b4
{ We start active operations on the queenside with the point that our attack will be faster. This is because Black has already weakened this flank and we already have the a-file to work with. Conversely, we have no weaknesses on the kingside. }
