{ 9...Qe7?!  is answered by  10.Nxe6  Qxe6  11.a4⩲  with a solid edge. } 10.
axb3 f6 11. Nf3 Nf8 { 11...Qe7  transposes to the10...Qe7 variation. } 12. Nd2
Qd7 { is a prelude to ...Ne6, intending to meet Qh5+ with ... Qf7. } 13. Nc4
Ne6 14. Kh1
{ White has several good options at this junction, ranging from 14. Nxb6, 14. Qf3 to 14. Kh1. The text is my preference as it rules out 14...O-O-O. }
14... O-O
{ 14...Bc5  to preserve the dark-squared bishop is well met by  15.f4!  exf4  16.Bxf4  Nxf4  17.Rxf4  O-O  18.Rf5  Bd6  19.Qf3↑  when there's no doubt White has easier play. }
15. g3
{ with the idea f4 is @@StartBracket@@arguably@@EndBracket@@ White's best option. This preparatory move was not considered by GM Laurent Fressinet in the chess24 video series Play the Berlin. }
15... a6
{ was exclusively played thus far. The point is to liberate the rook from having to defend the a7 pawn. }
16. f3
{ White would like to be able to bring the queen out to e2. By playing f3 first, White can then meet ...Nd4 with Qg2.   16.f4  exf4  is still premature due to  17.gxf4  f5!  a move Black is banking on. }
16... Rad8 17. Qe2 Bd4 18. Qg2
{ is a good point to stop. While the position remains complex, White retains the better chances as illustrated below:   @@StartBracket@@a@@EndBracket@@  18...f5  leads to complex play.  19.Qh3  f4   19...fxe4  20.dxe4⩲  opens the d-file in White's favor. The e5 pawn will also be hard to protect in the long run.  20.c3  Black can just about maintain the balance with a very accurate sequence of moves starting with the counterblow  20...b5  21.cxd4  bxc4  22.dxe5  cxd3  23.gxf4  Nxf4  24.Qxd7  Rxd7  25.Bd2  And now the only move to maintain the balance is  25...Rdf7□  The point is to meet Rxa6 with ... Ng6 when the f3 pawn drops.  26.Rad1  h5  is Black's best try.   26...g5  gives White some hope for the win with  27.h4  with the point that  27...gxh4  is bad because of  28.Rg1+  Rg7  29.Rxg7+  Kxg7  30.Bxf4  Rxf4  31.Rxd3  White has good chances of converting this rook endgame.  27.Bxf4  Rxf4  28.Kg2  Rd8  29.Kf2  Just to get here, Black had to find several only moves and the endgame is still uncomfortable for him. White has decent practical winning chances.   @@StartBracket@@b@@EndBracket@@  18...Qe7  played in½-½ @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2756@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2779@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2019 allows the brilliant countershot  19.b4!  Kh8  with the point that after  20.f4  exf4  21.gxf4  f5  22.c3  Bf6  23.exf5+-  surprisingly traps the knight. The idea behind 19. b4 is now revealed. Very deep and strong! }
