1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Nd7
{ is Black's third most popular move. In this move order, the second player can opt to get f6 in without first committing to castling short. }
7. Nc4 f6
{ Delaying ... O-O to first reinforce the center has been gaining in popularity. Karjakin and Wesley So have put the spotlight on this more flexible move order. }
8. c3
{ 8.O-O  is met by the immediate  8...Nf8  when Black can quickly get the knight to e6. }
8... O-O
{ 8...Nb6  9.b4  Bd6  10.Nxd6+  leads to similar play as the 9...Nb6 variation. }
9. O-O { Only now that Black has castled does White follow suit. } 9... Re8
{ allows White to expand in the center with d2-d4. } 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Bf8
12. Qb3
{ is a logical move, developing the queen with tempo. The central pawn duo affords White a stable advantage. Logical next moves include Re1 and Bf4.   12.Qc2  was tried by Fedoseev against Karjakin. Black got a decent game after  12...Nb6  13.b3  Bg4  White managed to win the game, but not due to an opening advantage.   Further analysis on  12...Kh8  can be found in the nextalternative variation that you can opt to train. }
*

