8... O-O
{ 8...Nb6  9.b4  Bd6  10.Nxd6+  leads to similar play as the 9...Nb6 variation. }
9. O-O { Only now that Black has castled does White follow suit. } 9... Re8
{ allows White to expand in the center with d2-d4. } 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Bf8
12. Qb3
{ is a logical move, developing the queen with tempo.   12.Qc2  was tried by Fedoseev against Karjakin. Black got a decent game after  12...Nb6  13.b3  Bg4  White managed to win the game, but not due to an opening advantage. }
12... Kh8 13. Re1 a5
{ Given that Black has surrendered control over the center, the second player creates play on the queenside.   13...Nb6  is met by the typical knight-sortie  14.Na5  pressuring Black's queenside.  14...Rb8  15.h3⩲  White is at least slightly better due to the big, stable center. }
14. Bf4 b5 15. Na3
{ is my preference, removing the knight from the c-file to target the c6 pawn. White has good play with Qc2 and Rad1 on the agenda.   15.Ncd2  is playable but I'm not a fan of allowing  15...a4  16.Qc2  c5!? }
*

