[White " 4. d3 | Berlin with 4...Bc5 Part II"]
[Black "6...Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Nd7
{ is Black's third most popular move. In this move order, the second player can opt to get f6 in without first committing to castling short. }
7. Nc4 f6
{ Delaying ... O-O to first reinforce the center has been gaining in popularity. Karjakin and Wesley So have put the spotlight on this more flexible move order. }
8. c3
{ 8.O-O  is met by the immediate  8...Nf8  when Black quickly gets his knight to e6. }
8... O-O
{ 8...Nb6  9.b4  Bd6  10.Nxd6+  leads to similar play as the 9...Nb6 variation. }
9. O-O { Only now that Black has castled does White follow suit. } 9... Nb6 10.
b4
{ is an interesting continuation, gaining space on the queenside and kicking back Black's bishop. After extensive analysis, I concluded the text move sets Black more practical problems than the more popular 10. Be3 and 10. Na5 moves. }
10... Bd6
{ has been exclusively played in all 8 games that reached this position.   10...Be7Ν  is an inferior square for the bishop. White can force concessions with  11.Na5  tying Black down to the defense of the b7 pawn and intending to take control over the c5 square with Be3. This practically forces  11...c5  when White can play  12.Be3  anyhow.   12.Be3  The point is that taking twice on b4  12...cxb4  13.cxb4  Bxb4  fails to  14.Qb3++-  12...Nd7  13.a3⩲  White has the better game and can look to break with d4 at an opportune moment.   10...Nxc4Ν  has yet to be played and for good reason. After  11.bxc5  Na5  Black's knight is completely misplaced on a5. White can immediately target it with  12.Ba3  Re8  13.Bb4  b6  14.Bxa5  severely compromising Black's structure.  14...bxa5  15.h3±  stops ...Bg4. Black's queenside is riddled with weaknesses, giving White a clear advantage. The first player can look forward to breaking with d3-d4. }
11. Nxd6 cxd6
{ 11...Qxd6  is a precarious place for the queen, which finds itself exposed after  12.a4  12...a5  13.bxa5  Rxa5  14.Ba3  c5  15.d4!  Black is in trouble with Nd2-c4 coming next. }
12. a4
{ Next up is a5 to knock back Black's knight. White has a comfortable position with a big space advantage and can look to break with d3-d4.   For example  12...Be6  13.a5  Nc8  14.d4!  gives White good prospects. }
*

