1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Nd7
{ is Black's third most popular move. In this move order, the second player can opt to get f6 in without first committing to castling short. }
7. Nc4 f6 8. c3 Nf8
{ is very rare. This provocative move caught my attention when Goryachkina first played it versus Iljiushenok in the 2020 Russian Team Championship.   8...Nf8  9.d4  is the move Black was looking to provoke. After  9...exd4  10.cxd4  Black now has the tricky  10...Be6!  which easily equalized in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@52@@EndBracket@@ Iljiushenok,I @@StartBracket@@2539@@EndBracket@@-Goryachkina,A @@StartBracket@@2592@@EndBracket@@ Sochi 2020. }
9. Be3
{ Novel and strong. White provokes the second player to take on e3 which would improve the c4 knight's position. }
9... Bxe3 10. Nxe3
{ The trade on e3 improved the knight's position. d3-d4 is now back on the agenda. }
10... Ng6
{ is the best square for the knight. Placing it on e6 would have blocked the c8 bishop.   10...Qe7  is well met by the immediate central strike  11.d4!  with the point that  11...exd4  12.Nxd4  Qxe4?  is a serious mistake as after the simple  13.O-O  Ng6  14.Qb3+-  White is already winning. Black's king is stuck in the center and Re1 is coming next. }
11. d4
{ 11.h4  is premature. Black gets a better version of the text following  11...h5  12.d4  exd4  13.Nxd4  c5  14.Ndf5  Qxd1+  15.Rxd1  Kf7  16.Nd5  Bxf5  17.exf5  Rhe8+  when the inclusion of h4 h5 favors Black. }
11... exd4 12. Nxd4
{ White's extra space and well placed knights are enough for a small edge.   12...Qe7  is strongly met by  13.Qb3!  noting that  13...Qxe4  14.O-O-O  is terrible for Black with the king stuck in the center. White is already winning with Re1 coming next.   12...c5  is Black's only real try. Following  13.Ndf5  Qxd1+  14.Rxd1  Kf7  15.Nd5  Bxf5  16.exf5  Rhe8+  17.Kf1  Ne7  18.Ne3  White has a slight pull in this endgame. }
