1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Nd7
{ is Black's third most popular move. In this move order, the second player can opt to get f6 in without first committing to castling short. }
7. Nc4 f6
{ Delaying ...O-O to first reinforce the center has been gaining in popularity. Karjakin and Wesley So have put the spotlight on this more flexible move order. }
8. c3
{ 8.O-O  is met by the immediate  8...Nf8  when Black quickly gets his knight to e6. }
8... Nb6 9. b4 Bd6 10. Nxd6+
{ is the superior knight move.   10.Na5  is another interesting possibility that has recently been tested in a few games.  10...O-O   10...c5  was played by Giri. While not an outright mistake, it's usually best not to commit to an early ...c6-c5 which later proved to be Giri's undoing. Please refer to the middlegame section for more details.  11.Be3  was played in the game1/2 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2753@@EndBracket@@-Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2020 Here Black could have immediately reacted with  11...f5  with a balanced game. }
10... cxd6
{ does consolidate Black's structure, but at the same time fails to put any pressure on the d3 pawn. }
11. a4
{ This natural move was not considered in the book Grandmaster Repertoire: The Berlin Defence by Michael Roiz. White grabs space on the queenside and intends to kick back Black's knight with a5. }
11... Be6 12. a5 Nc8 13. d4
{ After expanding on the queenside, it's now time to strike in the center. }
13... Ne7 14. O-O
{ White has a big space advantage and is thus clearly for choice. The opposite-colored bishops don't forecast any drawing tendencies as the endgame is nowhere in sight. }
