1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ This chapter is dedicated to Black's alternatives to the mainline with4...Bc5.   We start by covering the unusual  4...Ne7  and  4...Bd6  moves and then focus on the solid  4...d6  .  With 4...d6, Black opts to keep the bishop inside the pawn chain. The second player is hoping to quickly develop with ...Be7, ...O-O and then look to break in the center with ...d5. }
5. O-O Be7 { This is Black's main move, clearing the way for ...O-O. } 6. c3
O-O 7. Re1
{ This is the tabiya of the 4...d6 Berlin, especially if Black is heading towards the Closed Ruy Lopez or the 6.d3 variation.   Here  7...a6  transposes into the 6...d6 line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2
{ Compared to the standard Closed Spanish position, White has played Bc2 in one go and hasn't yet committed to h3 @@StartBracket@@note that ...Bg4 is only ever a concern when White has played d2-d4, putting pressure on the center@@EndBracket@@.   Another difference is that we jave played d2-d3 as opposed to d2-d4. This does allow ...d6-d5, but White is also far more flexible. In this move-order, playing à la Chigorin or à la Breyer is imprudent.   For example, the Breyer-like  9...Nb8  would be too slow as after  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  we already have our bishop on c2, and we haven't committed to h3, which is not useful at the moment. Hence, White is a tempo up compared to the actual Breyer move-order  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bpnbppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc2  .   The Chigorin knight sortie  9...Na5  is also senseless as we have our bishop on c2 already.   In the Yates variation, White also doesn't waste a tempo on h3, but the difference is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bg4  10.d5  Na5  White has to spend time retreating the bishop to c2, ending up down a tempo compared to our move-order. }
