5... c6 6. Bc4
{ The bishop is superbly placed on c4, controlling d5 and eyeing the weak f7 pawn. Black will have to constantly be on the lookout for Ng5 from now on. }
6... Ng6
{ This is, surprisingly, Black's most popular move. I say surprisingly because this natural move is objectively terrible, the reason being that White can expand on the kingside with h4!   6...d6  7.O-O  h6  8.d4  is comfortably better for White. First and foremost,  8...Ng6??  loses on the spot to  9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Bxf7++-   Better is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2npp1/2pp1n1p/4p3/2BPP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qc7  and now  9.Nh4!  is very accurate. White prevents ...Ng6 when the f8 bishop is simply stuck. Note that  9...g6?  trying to fianchetto it fails to  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.f4!  blasting open the f-file while Black is undeveloped. White is already close to winning. }
7. h4
{ intending to kick back the knight h5. Black has no option to play ...h5 which gives up the g5 square. }
7... h5 8. Ng5 { The pressure on the f7 pawn forces Black to push ...d5. } 8...
d5 9. exd5 cxd5
{ This natural move doesn't work out tactically.   9...b5  may very well be Black's best move.  10.Bb3  cxd5  11.d4±  gave White a big advantage in the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Socko,B @@StartBracket@@2616@@EndBracket@@ -Luch,M @@StartBracket@@2447@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2014. }
10. Nxd5 { Boom, Black's center collapses! } 10... Nxd5 11. Qf3 Be6 12. Nxe6
fxe6 13. Bb5+ { White's bishops now chase down Black's king. } 13... Ke7 14.
Bg5+ Nf6 15. Qxb7+
{ Black's king is forced into no man's land.   White was already winning in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Karthikeyan, M @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@-Minko, D @@StartBracket@@2207@@EndBracket@@ Sitges 2021, which continued  15...Kd6  16.c4!  with the deadly threat of c5+.  16...Rc8  17.Qxa7+-  Black didn't last long, clickhere to see the rest of the game. }
