1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bd6
{ is yet another unusual 4th move alternative. Black pre-emptively defends the e5 pawn, anticipating Bxc6. If White foregoes the bishop for knight exchange, Black is planning to break in the center with ...d5 after ... O-O, ...Re8 and ...Bf8. }
5. Nbd2
{ A logical-developing move that carries the threat of Nc4 hitting Black's bishop and the e5 pawn. }
5... a6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nc4
{ As we've seen throughout the Key middlegame themes chapter, the knight stands superbly on c4. From this square, it pressures the e5 pawn and can later jump to a5 to soften up Black's queenside. }
7... Qe7
{ 7...Nd7  is far less common, the reason being that White can immediately break with  8.d4!  Qe7  9.O-O  O-O  10.Re1⩲  White had a comfortable edge, going on to win in1-0 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Aveskulov,V @@StartBracket@@2514@@EndBracket@@-Baryshpolets,A @@StartBracket@@2477@@EndBracket@@ Kharkov 2011.   7...Bg4?!  makes little sense as after  8.h3  the pressure on the e5 pawn forces Black to play  8...Bxf3   8...Bh5?  9.g4  Bg6  10.Nfxe5+-  wins material.  9.Qxf3±  Black has parted with the two bishops for no gain whatsoever. }
8. h3 { White rules out ...Bg4 before castling. } 8... O-O 9. O-O b5 10. Ne3
{ White has the upper hand in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Bachmann,A @@StartBracket@@2505@@EndBracket@@-Arias,L @@StartBracket@@2293@@EndBracket@@ Morelia 2008. The first player can look to undermine Black's queenside with a2-a4 and develop the c1 bishop via b2. A common theme in this structure is to meet ...Be6 with Ng5, where the knight is very annoying. Kicking it back with ...h6 dramatically weakens the f5 square, which White can exploit with Ne3-f5 or Nf3-h4-f5. }
