[Black "4...d6 5...a6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ With 4...d6, Black opts to keep the bishop inside the pawn chain. The second player is hoping to quickly develop with ...Be7, ...O-O and then look to break in the center with ...d5. }
5. O-O a6
{ This move forces White to give up the bishop for the knight. However, it comes at the cost of weakening Black's pawn structure and spending an entire tempo on ...a6, which is not terribly useful. }
6. Bxc6+
{ 6.Ba4?!  is no good here since the e5-pawn is protected. This allows Black to grab the bishop without damaging his pawn structure with  6...b5  7.Bb3  Na5  . }
6... bxc6 7. Re1
{ 7.d4  has been tried quite a few times at the top level with good results for White. For example, Nakamura and Karjakin used this move to score important wins against Carlsen and Aronian respectively. Nevertheless, the text move is a slightly better approach as the rook will be very useful on the e-file. }
7... c5 8. c3
{ Black's last move came with the obvious intention of preventing d4. However, we can get in anyway with this preparatory move. }
8... Be7
{ Simply developing - a move tried by Esipenko against Grishchuk in August 2021 }
9. d4 { White naturally continues with his plan of breaking in the center. }
9... cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11. Nxd4
{ The exchanges in the center led to an open game, which in principle would favor Black's bishop pair. However, the e7 bishop is completely restricted and Black has a number of weaknesses, meaning White has the better chances. }
11... Bd7
{ Logical, avoiding the knight invasion on c6. Note how clumsily placed Black's pieces are, we've already highlighted Black's buried bishop on e7, the d7 one is tied to the defense of the c6 pawn and finally the f6 knight is a mere spectator. }
12. Nc3
{ Developing the knight, controlling the e4-pawn and in some cases controlling the very important d5-square, which can become relevant should Black play ...c7-c5. }
12... O-O
{ Here, White has several ways to maintain a very slight but safe edge. } 13.
h3
{ White might as well start with this move as the first player needs to control the g4 square. Let's take stock of the current position: Black's minor pieces can barely move and hardly have any prospects. Moreover, the second player's queenside structure is compromised. Any pressure Black hopes to amount along the b-file is easily neutralized by b2-b3.   White can aim to slowly improve on the kingside with moves like Qf3 and Ne2-g3, increasing control over the f5 square. Top Indian player and Chessable author, Harikrishna, won a convincing game from this position in1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Harikrishna, P @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ -Oleksienko,M @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2020   13.Qf3  is also playable and was Grischuk's's choice vs Esipenko in 2021.  13...Re8  14.h3⩲  needs to play this move anyhow to control the g4-square. White is slightly better, with Esipenko struggling but eventually managing to hold in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2778@@EndBracket@@ -Esipenko,A @@StartBracket@@2716@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2021. }
