1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ With 4...d6, Black opts to keep the bishop inside the pawn chain. The second player is hoping to quickly develop with ...Be7, ...O-O and then look to break in the center with ...d5. }
5. O-O a6
{ This move forces White to give up the bishop for the knight. However, it comes at the cost of weakening Black's pawn structure and spending an entire tempo on ...a6, which is not terribly useful. }
6. Bxc6+
{ 6.Ba4?!  is no good here since the e5-pawn is protected. This allows Black to grab the bishop without damaging his pawn structure with  6...b5  7.Bb3  Na5  . }
6... bxc6 7. Re1
{ 7.d4  has been tried quite a few times at the top level with good results for White. For example, Nakamura and Karjakin used this move to score important wins against Carlsen and Aronian respectively. Nevertheless, the text move is a slightly better approach as the rook will be very useful on the e-file. }
7... c5 8. c3
{ Black's last move came with the obvious intention of preventing d4. However, we can get in anyway with this preparatory move. }
8... Bg4
{ is a more active approach than ...Be7, which was essayed by Rapport in 2017. }
9. h3 Bxf3
{ Taking on f3 doesn't make much sense as the entire point behind ... Bg4 was to pin the knight and thus make it harder for White to break with d4. }
10. Qxf3
{ White is clearly for choice with a better bishop and Black's numerous light-squared weaknesses.   A sample continuation runs  10...Be7  11.Be3  O-O  12.Nd2  Nd7  13.Nc4  Bg5  14.b4  Bxe3  15.Nxe3⩲  White has more space, the better pawn structure, and can look to exploit Black's weak light-squares. }
