{ With 4...d6, Black opts to keep the bishop inside the pawn chain. The second player is hoping to quickly develop with ...Be7, ...O-O and then look to break in the center with ...d5. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ This position bears several similarities to the Deferred Steinitz variation, which arises after 1. e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 Bd7. The main differences are that Black has omitted ...a6 and White has spent a tempo on d2-d3, as opposed to the usual plan of c2-c3 followed by d2-d4. While this is in Black's favor, the extra tempo we spent on d3 is not overly significant as the position is closed. }
6. Re1
{ 6.c3  is possible here, but we can opt for the more straightforward approach of breaking with d4 without a prior c3. }
6... g6 7. d4
{ It's possible to first support this pawn break with c2-c3. However, given that Black can't take on d4, it's stronger to push the d-pawn immediately. }
7... Bg7 8. d5 Nb8
{ Simply taking on d7 and following up with c4 + Nc3 is very much possible, but I like the funky }
9. c4
{ This might transpose back to 9.Bxd7 after O-O , but we should always take the chance to pose our opponents a tricky question. ... Bxb5 would open up the c-file in our favor after cxb5, when the c7 pawn would become a potential target. }
9... O-O
{ 9...c6  is inadvisable as it leaves Black with a series of structural weaknesses following  10.dxc6  bxc6  11.Ba4  The d6 and c6 pawns are very weak. }
10. Bxd7 Nbxd7 11. Nc3
{ Black's knight on d7 would much rather be on e7, from where it would support the f5 break and allow the f6 knight to drop back to d7. White had a stable advantage, going on to win a nice game in1-0 Karjakin, S @@StartBracket@@2757@@EndBracket@@ - Sakaev, K. @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ Jurmala 2015. }
