1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ With 4...d6, Black opts to keep the bishop inside the pawn chain. The second player is hoping to quickly develop with ...Be7, ...O-O and then look to break in the center with ...d5. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ This position bears several similarities to the Deferred Steinitz variation, which arises after 1. e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 Bd7. The main differences are that Black has omitted ...a6 and White has spent a tempo on d2-d3, as opposed to the usual plan of c2-c3 followed by d2-d4. While this is in Black's favor, the extra tempo we spent on d3 is not overly significant as the position is closed. }
6. Re1
{ 6.c3  is possible here, but we can opt for the more straightforward approach of breaking with d4 without a prior c3. }
6... g6 7. d4
{ It's possible to first support this pawn break with c2-c3. However, given that Black can't take on d4, it's stronger to push the d-pawn immediately. }
7... Bg7 8. d5 Ne7 9. Bd3
{ is practically a novelty. It's been played in a couple of engine vs engine games, but has yet to be tested in OTB or correspondence games.   9.Bxd7+  is very reasonable and White's main move. It leads to King's Indian type positions, where exchanging the light-squared bishops is usually in White's favor as it hinders Black's kingside initiative. Nevertheless, White will be much faster on the queenside and Black's position is fairly cramped, so keeping another pair of minor pieces on the board is certainly logical. }
9... O-O 10. c4 b6 11. Nc3 a5
{ A very logical way to White from immediately pushing the queenside pawns, but it won't deter us for long. }
12. a3 h6 13. Ra2
{ is certainly worth remembering. White moves the rook up a square to a2, where it's now defended by the knight, thus enabling b2-b4. }
13... Nh7 14. b4 f5 15. Nd2
{ Let's evaluate this position. Black's kingside play is very far away from being at all worrisome, while White is about to break with c4-c5. White can then try to induce Black to take on c5 with Nc4 or, more likely, push the c-pawn forward to c6. The latter will force Black to take on b4, otherwise the a5 pawn will be too weak. This will result in the opening of the a-file, which is greatly in White's favor.   Finally, Black will have to decide where to place the light-squared bishop. If the second player opts for e8, it won't contribute to the play on the kingside. More logical is to place it on c8, when White can look to exchange it off with the typical Nc3-b5-a7 maneuver, hitting the weak c7 pawn on the way. }
