10... Bf8
{ There are no better choices, as taking on d4 only helps White to get his knight to c3. }
11. d5 Ne7 12. Bxd7 Nxd7 13. c4
{ Novel and strong. White has a supercharged version of the King's Indian, as Black's position is very cramped and his minor pieces are not particularly well placed to start active operations on the kingside. }
13... f5
{ 13...g6  is just too slow, and White can clamp Black down with  14.g4!?  when ...f5 will be very hard to get in. Also great is  14.Nc3  f5  15.exf5  when Black has only weakened his position with ...g6. If the second player now takes back with the knight, the g6 pawn remains very weak while  15...gxf5  is strongly met by  16.g4!  when White will be the only one attacking on the kingside. }
