6. c3 O-O 7. Re1
{ This is the tabiya of the 4...d6 Berlin, especially if Black is heading towards the Closed Ruy Lopez or the 6.d3 variation.   Here  7...a6  transposes into the 6...d6 line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ We've landed in 6.d3 Spanish territory, which usually arises from the following move-order @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
8... Re8
{ Black delays moving the b-pawn, which makes perfect sense given that after  8...b5  9.Bc2  the bishop protects the e4 pawn. As such, White can go straight for Nf1 and push d4 without having to worry about the e4 pawn after the trade of the e5 and d4 pawns. By playing  8...Re8  Black sets his eyes on the e4 pawn with ...Bf8 to follow. This means White won't be able to go for Nf1 and the immediate d4. }
9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. d4
{ The typical  10.Nf1  is possible but after  10...h6  11.Ng3  Black solves all his problems with  11...d5  If White chooses to shatter Black's pawn structure with  12.exd5  Qxd5  13.Bxc6  bxc6  Black will continue with ...Nd7, ...c5, and ...Bb7 with good chances. }
10... b5 11. Bc2 Bg4
{ This is an improved version of the 9. d4 Yates Variation as White already has the light-squared bishop on c2. }
12. h3 Bh5 13. d5 Ne7
{ 13...Na5  makes little sense as White's bishop is already on c2. } 14. Nf1 c6
{ This is Black's typical break in the Yates Variation, but here his pieces are not well placed to support this. }
15. dxc6 Nxc6 16. g4
{ Breaks the pin and with Nh4 to come, White is clearly for choice.   A sample line runs  16...Bg6  17.Nh4  d5  is the only sensible move. Black needs to get rid of the d6 weakness.  18.Nxg6  hxg6  19.exd5  Qxd5  20.Qxd5  Nxd5  21.Be4  Rad8  22.a4±  White is better with the two bishops and pressure on Black's queenside. }
