{ It's now time to turn our attention to Black's main move 5...Be7, clearing the way for ...O-O. }
6. c3 O-O 7. Re1
{ This is the tabiya of the 4...d6 Berlin, especially if Black is heading towards the Closed Ruy Lopez or the 6.d3 variation.   Here  7...a6  transposes into the 6...d6 line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ We've landed in 6.d3 Spanish territory, which usually arises from the following move-order @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
8... Re8
{ Black can delay the move ...b5, which makes perfect sense given that after 8... b5 9. Bc2 the bishop protects the e4 pawn. As such, White can go straight for Nf1 and push d4 without having to worry about the e4 pawn after the trade of the e5 and d4 pawns. By playing 8...Re8, Black sets his eyes on the e4 pawn with .. .Bf8 to follow. This means White won't be able to go for Nf1 and the immediate d4. }
9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. d4 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. h3
{ Having stumbled upon a lot of transpositions, in the end I decided to go with this move. Here's why:   @@StartBracket@@a@@EndBracket@@  12.d5  is rather premature.  12...Nb8  13.b3  c6  14.c4  At first sight, this position may seem advantageous for White. However, Black's bishop is still on f8 and he hasn't yet committed to g7-g6. Moreover, a6-a5-a4 is coming soon, which will distract White from solely playing on the kingside.   @@StartBracket@@b@@EndBracket@@  12.a3  Nb8  13.b3   13.a4  This was our recommendation vs the Breyer with the difference that our h-pawn is on h2 instead of h3. Surprisingly, this makes all the difference. The following continuation is a great illustration of how subtle chess can be.  13...Nbd7  14.Bd3  In the actual Breyer, Black was forced to play ...c7-c6. But with the pawn on h2, here Black can actually strike with  14...d5!  15.axb5  The most logical move, biting the bullet.  15...dxe4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Bxe4  Nxe4  18.Rxe4  axb5  19.Rxa8  Qxa8  Up until here, every move has been practically forced.  20.Qe2  A natural move, creating a seemingly lethal pin along the e-file and simultaneously hitting the b5 pawn.  20...f5  21.Re3  e4!  The entire point is that  22.Qxb5?  fails to  22...exf3  23.Qxd7  Rxe3  Remarkably, if White's pawn were on h3 as opposed to h2, White could simply capture on e3 with the bishop and have a huge advantage. As it stands,  24.fxe3  is forced and after  24...Qa1  Black wins. A true testament of how fascinatingly deep chess can be!   13.b4  is perfectly playable, but Black can hold his own by going for the ...d5 break.  13...Nbd7  14.Bb2  Nb6  The best move, played by none other than Jan Gustafsson in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Needleman, A @@StartBracket@@2411@@EndBracket@@ -Gustafsson,J @@StartBracket@@2571@@EndBracket@@ Dos Hermanas 2004. Black successfully gets his dream breakthrough in. For example  15.h3  d5  Everything works out for Black after the following set of trades:  16.dxe5  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  dxe4  18.Bxe4  Bxe4  19.Rxe4  Qxd1+  20.Rxd1  Na4  21.Ba1  Nb6  The smoke has cleared and Black is holding his own.  13...Nbd7  14.Bb2  g6  15.a4   15.Bd3  is a very logical idea, trying to connect the rooks by putting the queen on c2. But once again Black is in time to break with ...d5.  15...Bg7  16.Qc2  d5!  Just in time!  17.exd5  Nxd5  18.dxe5  Nxe5  19.Nxe5  Nf4!  The only move but a sufficient one to equalize. The thing is, Black should avoid putting himself under a pin after White's Be4 @@StartBracket@@had Black taken on e5@@EndBracket@@.  20.Be4  Bxe4  21.Nxe4  Rxe5  22.Rad1  Qe7  23.c4  Re6  24.Bc1  Bh6  Black is in good shape.  15...Bg7  16.Bd3  Now it's important to note that this move allows  16...bxa4!   and not the passive  16...c6  which was played in 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Motylev,A @@StartBracket@@2649@@EndBracket@@ - Dominguez Perez, L  @@StartBracket@@2732@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015.  17.Rxa4  d5!  Black may soon take over the initiative, a scenario we should certainly avoid! }
12... g6
{ This is the only independent line that doesn't transpose into our repertoire vs the Zaitsev. But now that ...g7-g6 has been played, we can go for a favorable version of the d5-c4-b3 structure.   12...Nb8  transposes to the 13.a4 Variation of Breyer after  13.a4  Nbd7  14.Bd3  .   12...h6  transposes to our recommeded line in the Zaitsev after  13.a3 }
13. d5 Nb8 14. b3 c6 15. c4
{ White has a pleasant space advantage and it certainly for choice. For more details on White's plans, please refer to the typical middlegames chapter. }
