8... Re8
{ Black delays moving the b-pawn, which makes perfect sense given that after  8...b5  9.Bc2  the bishop protects the e4 pawn. As such, White can go straight for Nf1 and push d4 without having to worry about the e4 pawn after the trade of the e5 and d4 pawns. By playing  8...Re8  Black sets his eyes on the e4 pawn with ...Bf8 to follow. This means White won't be able to go for Nf1 and the immediate d4. }
9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. d4 b5 11. Bc2 exd4 12. cxd4 Nb4
{ As a rule of thumb, this knight jump does not work when the a-pawn is still on a2 @@StartBracket@@as opposed to a4@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Bb1 c5 14. d5
{ The big threat of a2-a3 to trap the knight forces Black to make concessions. }
14... c4
{ 14...a5  this is logical, liberating the a6-square for the knight but after  15.a3  Na6  16.b3±  Black's queenside is very vulnerable as the pawns are hard to protect and can't be easily pushed. }
15. a3 Nd3
{ Dropping in on d3 was the main idea behind 14...c4. However, things don't turn out well for Black following... }
16. Bxd3 cxd3 17. b4 Bg4 18. Bb2 { White will slowly round up the d3-pawn. } *

