1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ is Black's main alternative to 4... Bc5. } 5. O-O Be7
{ It's now time to turn our attention to Black's main move 5...Be7, clearing the way for ...O-O. }
6. c3 O-O 7. Re1
{ This is the tabiya of the 4...d6 Berlin, especially if Black is heading towards the Closed Ruy Lopez or the 6.d3 variation.   Here  7...a6  transposes into the 6...d6 line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ We've landed in 6.d3 Spanish territory, which usually arises from the following move-order @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
8... Re8
{ Black delays moving the b-pawn, which makes perfect sense given that after  8...b5  9.Bc2  the bishop protects the e4 pawn. As such, White can go straight for Nf1 and push d4 without having to worry about the e4 pawn after the trade of the e5 and d4 pawns. By playing  8...Re8  Black sets his eyes on the e4 pawn with ...Bf8 to follow. This means White won't be able to go for Nf1 and the immediate d4. }
9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. d4 b5 11. Bc2 exd4 12. cxd4 Bg4
{ This is a slightly different version of one of the 9... Re8 variations, where the moves Nf1 and ...h6 were included. }
13. h3
{ The text is slightly stronger than  13.Nf1  which was tried in Nepomniachtchi, I - Magnus, C chess. com INT 2020. The point is that by keeping the knight on d2, we can kick the bishop as ...Bxf3 is met by Nxf3 maintaining a compact structure. }
13... Bh5 14. Nf1 Bxf3
{ Otherwise White would have forced Black to make the concession with Ng3 anyway. }
15. gxf3 g6
{ Giving the bishop some breathing space.   15...Nb4  is not satisfactory as after  16.Bb1  c5  17.d5  a5  18.a3  Na6  White now has  19.a4!  bxa4   19...Nc7  is met by  20.Bg5⩲  20.Bc2⩲  A final, important move. Instead of taking on a4 with either of the major pieces, White's light-squared bishop is coming to this square. White's kingside structure is of no concern and, if anything, gives the first player chances to attack Black's king. }
16. d5
{ Gains space with a healthy advantage. The two bishops and the extra space will make themselves felt.   A sample line runs  16...Nb4  17.Bb1  a5  18.a3  Na6  19.Bd3  Qd7  20.Ng3  Nc5  21.Bf1↑  White is undoubtedly for choice. Note that  21...a4  is well met by  22.Bg5!  gaining a tempo and clearing the way for Rc1.  22...Bg7  23.Rc1  Nb3  24.Rc6  White managed to get his rook out of the corner, and now Black has to play very accurately to stay in the game. The machine suggests  24...h5!?  25.Ne2  The b5 pawn is about to get under serious pressure with Nc3 coming.  25...Nh7  26.Be3  Bxb2  27.Nc3  Bxa3  28.Nxb5  Bb4  29.Re2⩲  Black's a-pawn isn't going anywhere as the b3 knight needs protection. White will soon restore material equality and emerge with a slight edge. }
