1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ is Black's main alternative to 4... Bc5. } 5. O-O Be7
{ It's now time to turn our attention to Black's main move 5... Be7, clearing the way for ...O-O. }
6. c3 O-O 7. Re1
{ This is the tabiya of the 4...d6 Berlin, especially if Black is heading towards the Closed Ruy Lopez or the 6.d3 variation.   Here  7...a6  transposes into the 6...d6 line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1pppbppp/p1n2n2/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.d3  d6  7.c3  O-O  8.Re1  . }
7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2
{ Compared to the standard Closed Spanish position, White has played Bc2 in one go and hasn't yet committed to h3 @@StartBracket@@note that ...Bg4 is only ever a concern when White has played d2-d4, putting pressure on the center@@EndBracket@@.   Another difference is that we've played d2-d3 as opposed to d2-d4. This does allow ...d6-d5, but White is also far more flexible. In this move-order, playing à la Chigorin or à la Breyer is imprudent.   For example, the Breyer-like  9...Nb8  would be too slow as after  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  we already have our bishop on c2, and we haven't committed to h3, which is not useful at the moment. Hence, White is a tempo ahead over the actual Breyer move-order  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bpnbppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc2  .   The Chigorin knight sortie  9...Na5  is also senseless as we have our bishop on c2 already.   In the Yates variation, White also doesn't waste a tempo on h3, but the difference is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bg4  10.d5  Na5  White has to spend time retreating the bishop to c2, ending up down a tempo compared to our move-order. }
9... d5
{ This has to be the best approach, taking advantage of the fact that White went Bc2 in one go. The downside of having the bishop on c2 instead of b3 is that White has lost control over the d5 square. }
10. Nbd2 d4
{ has been played several times by Aronian and thus warrants some attention. }
11. cxd4
{ This is the best move in my opinion, it's important to first flick in cxd4 before going Nb3. The reason is that   11.Nb3  Bg4  12.h3  Bh5  13.cxd4  We have been following Anand, V - Aronian, L 2017, where Aronian missed  13...Bxf3!  14.Qxf3  Funnily enough, there was another game that reached this position, Annaberdiev, M - Pantzar, M 2019, and once again Black missed his chance to equalize with  14...Nxd4  15.Nxd4  Qxd4=  with no problems whatsoever. }
11... Nxd4
{ This approach is objectively quite dubious but White does need to know what to do. Careless play can quickly lead to disaster. }
12. Nxe5 Ng4 { is Black's most testing move, forcing White to be precise with }
13. Nef3
{ This is the only move to fight for an advantage!   13.Nxg4  is no good as the c2 bishop drops after  13...Bxg4  14.Qxg4??  Nxc2-+ }
13... f5 14. h3 Nxf2 { Black has to bite the bullet! } 15. Kxf2 fxe4 16. Bb3+
{ It's important to flick in this check before taking on e4. Why so? Well, Black intended to give a check on h4 and pick up the e1 rook. Our queen is essential in the defense of our kingside and should thus not be tied up defending the light-squared bishop. Note that if Black takes on b3, White will be able to give an intermediate check once again by recapturing with the queen. The generalities above are useful but there's nothing like checking a few concrete variations to get the full picture:   16.Nxe4  Bh4+  17.Kg1  Since Black's king was not forced to the corner, the second player can use the following tactic to generate counterplay:  17...Rxf3!  18.Bg5  This is what we will be using in the Bb3+ Kh8 variation mentioned below.  18...Bxg5  19.Nxg5   19.gxf3  Doesn't help either as after  19...Bf4  Black's attack is tremendous.  19...Qxg5  This would not have been possible had we given a check on b3, forcing Black's king to h8, when Re8 now would be checkmate! Giving a check on b3 now with  20.Bb3+  is too little too late as Black has the extra option of playing  20...Kf8  when White, being a piece down, can resign. }
16... Kh8 17. Nxe4 { Now and only now do we take on e4 with the knight. } 17...
Bh4+ 18. Kg1 Nxf3+
{ 18...Rxf3  With the king on h8, this move does not work!  19.Bg5!  Bxg5  20.Nxg5  White's current threat is Nf7+ with a fork not to mention the rook on f3 is hanging. Importantly  20...Qxg5  is not possible due to  21.Re8+  with checkmate to come! This is why we played 16. Bb3+! }
19. gxf3 Bxe1 20. Qxe1
{ White has two minor pieces for a rook, which is usually sufficient for an edge. Granted White's structure with isolated, hanging pawns on d3, f3 and h3, is far from impressive. Nevertheless, Black is unable to take any of them due to the huge threat of Ng5-f7. Certainly messy, but things do work out concretely for White!   Until now, everything has been basically completely forced. Black has to find the following ingenious move to survive:  20...a5!  A brilliant idea, preparing to swing the rook over to attack White's exposed king.   20...Qxd3?  This, on the other hand, is clearly asking for trouble.. .  21.Be3+-  with the threat of Rd1, Black is going to get crushed very soon.   20...Rxf3?  is also no good as after  21.Ng5  Rf6  22.Qe5  Bb7  23.Be3±  White has brought all his pieces into the game. Soon, it'll be Black's king feeling the heat.  21.Bg5  Qd7  22.Qe3  Ra6   Instead, if Black wastes time by taking the pawn on h3 with  22...Qxh3  23.Rf1  White gets enough time to regroup, and Black does not have enough pieces to attack our king.  23.f4  Intending Bd1-h5 if ...Rg6 comes. White also safeguards the h3 pawn laterally, enabling the king to hide on h2 if need be @@StartBracket@@without having to worry about ...Qxh3 ideas@@EndBracket@@.  23...Rg6  24.Bd1  h6  25.Bh5  Rc6  26.Bh4⩲  The position remains complicated but White has done a great job activating all his minor pieces. With precise play, White has good winning chances. }
