{ An interesting, trendy move. White takes control over the g4 square and asks Black to come up with a plan.   12.a4  or  12.Qe2  are twice as popular, but objectively not as strong. }
12... Bc5 13. a4 Ba7
{ And here, instead of Karjakin's  14.Nf1  , I prefer gaining space on the queenside with }
14. b4
{ 14.Ng5  to kick back Black's bishop is an interesting alternative. Following  14...Bc8  15.Qe2  White has some slight queenside pressure. Note that  15...h6  is simply met by  16.Ngf3 }
14... Ne8
{ Black's knight is headed to c4, attempting to exploit the main downside of b2-b4. }
15. Qe2
{ A typical maneuver, White removes the queen from the d-file in order to reroute the d2 knight without exchanging queens.   Importantly  15...Nd6  16.Nf1  Nc4  is well answered by  17.Ng5!  forces the e6 bishop back, leaving the c4 knight exposed to Bb3. }
