7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2
{ Compared to the standard Closed Spanish position, White has played Bc2 in one go and hasn't yet committed to h3 @@StartBracket@@note that ...Bg4 is only ever a concern when White has played d2-d4, putting pressure on the center@@EndBracket@@.   Another difference is that we've played d2-d3 as opposed to d2-d4. This does allow ...d6-d5, but White is also far more flexible. In this move-order, playing à la Chigorin or à la Breyer is imprudent.   For example, the Breyer-like  9...Nb8  would be too slow as after  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  we already have our bishop on c2, and we haven't committed to h3, which is not useful at the moment. Hence, White is a tempo ahead over the actual Breyer move-order  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bpnbppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N1P/PP1N1PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc2  .   The Chigorin knight sortie  9...Na5  is also senseless as we have our bishop on c2 already.   In the Yates variation, White also doesn't waste a tempo on h3, but the difference is that after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/3PP3/1BP2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bg4  10.d5  Na5  White has to spend time retreating the bishop to c2, ending up down a tempo compared to our move-order. }
9... d5
{ This has to be the best approach, taking advantage of the fact that White went Bc2 in one go. The downside of having the bishop on c2 instead of b3 is that White has lost control over the d5 square. }
10. Nbd2 dxe4 { This is by far Black's most common move. } 11. dxe4 Be6 12. h3
{ An interesting move, trendy move. White takes control over the g4 square and asks Black to come up with a plan.   12.a4  or 12. Qe2 are twice as popular, but objectively not as strong. }
12... Nd7
{ Play is most likely going to take place on the queenside. As such, Black prepares to transfer the knight there. Moreover, by clearing the f6 square, Black can now reinforce the e5 pawn with . ..f7-f6 if need be. }
13. Nf1 Nc5
{ This was the continuation chosen in the high-profile gameCarlsen, M - Aronian, L Bilbao 2011   13...Nb6  is also possible, when White continues development in standard fashion.  14.Qe2  Bc4   14...Qc8  15.Ne3  featured in the following engine vs engine game that White won convincingly:1-0 @@StartBracket@@77@@EndBracket@@ 77 Equinox 3.20 64-bit 3102-Andscacs 0.88 64-bit 3111 CCRL 2016  15.Qe3  f6  16.Nh4⩲  followed by Qg3 and Nf5 with a slight initiative. While there's nothing obviously wrong with Black's position, White's side is far easier to play. }
14. Qe2
{ As usual, we prefer keeping the queens on the board and thus possible future kingside attacking chances.   14.Ne3  This was the actual continuation of the aforementioned game. If you like to play slightly dry endgames, this is a nice choice.  14...Qxd1  15.Rxd1  f6  16.Nd5  White has got a very safe and slight edge, and he can push forever, even though if Black is precise he can hold without any doubt.  16...Bd6  17.Be3  Nb7□  Note that   17...Nd7?  is no good as it allows to White quickly get the upper hand. Following  18.Bb3  Rfe8  19.Nxc7  Bxc7  20.Rxd7+-  Black was busted inGallagher, J - Codenotti, M Balatonszarszo 2017.  18.Nh4!?  is Leela's top choice, and a possible improvement over Magnus' 18.b4.  18...g6  19.Bh6  Rf7  20.b4↑  with a slight initiative for White. }
14... Bc4 15. Qe3
{ White's queen may look slightly awkward on e3, but this is only temporary. Black's position is by no means easy to handle as the following sample continuation illustrates.   15...a5  Gaining space on the queenside is likely Black's best plan.  16.Ng3  a4  17.Nf5  The knight has made its way to the optimal f5 outpost.  17...f6  18.Nd2  Be6  19.Qe2  makes way for the typical maneuver Nf1-e3 with the better chances. }
