1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy Lopez is a first rate variation in the Spanish. Anand brought it into the limelight when he essayed it in the 1995 PCA Candidates against Kamsky and in the 1995 World Championship match versus Kasparov. Nowadays, this defense is played by a large subset of the world's elite such as Carlsen, So and Mamedyarov. With perfect play, Black is objectively equal everywhere but this doesn't mean White cannot pose problems in practical games. Black's main idea is to use use the time White will take to regain the pawn to gain a foothold in the center. }
6. d4 exd4
{ is outright bad. Opening up the e-file with the king still in the center cannot be recommended. }
7. Re1 d5
{ Reinforcing the knight on e4 is Black's only way of staying in the game. } 8.
Nxd4
{ Black has big problems dealing with the pin. The only trick White needs to be aware of is ...Bd6 with ideas of ...Bxh2. }
8... Bd6 9. Nxc6 Bxh2+ 10. Kh1
{ Unfortunately for Black, chess is not checkers and White is under no obligation to capture the bishop.   And not  10.Kxh2??  when Black can escape with a perpetual after  10...Qh4+  11.Kg1  Qxf2+  12.Kh2  Qh4+= }
10... Qh4 11. Rxe4+
{ is the winning shot. Black has no option but to take on e4. } 11... dxe4 12.
Qd8+ { forces the queens off the board and gives White a decisive advantage. }
12... Qxd8 13. Nxd8+ Kxd8 14. Kxh2
{ The dust has settled and White emerged with two minor pieces for a rook and a pawn. The first player is clearly better and Black has a very hard task ahead of him. Funnily enough, this position featured in the 2020 Netflix hit show The Queen's Gambit. Avid fans will recall that Black ended up blundering mate in one there. }
*

