1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy Lopez is a first rate variation in the Spanish. Anand brought it into the limelight when he essayed it in the 1995 PCA Candidates against Kamsky and in the 1995 World Championship match versus Kasparov. Nowadays, this defense is played by a large subset of the world's elite such as Carlsen, So and Mamedyarov. With perfect play, Black is objectively equal everywhere but this doesn't mean White cannot pose problems in practical games. Black's main idea is to use use the time White will take to regain the pawn to gain a foothold in the center. }
6. d4 Be7
{ used to be popular all the way back in the 90s. It's very rare nowadays although a couple of super-GMs have played it on occasion. Mamedyarov used it successfully vs Aronian in the 2018 Batumi Olympiad and Magnus Carlsen also gave it a shot in the 2019 London Chess Classic with two draws against MVL. }
7. Re1 b5
{ is the only move you're bound to encounter in practice.   7...f5?  only weakens Black's position.  8.dxe5  O-O  9.Nc3!  Nxc3  10.bxc3±  gives White a big advantage. White's has more space, superior central control and is ahead in development. }
8. Rxe4 d5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Rxe5 bxa4
{ is a position that arises pretty much by force when Black plays 6...Be7. We must play energetically to exploit our lead in development. If Black is given enough time to complete development, he'll be fine. }
11. Qe2
{ After extensive analysis, we concluded this is White's strongest move. The pressure on the e7 bishop rules out ...O-O and the plan is to quickly bring the queenside pieces into the game with Nc3, Bf4 and Rae1. }
11... c6
{ was Magnus's choice vs Maxime Vachier Lagrave in the 2019 London Chess Classic. }
12. Nc3
{ is stronger than MVL's choice of 12. Bd2. The dark-squared bishop will be far better placed on f4 than on d2. }
12... Ra7 { Black covers the e7 bishop laterally so he can finally castle. }
13. Bf4 { clears the way for Re1. } 13... O-O 14. Re1
{ White is fully centralized and has complete control over the critical e-file. }
14... Be6
{ Black blocks the e-file and is now ready to displace our rook with ...Bf6/ d6.   14...Bd6??  is not possible due to  15.Re8!  Rxe8  16.Qxe8+  Qxe8  17.Rxe8+  Bf8  18.Bd6+-  when Black can resign. }
15. Re3 a3 16. bxa3
{ gives White a clear advantage. We are a pawn up and every single one of our pieces is more active than Black's counterpart. }
