1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy Lopez is a first rate variation in the Spanish. Anand brought it into the limelight when he essayed it in the 1995 PCA Candidates against Kamsky and in the 1995 World Championship match versus Kasparov. Nowadays, this defense is played by a large subset of the world's elite such as Carlsen, So and Mamedyarov. With perfect play, Black is objectively equal everywhere but this doesn't mean White cannot pose problems in practical games. Black's main idea is to use use the time White will take to regain the pawn to gain a foothold in the center. }
6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 Be7
{ is an old forgotten line that I doubt will ever be revived. White gets a pleasant advantage with natural moves starting with }
8. dxe5 O-O 9. Bd5
{ White installs the bishop on the center of the board with a tempo on Black's knight. The bishop is extremely active on d5, complicating Black's task of completing development. }
9... Nc5 10. Nc3 Rb8 { Stepping out of the pin makes sense. } 11. Re1
{ White reinforces the e5 pawn. Having established a foothold in the center, the first player can now turn his attention to the queenside. Black's ...b5 pawn is about to be undermined with a2-a4. }
11... Bb7 12. a4 b4 13. Ne4 Nxe4
{ This was all seen in the game1/2-1/2  @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Ligterink,G @@StartBracket@@2440@@EndBracket@@-Rasmussen,L Middlesborough @@StartBracket@@Teesside@@EndBracket@@ 1978. Now the novel }
14. Bxe4
{ is stronger than 14. Rxe4, which was played in the aforementioned game. The bishop is very powerful on e4 and White is ready to follow up with Qd3 to provoke weaknesses in Black's kingside. }
14... d6 15. Qd3
{ gives White a clear advantage. There's no convenient way of covering h7 as ...g6 weakens too many dark squares and ...h6 runs into e6!   For example  15...h6  16.e6!  fxe6  17.Bxh6  gxh6  18.Bxc6  Bxc6  19.Qg6++-  is lights out. Black's king won't survive this onslaught, a nice sample continuation being  19...Kh8  20.Qxh6+  Kg8  21.Qg6+  Kh8  22.Qh5+  Kg7  23.Qg4+  Kf7  24.Qxe6+  Kg7  25.Qg4+  Kh7  26.Nd4+-  Black is defenseless against the ROVER @@StartBracket@@rook up and over!@@EndBracket@@ Re3-h3 and Nd4-e6. }
