[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy Lopez is a first rate variation in the Spanish. Anand brought it into the limelight when he essayed it in the 1995 PCA Candidates against Kamsky and in the 1995 World Championship match versus Kasparov. Nowadays, this defense is played by a large subset of the world's elite such as Carlsen, So and Mamedyarov. With perfect play, Black is objectively equal everywhere but this doesn't mean White cannot pose problems in practical games. Black's main idea is to use use the time White will take to regain the pawn to gain a foothold in the center. }
6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5
{ It's now time to turn our attention to Black's main move. } 8. Nxe5
{ is a very interesting alternative to the super theoretical mainline with 8. dxe5. Black is objectively fine after both moves and the mainline comes with a lot more theory. This led us to recommend the text, which is far more practical and your opponent is much less likely to be booked up in this rarer line. As we're about to see, White can certainly pose a number of practical problems.   The advantage of playing Nxe5 is that the knight is no longer in the way of f4-f5, which oftentimes results in a strong kingside attack. The downside is that Black can create a stronger center by expanding with ...c7-c5 later on. }
8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Bb7
{ The bishop is completely misplaced on b7, blocked in by the d5 pawn. The only logical idea of putting the bishop here is to be able to drop back the knight to e6.   9...Nc5??  blunders  10.Bxd5+− }
10. c3 { creates a square for the bishop on c2 in case of ...Nc5. } 10... Nc5
11. Bc2 Ne6 12. f4
{ Black's knight reached the e6 square but it's about to be displaced with f4-f5. The second player is in trouble here. }
