8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Be6
{ is a more sensible square for the light-squared bishop than b7. } 10. Be3 Bc5
{ is a dubious continuation. Exchanging the dark-squared bishops is clearly in White's favor. }
11. Bxc5 Nxc5 12. Qd4
{ White centralizes the queen with tempo. No matter where the knight goes, Black is already in serious trouble. }
12... Nb7
{ with the idea ...c5 is playable. The knight is, however, misplaced on b7. }
13. c3 c5
{ 13...O-O  leads to similar play. After  14.Qe3!  c5  15.Rd1⩲  White has good pressure down the d-file. }
14. Qe3 Rc8 15. Nd2
{ White was slightly better in the game1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@78@@EndBracket@@ Morais,G @@StartBracket@@2323@@EndBracket@@-Vuillemin,G @@StartBracket@@2237@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2010   While White's advantage proved insufficient in a correspondence game, the first player has excellent chances in a practical OTB game. White can look to expand in the center with f2-f4 and, whenever Black castles kingside, Qd3 + Bc2 will force Black to weaken his kingside. }
