10... Nxd2 11. Qxd2
{ is half as popular as  11.Bxd2  but far stronger. This rare move was one of the main reasons I decided to recommend 8. Nxe5. What's the point? The idea is that White now has the option of targeting Black's kingside with c3, Bc2 and Qd3 - an attacking scheme that would not be available had the bishop been developed to d2.   11.Bxd2  I failed to find any way of putting pressure on Black's position in this variation. The mainline of my analysis went  11...Be7!  12.Qh5  Be6  13.c3  Qd7  14.Bg5  Bg4!  15.Qh4  Bc5=  when Black has no problems.  This recapture was not considered in the book Grandmaster Repertoire: Open Spanish by GM Victor Mikhalevski. }
