[Black "4...Bc5 overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5
{ has recently become somewhat trendy. This line has seen an uptick in popularity in large part due to Jorden Van Foreest. The strong Dutch GM and theoretician essayed it with great success in the 2020 Wijk ann zee tournament and in a variety of online tournaments.   This variation was first analyzed by Alois Fink in Österreichische Schachzeitung in 1956 and in Wiener Schach Nachrichten in 1979. It was named The Graz Defense. This early bishop sortie can transpose into the Møller or even the Modern Arkhangelsk if Black goes Nf6. However, bringing the bishop out on move 4 usually signals Black is aiming for Cozio-like setup with ...Nge7-g6. The only way to challenge Black's configuration is to expand in the center with c3-d4 at the right moment. We often get a space advantage and, with the precise play, can count on a slight pull. }
5. O-O
{ After extensive analysis, I concluded this is the most challenging continuation.   5.c3  immediately preparing d4 has been tried. The problem is that after  5...Nge7  6.d4  exd4  7.cxd4  Black now has the disruptive check  7...Bb4+=  Best play results in an endgame where Black has been holding his own. A relatively recent example is½-½ @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021, where Jorden held his Dutch compatriot to a draw. I didn't find any significant improvements for White. }
*

