[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Møller & others"]
[Black "4...Bc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5
{ has recently become trendy. This line has seen an uptick in popularity in large part due to Jorden Van Foreest. The strong Dutch GM and theoretician essayed it with great success in the 2020 Wijk ann zee tournament and in a variety of online tournaments. This line was first analyzed by Alois Fink in Österreichische Schachzeitung in 1956 and in Wiener Schach Nachrichten in 1979. It was named The Graz Defense. This early bishop sortie can transpose into the Møller or even the Modern Arkhangelsk if Black goes Nf6. However, bringing the bishop out on move 4 usually signals Black is aiming for Cozio-like setup with ...Nge7-g6. The only way to challenge Black's configuration is to expand in the center with c3-d4. We often get a space advantage and, with the precise play, we can count on a slight pull. }
5. O-O
{ After extensive analysis, I concluded this is the most challenging continuation.   5.c3  immediately preparing d4 has been tried. The problem is that after  5...Nge7  6.d4  exd4  7.cxd4  Black now has the disruptive check  7...Bb4+=  Best play results in an endgame where Black has been holding his own. A relatively recent example is½-½ @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021, where Jorden held his Dutch compatriot to a draw. I didn't find any significant improvements for White. }
5... Nge7 6. c3 Ng6 7. d4 Ba7 8. Bg5
{ is the only way to fight for an advantage. We provoke ...f7-f6 to create holes in Black's kingside. }
8... f6 9. Be3 O-O
{ At this stage, Aryan Tari was tempted by the d-pawn push d5-d6 and ended up losing in0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Tari, A @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@-Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021.   Far better is }
10. Nbd2
{ White does best in simply developing and enjoying the space advantage. }
10... d6 11. Re1 Kh8
{ Black will have to play this move sooner or later. Otherwise, the king will find itself exposed along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
12. h3
{ Takes control over the g4 square and limits the activity of Black's pieces. This is the strategy White should employ. Direct attacks don't work as Black's position is very solid and hard to break. }
12... exd4
{ Nabaty Tamir played this line twice but didn't have good results. He lost to Dominguez and drew a 2494. The simplest route towards an advantage is to trade a pair of knights with }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4
{ Dominguez played  14.Bxd4  and went on to defeat Nabaty. However, it's better to keep the dark-squared bishops on the board since Black's bishop on a7 isn't doing much. }
14... f5
{ is the most logical continuation.   Alternatively  14...c5  is well met by  15.Nf3  Be6  and now the simple  16.Bc2  gives White a pleasant advantage. }
15. Nf3
{ An important move to remember. White is clearly better and threatening Bg5 to trap Black's queen.   Black's best is to trade a pair of knights with  15...Nh4  White has several good options at this point, my preference being  16.exf5  b5  17.Nxh4  Qxh4  18.Bc2  Bxf5  19.Bxf5  Rxf5  20.a4!  creating weaknesses in Black's camp. White is undoubtedly better. }
