5... Nge7 6. c3 Ng6 7. d4 Ba7 8. Bg5
{ is the only way to fight for an advantage. We provoke ...f7-f6 to create holes in Black's kingside. }
8... f6 9. Be3 O-O
{ At this stage, Aryan Tari was tempted by the d-pawn push d5-d6 and ended up losing in0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Tari, A @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@-Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021.   Far better is }
10. Nbd2
{ White does best in simply developing and enjoying the space advantage. }
10... d6 11. Re1 Kh8
{ will have to play this move sooner or later. Otherwise, the king will find itself exposed along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
12. h3
{ Takes control over the g4 square and limits the activity of Black's pieces. This is the strategy White should employ. Direct attacks don't work as Black's position is very solid and hard to break. }
12... Bd7
{ I had this interesting line in one of my opening files, which was later played in ½-½  @@StartBracket@@85@@EndBracket@@ Ter Sahakyan, S @@StartBracket@@2640@@EndBracket@@-Indjic, A @@StartBracket@@2604@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. Black managed to draw the game but didn't find the right path.   12...Bd7  The idea Black missed and the whole point of 12...Bd7 is to be able to meet a careless move like  13.Nf1  played in the aforementioned game with  13...exd4  14.cxd4  d5!  Bingo! This is the key resource, the point being that after  15.exd5  Nb4  White is now regretting having retreated the knight to f1.  16.Bb3  reinforcing the d5 pawn is well answered by  16...Bb5!  17.a4  Be8  and Black is in great shape. }
13. Rc1
{ is an excellent prophylactic move. It prevents Black from getting in 13...exd4 followed by 14...d5. }
13... Qe8
{ Black's best is to just sit passively, and White will simply avoid from any tricks by just tucking the bishop back to c2. }
14. Bc2 Nce7
{ is the best course of action. Black holds tight, basically claiming his position is rock-solid.   The novel  14...Nd8  was recommended by GM Mihail Marin in the Modern Chess Database Ruy Lopez with 3...a6 and 4...Bc5 - Complete Repertoire for Black. White can get the upper hand by expanding on the queenside with  15.b4!  Ne6  16.Nf1  Nef4  17.Ng3⩲  with ideas of Nf5 and a2-a4. }
15. Nf1 Rd8 16. Ng3
{ Objectively, Black is fine and Lc0 only gives White a tiny advantage due to the extra space. Notwithstanding, White is far more comfortable and is essentially playing for two results. A possible plan is to expand on the queenside, opening up another front of attack. }
