1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ The Møller Defense is named after Jorgen Møller, who first analyzed it in Tidskrift för Schack. The idea of this move is not to play ...b7-b5 but rather to drop back the bishop to a7. }
6. c3 { As usual, we prepare the d4 advance when Black puts his bishop on c5. }
6... O-O
{ The so-called Carlsen's Møller, mainly because Carlsen played this successfully in a number of games recently. }
7. d4
{ We're at a crossroads now: Black can either drop the bishop back to b6 or a7. }
7... exd4
{ is clearly asking for trouble. White takes full control over the center with }
8. cxd4 Ba7 { followed by } 9. e5 Nd5 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3
{ White has a huge space advantage while Black's pieces are miserable. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Møller & others"]
[Black "5...Bc5 Møller 6...O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ The Møller Defense is named after Jorgen Møller, who first analyzed it in Tidskrift för Schack. The idea of this move is not to play ...b7-b5 but rather to drop back the bishop to a7. }
6. c3 { As usual, we prepare the d4 advance when Black puts his bishop on c5. }
6... O-O
{ The so-called Carlsen's Møller, mainly because Carlsen played this successfully in a number of games recently. }
7. d4
{ We're at a crossroads now: Black can either drop the bishop back to b6 or a7. }
7... Bb6
{ Retreating to b6 can lead to different play than ... Ba7. In certain variations, White's f3 knight ends up taking on c6 when Nxa7 is no longer possible. In general, our approach remains unchanged. }
8. Bg5
{ is the most popular continuation. It's very logical, pinning the knight on f6 and thus threatening to take on e5 without allowing ...Nxe4. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 g5
{ is terrible timing. For this to work, Black usually needs to precede it by ...d6. Here it simply doesn't work due to }
10. Nxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5
{ when the e5 pawn cannot be reinforced. 11 moves in and White is already winning.   11...d6  is too little too late. White wins on the spot with  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Qxd8  Rxd8  15.Bxf6+-  with two pawns to the good   Alternatively  11...exd4  is strongly met by the intermezzo  12.Bxc6!  dxc6  13.Qf3  Kg7  14.e5+-  winning the f6 knight. Black is busted. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Møller & others"]
[Black "5...Bc5 Møller 6...O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ The Møller Defense is named after Jorgen Møller, who first analyzed it in Tidskrift för Schack. The idea of this move is not to play ...b7-b5 but rather to drop back the bishop to a7. }
6. c3 { As usual, we prepare the d4 advance when Black puts his bishop on c5. }
6... O-O
{ The so-called Carlsen's Møller, mainly because Carlsen played this successfully in a number of games recently. }
7. d4
{ We're at a crossroads now: Black can either drop the bishop back to b6 or a7. }
7... Bb6
{ Retreating to b6 can lead to different play than ... Ba7. In certain variations, White's f3 knight ends up taking on c6 when Nxa7 is no longer possible. In general, our approach remains unchanged. }
8. Bg5
{ is the most popular continuation. It's very logical, pinning the knight on f6 and thus threatening to take on e5 without allowing ...Nxe4. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 d6 10. Bxc6
{ is the way to go.   There's no need to spend a tempo on  10.h3  as played by Nepo against Fabi. This allows  10...g5  11.Nxg5  hxg5  12.Bxg5  Here, instead of 12... Kh7 which occurred in1-0  @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2835@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020, Black should have played  12...Kg7=∞  with an unclear position. }
10... bxc6 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nbd2
{ 12.Nxe5  g5!  kills any hopes of an advantage. Black immediately wins the pawn back on e4. }
12... Re8
{ 12...g5  now is asking for trouble. After  13.Bg3  the e5 pawn is hanging and Black has no good way to cover it. }
13. Qc2
{ White is threatening Nc4 and is clearly for choice.   Black's best is to break the pin with  13...g5  14.Bg3  Nh5  15.Nc4  Nxg3  16.hxg3  Qf6  17.Rad1  Black's structure is compromised while White doesn't have any weaknesses. There's no doubt White is better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Møller & others"]
[Black "5...Bc5 Møller 6...O-O #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ The Møller Defense is named after Jorgen Møller, who first analyzed it in Tidskrift för Schack. The idea of this move is not to play ...b7-b5 but rather to drop back the bishop to a7. }
6. c3 { As usual, we prepare the d4 advance when Black puts his bishop on c5. }
6... O-O
{ The so-called Carlsen's Møller, mainly because Carlsen played this successfully in a number of games recently. }
7. d4
{ We're at a crossroads now: Black can either drop the bishop back to b6 or a7. }
7... Ba7
{ is by far the main move with over 350 games played, 6 of which by Magnus Carlsen. We'll be following the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L  @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2847@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. }
8. Bg5
{ Prevents ...Nxe4 by pinning the knight. White is now threatening dxe5.   8.dxe5  is another possibility. The mainline goes  8...Nxe4  9.Qd5  Nc5  10.Bc2  Ne7  11.Qd1  d5!  Black is fine in all the ensuing lines. }
8... exd4
{ was Carlsen's choice against Aronian. White should immediately strike in the center with }
9. e5 h6 10. Bxf6
{ 10.Bh4  g5  gave Black a fine endgame in0-1 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2847@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021, which Magnus even ended up winning. }
10... gxf6 11. cxd4 fxe5
{ 11...d6  runs into  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.Qc1  with a double-attack on the c6 and h6 pawns. }
12. dxe5 Re8 13. Bxc6
{ White eliminates the c6 knight to preserve the e5 pawn. } 13... dxc6
{ In the book Carlsen's Neo-Møller: A Complete and Surprising Repertoire Against the Ruy Lopez, FM Ioannis Simeonidis stopped here saying that Black's bishop pair should be enough to hold. However, both Stockfish and Lc0 give White a significant advantage after }
14. Qc2 { Preventing Bf5. } 14... Kh8 15. Re1
{ Black's kingside is in tatters. We're planning to bring the b1 knight into the attack with Nc3-e4 combined with ideas of g2-g3 and Nh4. I like White's chances. }
