{ 10.Bh4  g5  gave Black a fine endgame in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2847@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021, which Magnus even ended up winning. }
10... gxf6 11. cxd4 Re8
{ Hitting the e5 pawn. Black hasn't taken on e5 yet and so we should delay Bxc6. Otherwise the d4 pawn will become a weakness. The best course of action is to simply reinforce the e5 pawn with }
12. Re1 fxe5 { Sooner or later, we'll have to take on e5. } 13. dxe5 d6 14. Nc3
{ A very interesting pawn sacrifice, seeking to gain the initiative with rapid development. }
14... dxe5 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Qc2
{ We keep the queens on the board to have attacking chances against Black's king. }
16... Re6 { is the only way to hold everything together. } 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. Qf5
{ Taking advantage of Black's weakened structure. } 18... Rb8 19. b3
{ Black managed to hold in the correspondence game½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Llorente Alvarez,J @@StartBracket@@2190@@EndBracket@@ -Maetzig,R @@StartBracket@@2270@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018, but practically White's position is far easier to play. }
