{ is a very interesting line. At first sight, ...b5 may look premature given that it allows White to drop back the bishop to c2 in one go. Nevertheless, it leads to very complex positions that Caruana has thrived in with the Black pieces. The American Super-GM defeated Dominguez and drew MVL - a game he really should have won. I've spent a lot of time analyzing these lines for both colors and have yet to find an advantage for White.   As such, the best is to bypass this labyrinth of variations with }
7. Bb3 Bb7 8. a4 { whichtransposes into the modern Arkhangelsk variation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Møller & others"]
[Black "5...Bc5 Møller 6...b5 7...d6 8...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ The Møller Defense is named after Jorgen Møller, who first analyzed it in Tidskrift för Schack. The idea of this move is not to play ...b7-b5 but rather to drop back the bishop to a7. }
6. c3 { As usual, we prepare the d4 advance when Black puts his bishop on c5. }
6... b5
{ is a very interesting line. At first sight, ...b5 may look premature given that it allows White to drop back the bishop to c2 in one go. Nevertheless, it leads to very complex positions that Caruana has thrived in with the Black pieces. The American Super-GM defeated Dominguez and drew MVL - a game he really should have won. I've spent a lot of time analyzing these lines for both colors and have yet to find an advantage for White.   As such, the best is to bypass this labyrinth of variations with }
7. Bb3 d6 8. a4
{ 8...Bb7  and  8...Rb8  transpose to thenext chapter on the Arkhangelsk. }
8... Bg4
{ Black brings the bishop out to g4, which is usually premature when White's d-pawn is still on d2. As a rule of thumb, Black should only play ...Bg4 in the Ruy Lopez once White has expanded in the center with d4, the point being to put pressure on this pawn.   Nevertheless, this move is concretely quite strong and it's not easy to find an objective advantage with White. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. d3
{ If White were to play d4, Black's bishop on g4 would find itself perfectly placed to pressure the center. Instead, we go for the modest d3 aiming to slowly develop our queenside forces. After g2-g4 later on, Black's light-squared bishop may quickly find itself out of play as it'll be restricted by both the e4 and g4 pawns.   10.axb5  was recommended by both Gajewski and Grandelius in their Chessable courses on the Spanish. However, they both missed a strong resource for Black that leads to equality. Best play by both sides goes  10...axb5  11.Rxa8  Qxa8  12.d3  O-O  13.Bg5  And here both authors missed  13...Nd8!  completely ignoring the 'threat' of Bxf6 and instead heading for the f4 square with the knight. Turns out that  14.Bxf6  gxf6=  is not at all a problem for Black, who'll be able to make use of the g-file after a subsequent ...Kh8. I spent a number of hours analyzing various options here but could not find any hint of a White advantage. }
10... Na5 11. Ba2 b4
{ Black must create active play on the queenside or he'll soon find himself in trouble. }
12. cxb4 Bxb4 13. Nc3
{ White has good chances for a slight advantage in this position. The immediate threat is to go Bg5 followed by Nd5 taking advantage of the lack of coordination in Black's camp.   A sample line goes  13...Rb8!  14.Bg5  h6  15.Bxf6  Qxf6  16.Nd5  Qd8  which was all recommended in the book The Arkhangelsk Ruy Lopez by GM Shyam Sundar. White can still ask some questions after both  17.Qc1  hitting the c7 pawn  or by breaking in the center with  17.d4  Objectively, Black can maintain the balance with precise play but White's position remains easier to play in both lines. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Arkhangelsk"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ The Modern-Arkhangelsk, also known as the Neo-Arkhalgelsk, is a refined version of the regular Arkhangelsk Defence that incorporated ideas from the Møller variation. By delaying the queenside fianchetto, Black maintains the option of pressuring White's center with ...Bg4.   White's main move continuation is 7. a4 although White can also to start with 7. c3 and only then play 8. a4, with 8. d4 also being possible. Black usually reacts to a2-a4 with ...Rb8, unless he decides to transpose into the usual Arkhangelsk with ...Bb7.   This variation has become extremely popular at the top level with super-GMs playing this line with both colors. Practically speaking, even though the lines are very sharp and can get very messy, Black is only playing for a draw provided both players are well prepared.   As such, it's important to try and surprise your opponents and take them out of their comfort zone by finding novel options. With perfect play, Black will reach a holdable position but we'll certainly make it as uncomfortable as possible! }
7. a4
{ is the most testing option, immediately asking Black to clarify his intentions. The second player can either opt for the Modern Arkhanglesk with  7...Rb8  or instead play  7...Bb7  ,  entering the old Arkhangelsk complex. Both are very much playable, the recent trend being to choose  7...Rb8  . }
*

