[White "Bc5 systems | Arkhangelsk"]
[Black "6...Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ This move order has subsided in popularity. Nevertheless, it's been played in thousands of games. Black immediately aims the bishop at the e4 pawn, making Nxe4 a potential threat in many variations. }
7. Re1
{ Simple and effective, reinforcing the e4 pawn.   7.d3  is very much possible. Given that our main approach is c3 + d4, we should reject this option.   The immediate  7.c3  gives Black the extra option of  7...Nxe4  which we do best in avoiding. }
7... Bc5
{ 7...Be7  Transposes to the Trajkovic variation in the 6th move alternatives chapter. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. Be3
{ We continue analogously to the 7...Bb7 lines in which a4 has been played. The threat is d4-d5. }
10... exd4
{ The text move was seen in a dozen of games, most notably in½-½ @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Wang,H  @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@-Bu,X @@StartBracket@@2697@@EndBracket@@ Chengdu 2017.   10...Nxe4?  blunders a piece to  11.d5+-   10...Na5  Black can try to play Na5 before taking on d4. However, this gives White the option of opening up the center with  11.dxe5  Nxb3  12.Qxb3  dxe5  13.c4!?  White has several good moves. This is my preference, immediately putting pressure on Black's queenside.  13...bxc4  14.Qb4⩲  is an important move, stopping Black from castling. White is at least slightly better. The e1-rook is well-placed and there's no need to worry about the material deficit since the c4 and e5 pawns will drop sooner than later. }
11. cxd4 Na5 12. Bc2 h6 13. Nbd2 O-O
{ All of this happened in the aforementioned game. Now I like } 14. Rc1
{ taking control over the c-file. Importantly, Black will never be able to play ...c7-c5 as after d4-d5 both of his bishops along with the a5-knight will be severely restricted. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Arkhangelsk"]
[Black "6...Bb7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ This move order has subsided in popularity. Nevertheless, it's been played in thousands of games. Black immediately aims the bishop at the e4 pawn, making Nxe4 a potential threat in many variations. }
7. Re1
{ 7.d3  is very much possible. Given that our main approach is c3 + d4, we should reject this option.   The immediate  7.c3  gives Black the extra option of  7...Nxe4  which we do best in avoiding. }
7... Bc5
{ 7...Be7  Transposes to the Trajkovic variation in the 6th move alternatives chapter. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. Be3
{ We continue analogously to the 7...Bb7 lines in which a4 has been played. The threat is d4-d5. }
10... O-O
{ is the most popular continuation with well over 500 games played. Here I like doubling the b-pawns with d5 followed by Bxb6. }
11. d5
{ Despite being 8x less common than   11.Nbd2  I believe the text is the best. }
11... Ne7
{ 11...Na5  makes no sense. The knight finds itself completely misplaced on a5 after  12.Bxb6  cxb6   12...Nxb3  drops the c7-pawn to  13.Bxc7  Qxc7  14.axb3±  13.Bc2⩲  The knight would much prefer to be on e7. }
12. Bxb6 cxb6 13. Nbd2
{ These positions are unpleasant for the second player. The doubled b-pawns are far from ideal. The c-file does not offset the compromised structure since Black can't generate any play there. }
13... h6
{ Once again, Black takes control over the g5 square before breaking with ...f5. The text also creates a square on h7 for the knight to drop back to.   13...Nd7  occurred in the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Yu,Y @@StartBracket@@2721@@EndBracket@@-Bu,X @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ Shenzhen 2016. Black is preparing ...f7-f5.  14.Bc2  The bishop is no longer useful on b3, so it's time to drop it back.  14...h6  Black takes control over the g5 square before striking with ...f5. Otherwise, he'd have to contend with Ng5-e6.  15.Nf1  The knight is headed to g3/ e3 when ...f5 will be much harder to achieve. This forces Black's hand.  15...f5  16.exf5  Nxf5  17.Qd2⩲  An interesting Leela suggestion, sacrificing the d5 pawn for pressure along the d-file with Rad1. }
14. Qe2 Nh7
{ 14...Bc8  is a logical move as the bishop wasn't doing anything on b7. But the question is, what exactly is it doing on c8? This shows how hard it is to come up with a constructive plan for Black.  15.Nf1  Conversely, we have the straightforward plan of improving our knight. It's headed towards e3 @@StartBracket@@preceded by N3d2 to cover the e4 pawn@@EndBracket@@. White will then open up the queenside with a2-a4 at an opportune moment.  15...Ng6  is nothing to be worried out. The simple  16.g3  restricts the knight. There's no need to worry about the slight weakening of the light-squares since Black can't exploit it.   14...Nh5?!  is far from ideal as after  15.g3  Black has essentially wasted a tempo since the knight will have to return to f6. }
15. a4 { Perfect timing! } 15... bxa4 16. Bxa4
{ White has a stable advantage in these kinds of positions.   Black's queenside structure and especially the b7 bishop are far from ideal.   White can look to double up on the a-file to pressure the a6 pawn, which can be further attacked with Bc2-d3. Later on, White can consider pushing the queenside pawns. }
