{ The Modern-Arkhangelsk, also known as the Neo-Arkhalgelsk, is a refined version of the regular Arkhangelsk Defence that incorporated ideas from the Møller.   By delaying the queenside fianchetto, Black maintains the option of pressuring White's center with ...Bg4. White's main move continuation is 7. a4 although White can also to start with 7. c3 and only then play 8. a4, with 8. d4 also being possible.   Black usually reacts to a2-a4 with ...Rb8, unless he decides to transpose into the usual Arkhangelsk with ...Bb7.   This variation has become extremely popular at the top level with super-GMs playing this line with both colors. Practically speaking, even though the lines are very sharp and can get very messy, Black is only playing for a draw provided both players are well prepared. As such, it's important to try and surprise your opponents and take them out of their comfort zone by finding novel options. With perfect play, Black will reach a holdable position but we'll certainly make it as uncomfortable as possible! }
7. a4
{ is the most testing option, immediately asking Black to clarify whether his intentions. He can either opt for the Modern Arkhanglesk with 7...Rb8 or instead play 7...Bb7, entering the old Arkhangelsk complex. Both are very much playable, the recent trend being to choose 7...Rb8. }
7... Bb7
{ The Arkhangelsk Defense @@StartBracket@@or Archangel Defense@@EndBracket@@ is named after the Russian city Arkhangelsk and was popularized by a variety of Soviet players, most remarkably Vladimir Malaniuk. This variation, alongside all the other ... Bc5 systems, leads to very sharp positions where both sides must know what they are doing. We'll be aiming for setups involving c3 + d4, which are considered to be the most challenging. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6
{ The two mainlines at this junction,  10.Bg5  and  10.Re1  ,  (lead to very complex play. After extensive analysis, I came to appreciate the unexplored but strong:) }
10. Be3
{ At the time of writing, this move has only been played in a handful of games, a notable game being ½-½  @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Vachier Lagrave,M @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ -Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. Black's task of equalizing is just as hard as in the 10. Bg5 mainline so practically it makes a lot of sense to opt for this variation. I've come up with an array of novelties that are sure to set Black several practical problems. }
10... O-O
{ was played in two games both of which continued with 11. Nbd2. I propose the novel }
11. axb5
{ which leads to a superior endgame after the following sequence of moves. }
11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. dxe5 dxe5
{ 13...Nxe5  14.Nxe5  dxe5  15.Bxb6  leads to a very similar endgame as the text. }
14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Bxb6 cxb6 16. Ng5
{ An important move, covering e4 and hitting the f7 pawn. } 16... Rd7 17. f3
{ Black's queenside pawns are doubled and the bishop on a8 is completely restricted by the e4 pawn. White can look to slowly improve his pieces with Kf2-e2/e3 followed by Nd2. If the g5 knight is attacked, it can be recycled with Nf3-f2-d3. Black has enough resources to maintain the balance with precise, but there's no doubt White's position is far easier to play. }
