{ is currently my preferred approach. Yes, we release the tension on the queenside but gain some space and can now turn our attention to the center and the kingside. Moreover, we shove the Bishop to a less well-defended square on a7. }
10... Nxa5
{ Black is in no position to go pawn grabbing.   10...Bxa5??  blunders a piece to  11.d5+- }
11. Rxa5 Bxa5 12. dxe5 Nxe4 { Too much greed. Black is punished with } 13. Qd5
{ hitting both the knight and the f7 pawn. } 13... Be6 14. Qxe4 Bxb3 15. Nd4
{ Black is in big trouble. The b3 bishop is hanging and Nc6 with a triple fork is a huge threat. }
