[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bc5 systems | Arkhangelsk"]
[Black "Why not 13.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. a4 Rb8 8. c3
d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5 Ba7 11. h3 Bb7 12. Be3 Nxe4
{ was the move Black prepared with 11...Bb7. Now that the c6 knight is defended, Black can take on e4 without having to worry about Bd5. This leads to a tense struggle. }
13. d5
{ At first sight, this may seem like the most challenging line, but it leads nowhere. Black is just fine after the following tactical fireworks }
13... Bxe3 14. dxc6 Nxf2 15. Qe2 Nxh3+ 16. Kh1 Nf2+ 17. Rxf2 Bxf2 18. cxb7 Ba7
19. Bd5 Qd7
{ Everything up until now was pretty much forced. This all occurred in the game0-1 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Vachier Lagrave,M @@StartBracket@@2760@@EndBracket@@ -Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@ Paris 2021, where White played very poorly and ended up losing. White's best is }
20. Nd4
{ which is a novelty. I'd have made this my main recommendation, which threatens both Bc6 and Nc6, if not for }
20... Qe7 21. Bc6+ Kf8 22. Nf3 d5
{ A bolt from the blue that just about equalizes after the following long, forced line: }
23. Qxe5 Qxe5 24. Nxe5 Ke7 25. Nd3 Kd6 26. Nb4 Bc5 27. Nxa6 Kxc6 28. Nxc5 Kxc5
29. a6 b4 30. Nd2 bxc3 31. bxc3 Kb6 32. a7 Rxb7 33. a8=Q Rxa8 34. Rxa8 Ra7
{ And we end up in a drawn endgame. Remarkably, Black holds after all these forced moves. Yet another example of the large drawing margin in chess. }
