13... Ne7
{ was played in the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2759@@EndBracket@@ -Dubov, D @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Lichess. org INT 2021. Now White should have played }
14. Nbd2 { Black is forced to capture on d2, otherwise e5 drops. } 14... Nxd2
15. Bxd2 O-O
{ Black had to give up the e5-pawn as taking on d4 would have allowed Bg5 immediately winning the e7-knight. }
16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Nxe5 Ng6 18. Be3
{ gave White the upper hand in the correspondence game1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Castro, F @@StartBracket@@2271@@EndBracket@@-Pastukhov, I ICCF email 2015 that continued  18...Bxe3  19.Rxe3  Qg5  20.Qg4  Qxg4  21.hxg4  Nxe5  22.Rxe5  Rfe8  23.Rc5±  with a very pleasant endgame advantage. }
18... Nxe5
{ was recommended in the book The Modernized Arkhangelsk Variation by GM Viktor Erdos. Rather than defend the a7 bishop, Black goes after the g1 king with ideas of ...Nf3+ followed by ...Qg5+ - a surprisingly strong idea! }
19. Qxd8
{ Heading for the endgame is the most challenging continuation.   The point behind Black's last move was that after  19.Bxa7  there's the brilliant tactical resource  Nf3+!!  blasting open the kingside.  20.gxf3  Qg5+  It turns out there's no way for White to escape the checks. For example  21.Kh2  Qf4+  22.Kg2  Qg5+  23.Kh2  Qf4+  White can't avoid a perpetual, even after  24.Kg1  Black finds a way to draw with  Rbd8  25.Qe2  Qg5+  26.Kh1  Qh4  and White has nothing better than  27.Kg2=  with a repetition.   @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/Bbp2ppp/p7/Pp2n1q1/8/1BP4P/1P3PP1/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  19...Qg5  is another possibility but White is clearly for choice after  20.Bd5  Rbd8  21.Bxb7  Rxd1  22.Raxd1↑  White's two rooks and bishops dominate here. }
19... Rbxd8 20. Bxa7 Nd3 21. Re7 Bd5
{ Very precise - turns out that Black is just in time to exchange the bishops and thus neutralize White's bishop pair. }
22. Bxd5 { 22.Bc2  Nxb2  23.Rxc7  Rc8=  is not the way to play for an edge. }
22... Rxd5 23. Rxc7 Nxb2
{ Objectively, Black can hold this endgame with precise play. However, from a practical standpoint, this endgame is very unpleasant for Black. White has a strong rook on the 7th and the bishop is generally stronger than Black's knight. }
24. Bd4
{ I found this to be the most challenging continuation, although Black still holds with precise play. Alternatives are  briefly examined below:   @@StartBracket@@a@@EndBracket@@  24.Bb6  Nc4  25.Ra7  is the most tempting option, but Black has a nice idea to put White in a knot:  h5  26.Rxa6  Rd6!  Surprisingly, White can't move despite being a pawn up! For example,  27.Rb1  allows  Nxa5  28.Rxb5  Nc4  29.Rb4  Rc8  when White is paralyzed.   @@StartBracket@@b@@EndBracket@@  24.Re1  is also worth considering, but Black should be fine after something like  Nc4  25.Bc5  Rfd8  26.Ree7  Black's life is far from easy here, but he can hold with precise play. To start out, Black should create some luft with  h5!  noting that  27.Rxf7  runs into  27...Rxc5!  28.Rxg7+  Kf8  29.Rcf7+  when White has nothing better than a draw.   @@StartFEN@@3r2k1/2R1Rpp1/p7/PpBr3p/2n5/2P4P/5PP1/6K1 w - h6 0 27@@EndFEN@@  27.Kh2  Rf5  adequately covers f7. There's no way for White to displace the rook from the f-file, for example  28.g4  hxg4  29.hxg4  Rf4  30.Kg3  g5=  anchors the rook on f4 when White can't make much progress.  31.Bd4  stops ...Rd3+ but Black still has  Nd2!  threatening ...b4 and ...Ne4+.  32.Rb7  Ne4+  33.Kg2  Nd2  34.Kg3= }
24... Nc4 25. Ra7 b4 { This tactical resource ensures Black's survival. } 26.
Rxa6 b3
{ The b3 pawn will provide just enough of a distraction to draw the game. } 27.
Ra4 Nxa5
{ Another nice tactical solution.   27...b2  28.Rb4  stops the b-pawn dead in its tracks. White is again for choice and Black still has to work hard to draw. }
28. R4xa5 b2 29. Rxd5 b1=Q+ 30. Kh2
{ is a two-results endgame. White can keep on pushing, but Black should be able to hold. Needless to say, finding all this with Black is far from trivial and even then a draw still isn't guaranteed! }
