11... Bb7
{ is the latest trend. It has been played by super-GMs Caruana, Aruana, Grischuk, and Dubov as well as 2600+ GMs Inarkiev and Chessable author Surya Ganguly to name a few. This move was also recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the database Arkhangelsk Variation - Lifetime Solution for Black for modern-chess.com. }
12. Be3 Nxe4
{ was the move Black prepared with 11...Bb7. Now that the c6 knight is defended, Black can take on e4 without having to worry about Bd5. This leads to a tense struggle. }
13. Re1
{ is the best try for an advantage and has scored extremely well for White. Black is objectively fine after 13. d5 as shown below. }
13... exd4 14. cxd4 Ne7
{ was Avrukh's recommendation for modern-chess.com This is a logical approach, opening up the bishop's diagonal and protecting the e4 knight. If Black is allowed to castle, he'll simply be a pawn up. But White strikes immediately with }
15. Nbd2 d5
{ is more or less forced.   15...Nxd2  is strongly met by  16.Bxd2  when Black's knight on e7 is in big trouble.  16...O-O  17.Bg5!  followed by Qe2 may very well pick up the e7 knight. }
16. Nxe4
{ 16.Ne5  is also very interesting and given as analternative recommendation. }
16... dxe4 17. Ng5 Bd5
{ Black's previous moves were pretty much forced. And here comes the big improvement }
18. Nxe4
{ A very deeeep piece sacrifice. Avrukh completely missed it in his database for modern-chess.com. It's not winning or an outright refutation, but Black has to basically play like Stockfish to hold. }
18... Bxe4 { is a serious mistake. It'll soon become clear why. } 19. Bg5 h6
20. Bh4 f5
{ Black has occupied the h6 square ruling out Qh5-h6. However, White has another stunning shot up his sleeve: }
21. g4 { Garry strikes! : @@EndBracket@@ } 21... Qd7
{ is Black's best try, intending to meet gxf5 with ... Qxf5.   21...g5  fails to  22.gxf5  Bxf5  23.Qh5+  Kd7  24.Bg3+-  with a decisive advantage. }
22. Rc1
{ White brings out the rook and will develop the queen before taking on f5. }
22... Rd8 23. Qe2 c6 24. gxf5
{ Perfect timing! We will end up in a favorable endgame after the following forced sequence: }
24... Qxf5 25. Qxe4 Qxe4 26. Rxe4 g5 27. Rce1 Rh7 28. Bg3 Rxd4 29. R4e2
{ All of Black's moves so far have been forced. And White is clearly better as Black can hardly move. }
