1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ The Modern-Arkhangelsk, also known as the Neo-Arkhalgelsk, is a refined version of the regular Arkhangelsk Defence that incorporated ideas from the Møller.   By delaying the queenside fianchetto, Black maintains the option of pressuring White's center with ...Bg4. White's main move continuation is 7. a4 although White can also to start with 7. c3 and only then play 8. a4, with 8. d4 also being possible.   Black usually reacts to a2-a4 with ...Rb8, unless he decides to transpose into the usual Arkhangelsk with ...Bb7.   This variation has become extremely popular at the top level with super-GMs playing this line with both colors. Practically speaking, even though the lines are very sharp and can get very messy, Black is only playing for a draw provided both players are well prepared. As such, it's important to try and surprise your opponents and take them out of their comfort zone by finding novel options. With perfect play, Black will reach a holdable position but we'll certainly make it as uncomfortable as possible! }
7. a4
{ is the most testing option, immediately asking Black to clarify whether his intentions. He can either opt for the Modern Arkhanglesk with 7...Rb8 or instead play 7...Bb7, entering the old Arkhangelsk complex. Both are very much playable, the recent trend being to choose 7...Rb8. }
7... Rb8
{ The Modern way to handle the position, which has been played by virtually every top player. }
8. c3 { Preparing the standard d2-d4 central expansion. } 8... d6
{ Black essentially has to meet c2-c3 with ... d7-d6 in order to strengthen the center. Otherwise, d2-d4 will be disastrous for him. }
9. d4 Bb6
{ is the main tabiya in the Modern Arkhangelsk. White has tried a variety of moves, the three main approaches being 10. axb5, 10. a5 and 10. Na3 in descending order of popularity. }
10. a5
{ is currently my preferred approach. Yes, we release the tension on the queenside but gain some space and can now turn our attention to the center and the kingside. }
10... Ba7 { 10...Bxa5??  blunders a piece to  11.d5+- } 11. h3
{ prevents both ...Ng4 and ...Bg4. White is planning to complete development with Be3 and Nbd2. }
11... Bb7
{ is the latest trend. It has been played by super-GMs Caruana, Aruana, Grischuk, and Dubov as well as 2600+ GMs Inarkiev and Chessable author Surya Ganguly to name a few. This move was also recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the database Arkhangelsk Variation - Lifetime Solution for Black for modern-chess.com. }
12. Be3 Nxe4
{ was the move Black prepared with 11...Bb7. Now that the c6 knight is defended, Black can take on e4 without having to worry about Bd5. This leads to a tense struggle. }
13. Re1
{ is the best try for an advantage and has scored extremely well for White. Black is objectively fine after 13. d5 as shown below. }
13... exd4 14. cxd4 Ne7
{ was Avrukh's recommendation for modern-chess.com This is a logical approach, opening up the bishop's diagonal and protecting the e4 knight. If Black is allowed to castle, he'll simply be a pawn up. But White strikes immediately with }
15. Nbd2 d5
{ is more or less forced.   15...Nxd2  is strongly met by  16.Bxd2  when Black's knight on e7 is in big trouble.  16...O-O  17.Bg5!  followed by Qe2 may very well pick up the e7 knight. }
16. Nxe4
{ 16.Ne5  is also very interesting and given as analternative recommendation. }
16... dxe4 17. Ng5 Bd5
{ Black's previous moves were pretty much forced. And here comes the big improvement }
18. Nxe4
{ A very deeeep piece sacrifice. Avrukh completely missed it in his database for modern-chess.com. It's not winning or an outright refutation, but Black has to basically play like Stockfish to hold. }
18... O-O { Black does best in declining the sacrifice. } 19. Bc2 Bxe4
{ 19...Nf5  trying to exchange off the bishop on e3 runs into  20.Ng5!  Qf6  21.Qg4↑  with a very dangerous initiative. }
20. Bxe4 Nd5 21. Qc2 Nxe3 22. fxe3
{ It's move 22 and a moment to stop.   Black can hold the balance with the brilliant  22...Kh8!  a move I doubt too many humans would even consider. It's essentially a waiting move that avoids creating any kingside weaknesses and protects the h7 pawn indirectly. Nevertheless, White's position is far easier to play and Black still needs to be very precise thereafter to maintain the balance. }
