1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. a4 Rb8 8. c3
d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5 Ba7 11. h3 Bb7 12. Be3 Nxe4 13. Re1 exd4 14. cxd4 Ne7 15.
Nbd2 d5 16. Ne5 { is another interesting possibility. } 16... O-O 17. Rc1
{ Takes control over the c-file. White is now ready to play Nxe4 followed by Qg4. }
17... Rc8
{ is a very careless move. White essentially gets a free tempo as after... }
18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Qg4 { ...the threat Bh6 forces Black to play ...Qd6 anyhow. }
19... Qd6 20. h4
{ Harry comes into the fray. If Black does nothing @@StartBracket@@not an easy feat@@EndBracket@@, White will push --ahead with h5-h6. And if Black accepts the challenge with }
20... Bxd4
{ then we will end up in rook vs two minor pieces endgame after the following sequence: }
21. Red1 c5
{ 21...Qxe5??  blunders  22.Bxd4+−  hitting the queen, which can't move due to mate on g7. }
22. Bxd4 cxd4 23. Rxc8 Bxc8 24. Nxf7
{ is the only way to fight for an advantage. } 24... Rxf7 25. Qxe4
{ Since Black is unable to unpin the rook, White has enough time to pick up the e4 and d4 pawns. }
25... Qf6 26. Rxd4
{ with the lethal threat of Rd8. There is no need to be worried about the Qxf2 move as White can simply hide away with his king on h2 when Black simply can't prevent both Rd8 and Qxe7 at once. The game is not over though.   Black can unpin the rook and create some breathing space with  26...g6  Notwithstanding, White has every possibility of converting his advantage into a full point. }
