d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5 Ba7 11. h3 Bb7 12. Be3 Nxe4 13. Re1 exd4 14. cxd4 Ne7 15.
Nbd2 d5 16. Ne5 { is another interesting possibility. } 16... O-O 17. Rc1
{ Takes control over the c-file. White is now ready to play Nxe4 followed by Qg4. }
17... Qd6
{ Black might as well start with this move since Nxe4 followed by Qg4 will force Black to develop the queen to d6 anyway. }
18. Nxe4 { Our plan remains unchanged. } 18... dxe4 19. Qg4
{ As seen in the 17...Rc8 variation, if Black does nothing White will start pushing the h-pawn. Black should thus play actively with }
19... Nd5 20. Qxe4 Rbe8 21. Bd2
{ 21.Bd2  with the rather-obvious intention of meeting  21...f6  with  22.Bb4!  Objectively speaking, Black is fine but I'd take White any day here. It's not clear how Black will untangle his pieces. In summary, both 16. Nxe4 and 16. Ne5 set Black a fair share of practical problems. The second player can equalize with precise play. After all, chess is a draw with perfect play by both sides. }
