13... Rf8 14. Re1 Ra8
{ is a typical idea. Black protects the a7 bishop before playing ...Bb7. } 15.
Nf3
{ The knight has done its job on g5 and returns to f3, reinforcing the d4 pawn in order to develop the b1 knight. }
15... Bb7 16. Nbd2 Re8
{ Since the queen on d8 is now well-protected and the knight on d2 is blocking White's queen, Black can meet Ng5 with ...Re7.   Notwithstanding, White is still for choice after  17.Ng5  Re7  18.d5  Nb8  19.Bxa7  Rxa7  20.c4  The text is, however, stronger. }
17. g4
{ This is an extremely strong novelty that I've had in my files for a while now. I discovered it when examining this line from Black's point of view. Sethuraman completely missed this strong idea, which makes his proposed repertoire practically unplayable OTB.   The only way Black is surviving the upcoming complications is if he plays like an engine. g2-g4 carries a very deep point. It may seem like White is preparing g4-g5 but this is NOT the case! It may sound funny, but g4 is a high-class waiting move that leaves Black almost in zugzwang. How come you may be asking?   If you look closely, you'll see that Black can barely move any of his pieces:   @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ The rook on a8 is protecting the a7-bishop. Moving it away allows White to push ahead with d4-d5;   @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ The bishops are stuck;   @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  The knights can't really leave their posts;   @@StartBracket@@4@@EndBracket@@ The e8-rook is not doing much and has nowhere to go;  @@StartBracket@@5@@EndBracket@@ Finally, any pawn moves just weaken Black's position. For example, ... 6 only creates a hook for g4-g5. As such, Black must bail out with a concrete move and the only possibility is to take on d4. }
17... exd4 18. cxd4
{ is a good place to stop. Black needs to remember 14 more moves to have any chances of holding as shown in the following clickable line. Any deviation will result in a clearly worse position.   18.cxd4  Ne7!  is the only way to maintain the balance.  Black can easily go wrong with a move like   18...Nxe4  which fails to  19.Nxe4  Rxe4  20.Bxf7+  Kxf7  21.Ng5++-  winning.  19.Ng5!?  The most testing choice.  19...Rf8  20.e5  dxe5  21.dxe5  Bxe3  22.fxe3□  White should recapture with the rook in order to not to get hit by ...Nfd5.  22...Nfd5   22...Nd7?!  allows  23.e6↑  23.Nde4  h6  24.Nc5!  hxg5  25.Nxb7  Qc8  26.Nc5  c6  27.e4  Nf4  28.e6!  fxe6  29.Qd6  Qe8!  30.Nxe6  Nxe6  31.Qxe6+  Kh8  32.Rf1∞  The smoke has somewhat cleared and White is firmly in the driver's seat. White has many ways to pressure Black's position. Conversely, any mistake by the second player is likely to result in an outright loss. }
