1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ The Modern-Arkhangelsk, also known as the Neo-Arkhalgelsk, is a refined version of the regular Arkhangelsk Defence that incorporated ideas from the Møller.   By delaying the queenside fianchetto, Black maintains the option of pressuring White's center with ...Bg4. White's main move continuation is 7. a4 although White can also to start with 7. c3 and only then play 8. a4, with 8. d4 also being possible.   Black usually reacts to a2-a4 with ...Rb8, unless he decides to transpose into the usual Arkhangelsk with ...Bb7.   This variation has become extremely popular at the top level with super-GMs playing this line with both colors. Practically speaking, even though the lines are very sharp and can get very messy, Black is only playing for a draw provided both players are well prepared. As such, it's important to try and surprise your opponents and take them out of their comfort zone by finding novel options. With perfect play, Black will reach a holdable position but we'll certainly make it as uncomfortable as possible! }
7. a4
{ is the most testing option, immediately asking Black to clarify whether his intentions. He can either opt for the Modern Arkhanglesk with 7...Rb8 or instead play 7...Bb7, entering the old Arkhangelsk complex. Both are very much playable, the recent trend being to choose 7...Rb8. }
7... Rb8
{ The Modern way to handle the position, which has been played by virtually every top player. }
8. c3 { Preparing the standard d2-d4 central expansion. } 8... d6
{ Black essentially has to meet c2-c3 with ... d7-d6 in order to strengthen the center. Otherwise, d2-d4 will be disastrous for him. }
9. d4 Bb6
{ is the main tabiya in the Modern Arkhangelsk. White has tried a variety of moves, the three main approaches being 10. axb5, 10. a5 and 10. Na3 in descending order of popularity. }
10. a5
{ is currently my preferred approach. Yes, we release the tension on the queenside but gain some space and can now turn our attention to the center and the kingside. }
10... Ba7 { 10...Bxa5??  blunders a piece to  11.d5+- } 11. h3
{ prevents both ...Ng4 and ...Bg4. White is planning to complete development with Be3 and Nbd2. }
11... O-O { is by far the main move with 300+ games played. } 12. Be3
{ As usual, we first get the bishop out to e3 before developing the b1 knight. The e4 pawn is left hanging but Black is in no position to take it. }
12... exd4 { The absolute main line and the most challenging line. } 13. cxd4
Nb4 { is Black's usual follow up to ...exd4. } 14. Nc3
{ We now see the point of delaying Nbd2, that is White can now develop the knight to a more active square. }
14... Bb7 15. Qd2
{ Novel and strong. At very high depth, the engines tend to prefer this over 15. Ng5 which is the current mainline. Truth be told, both lead to equality but @@StartBracket@@a@@EndBracket@@ Black's path to equality is far harder after the text and @@StartBracket@@b@@EndBracket@@ it's a novelty that is likely to surprise your opponents.   15.Ng5  is White's main continuation. The absolute mainline goes  15...Qe7  16.e5  dxe5  17.Nxf7  and now  17...e4!  as played in the high-profile game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Vachier Lagrave,M @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@-Caruana,F  @@StartBracket@@2842@@EndBracket@@ Ekaterinburg 2020 is sufficient to maintain the balance. As usual, Caruana was extremely well prepared. White's best is  18.Ng5+!  Kh8  19.Ne6  but Black is objectively fine after  19...Rfc8=  This is still worth giving a shot in a practical game. I can't stress enough how well prepared Black must be to maintain the balance. }
15... c5
{ is the only move to stay within the realms of equality. All of Black's moves are pretty much forced and a single deviation is likely to be fatal. }
16. dxc5 dxc5 17. Rad1
{ It's very important to understand the differences between Rad1 and Rfd1.  After   17.Rfd1  Black can go for  17...Qe8  when we can't play  18.Bg5  due to  18...Nxe4  19.Nxe4  Qxe4  Now we don't have the option of playing Re1 @@StartBracket@@without allowing ...Qd3@@EndBracket@@. If the a-rook were on d1 and the kingside rook on f1, we could have played Rfe1 without allowing . ..Qd3. Nuanced but important!   17.Rfd1  Qe8  18.e5  is no solution. After  18...Bxf3  19.exf6  Bxd1  20.fxg7  Bxb3  21.gxf8=Q+  Qxf8  22.Bh6  Qd8  23.Qf4  Qd4  it's White that needs to be precise to keep himself above water. The text avoids all these possibilities. }
17... Qxd2
{ in order to pick up the e4 pawn makes little sense. White gets free play in the center and on the queenside after }
18. Rxd2 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Rd7
{ White is clearly for choice and Black must be very precise to have any chances of holding.   Best play by both sides continues  20...Rb7  21.Rfd1  Rxd7  22.Rxd7  Nc6  It's important to bring the knight back.   22...c4  is a big mistake as after  23.Bxa7  cxb3  White has  24.Bc5  23.Nd2  c4!  Funnily enough, this is now the only move to stay above water. Black is still not out of the woods and is required to hold a really sad endgame after  24.Bxa7  Bf5!  25.Rd6  Nxa7  26.Rxa6  and it's clear Black is struggling to draw this. }
*

