{ It's very important to understand the differences between Rad1 and Rfd1.   After  17.Rfd1  Black can go for  17...Qe8  when we can't play  18.Bg5  due to  18...Nxe4  19.Nxe4  Qxe4  Now we don't have the option of playing Re1 @@StartBracket@@without allowing ...Qd3@@EndBracket@@. If the a-rook were on d1 and the kingside rook on f1, we could have played Rfe1 without allowing ...Qd3. Nuanced but important!   17.Rfd1  Qe8  18.e5  is no solution. After  18...Bxf3  19.exf6  Bxd1  20.fxg7  Bxb3  21.gxf8=Q+  Qxf8  22.Bh6  Qd8  23.Qf4  Qd4  it's White that needs to be precise to keep himself above water. The text avoids all these possibilities. }
17... Qxa5 { is the only drawback of moving the a1-rook to d1. } 18. e5
{ gives White a big initiative and more than enough compensation for the pawn. Black needs to play precisely thereafter to stay alive.   A sample line goes  18...Rbd8  19.Qe1  is the most ambitious continuation, keeping the b4 knight pinned.  19...Bxf3  is practically forced. Moving the knight away allows Nd5.  20.gxf3  Rxd1  21.Qxd1  Rd8  22.Qb1  Nfd5!  another, far from obvious only move.  23.Nxd5  Nxd5  24.Bg5  c4!  Yet another only move.  25.Qe4  g6!  26.Bc2  Bc5!  27.Bxd8  Qxd8  28.h4↑  And Harry arrives on the scene, preventing ...Qg5 :@@EndBracket@@. Even after all this, Black must continue to find only moves to stay in the game. He needs to watch out for f4-f5 in particular. A way to get this is in is to play b3 later on, intending to meet ...c3 with b4 to lure the bishop to b4. On this square, it'll likely require protection from Black's queen, with say ...Qe7 which would then allow White to push the f-pawn since the h-pawn can no longer be taken. }
