1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 d6
{ is known as the Averbakh variation, named after the legendary Russian Grandmaster Yuri Averbakh. Rather than break the pin with ...b5, Black opts to simply defend the e5 pawn with ...d6. This line shares some similarities with the Steinitz Deferred, although Black is far less flexible here. The second player no longer has the option of transposing to the closed Ruy Lopez with ...b5 nor can he fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, which is already committed to e7. }
7. c3 Bg4
{ Black pins the f3 knight, thus preventing d2-d4.   7...b5  would transpose into the closed Ruy if White were to play 8. Bb3. However, we can save an entire tempo by simply dropping the bishop back to c2.  8.Bc2  This effectively rules out 7...b5. }
8. h3
{ is an interesting move order. White can also start with 8. d3, which is likely to transpose to the text. }
8... Bh5
{ is Black's most logical continuation, preserving the bishop and maintaining the pin. }
9. d3 h6 10. Nbd2 g5
{ is the only independent option. This pawn advance is nothing to be scared of.   10...O-O  transposes to the9...O-O 10...h6 variation. }
11. Nf1
{ White sends over a defender to the kingside and uncovers the queen. The first player is now ready to break in the center with d3-d4. }
11... g4 12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. d4
{ We all know that the best response to a flank attack is to counterattack in the center. d4-d5 is now huge a threat.  More details can be found in the nextalternative variation that you can opt to train. }
