1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 d6
{ is known as the Averbakh variation, named after the legendary Russian Grandmaster Yuri Averbakh. Rather than break the pin with ...b5, Black opts to simply defend the e5 pawn with ...d6. This line shares some similarities with the Steinitz Deferred, although Black is far less flexible here. The second player no longer has the option of transposing to the closed Ruy Lopez with ...b5 nor can he fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, which is already committed to e7. }
7. c3 Bg4
{ Black pins the f3 knight, thus preventing d2-d4.   7...b5  would transpose into the closed Ruy if White were to play 8. Bb3. However, we can save an entire tempo by simply dropping the bishop back to c2.  8.Bc2  This effectively rules out 7...b5. }
8. h3
{ is an interesting move order. White can also start with 8. d3, which is likely to transpose to the text. }
8... Bh5
{ is Black's most logical continuation, preserving the bishop and maintaining the pin. }
9. d3 Nd7
{ is an interesting maneuver. Black's knight is headed to c5 to break the pin. }
10. Be3 { Stops . ..Nc5 outright. } 10... h6 11. Nbd2 Bg5
{ is the second point behind 9...Nd7. Black cleared the d8-h4 diagonal, enabling ...Bg5 to exchange off some pieces and create some breathing space. }
12. Nf1 Bxe3 13. Rxe3
{ is the best recapture as the f1 knight is headed to g3. } 13... O-O 14. d4
{ is an interesting novelty, immediately taking over the center.   14.Ng3  is another good option. }
14... Nb6 15. Bxc6
{ Shatters Black's structure.   15.Bb3  is well met by  15...exd4  16.cxd4  d5!  with good play. }
15... bxc6 16. Ng3
{ Natural and effective.   16.b3  to stop ...Nc4 allows Black to generate counterplay with  16...f5!  17.exf5  Nd5  18.g4  Nxe3  19.Nxe3  Bf7  20.dxe5  dxe5  21.Nxe5  Qxd1+  22.Rxd1  This endgame is objectively balanced, although White has decent chances to win in a practical game. }
16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3
{ White has a stable advantage. Not only does the first player have the superior pawn structure, but his pieces are also far more active. }
