11... Na5 12. Bc2
{ By first retreating the bishop to b3, White provoked ...Na5. This effectively neutralizes ... d6-d5 as the e5 pawn lacks protection. }
12... c5 13. Nf1
{ The knight is headed to g3 with a stable advantage. White can then look to engineer the d4 break, typically prepared by Nf3-h4-f5, or instead undermine Black's queenside with a2-a4.   13.Nf1  Nc6  14.Ng3  Bg6  15.Nh4  White executes the standard knight dance.  15...Ne8  16.Nxg6  hxg6  17.Nf1!  With the pawn on g6, the f5 square is no longer available. White thus switches gears and heads to the d5 outpost.   13.Nf1  Re8  Preparing the ...d6-d5 break is well met by  14.Bd2!?  White threatens to break with a4 without allowing ...b4.  14...Qb6  Puts ...b4 back on the table.  15.Qe2  Rac8  16.Ng3  Bg6  17.Nh4⩲  gives White excellent prospects. }
