1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3
{ This is the well-known Closed Spanish tabiya from which thousands upon thousands of games have been played. Many top players have ventured these waters and champions have been decided in the complexities of these structures. Mastering this structure is guaranteed to improve your chess understanding.   Black’s top three choices in this position are the Chigorin with  9...Na5  , the Breyer with  9...Nb8  and the Zaitsev with  9...Bb7  . In this chapter, we’ll examine all of Black’s other options on move 9. does have some other choices, which will be covered in this chapter. }
9... a5
{ The Keres variation is named after the Estonian Paul Keres. He was one of the world's top players from the mid-1930s to the mid-1960s and essayed this variation on many occasions. The main idea of the text is to gain space on the queenside and push the bishop away from the active b3 post. Nowadays, this line is rarely seen given that White has many ways to obtain an advantage. }
10. d4
{ Popular and strong. White follows the old adage of responding to flank attacks with a counterattack in the center. }
10... a4 11. Bc2 exd4 12. cxd4 Nb4
{ Black will pick up the bishop pair, but White's space advantage will be far more significant. }
13. d5 Nxc2 14. Qxc2 Bd7 15. Nd4
{ The knight is excellently placed on d4, stopping .. .c7-c5 and taking control over the c6 square. White is clearly better thanks to the big space advantage. Note that Black's queenside pawns are merely targets.   A sample continuation is  15...Qc8  16.Be3  Qb7  17.Nd2±  Next up is Rc1 to take control over the c-file and thus rule out ...c5 for good. White can then slowly but surely expand on the kingside with f2-f4. Black's queenside weaknesses will tell sooner rather than later. }
