9... Be6
{ The Kholmov variation was once popular in the 1980s, but it's seldomly seen these days. That being said, White still needs to know what to do to emerge with an advantage. }
10. d4
{ Logical and strong, taking over the center. White is now threatening to win on the spot with d4-d5. }
10... Bxb3 { Nothing else makes sense. } 11. axb3
{ is the correct recapture, opening up the rook on a1. } 11... Nb8
{ This Breyer like retreat has yet to be played. This is unsurprising given that White can seize the initiative with }
12. b4 { followed by Nbd2-b3. A sample line runs } 12... Nbd7 13. Nbd2 c6 14.
Nb3 Qc7 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Nh4
{ Black has a whole host of weaknesses on a5, c5, and f5. The absence of the light-squared bishop will tell sooner rather than later. White is clearly better with Be3 and Qf3 on the way. }
