1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3
{ This is the well-known Closed Spanish tabiya from which thousands upon thousands of games have been played. Many top players have ventured these waters and champions have been decided in the complexities of these structures. Mastering this structure is guaranteed to improve your chess understanding.   Black’s top three choices in this position are the Chigorin with  9...Na5  , the Breyer with  9...Nb8  and the Zaitsev with  9...Bb7  . In this chapter, we’ll examine all of Black’s other options on move 9. does have some other choices, which will be covered in this chapter. }
9... Qd7
{ This variation is named after Vassily Smyslov, who was the first to play it at the top level. It shares some similarities with the Zaitsev with the big difference that Ng5 can now be met with ...Nd8. This is the main point behind 9...Qd7. With the c8-h3 diagonal obstructed, Black's light-squared bishop will be developed to b7. }
10. d4 Re8 11. Bc2
{ Given that Ng5 is ineffective , the bishop on b3 is no longer doing much. As such, White drops it back to c2 to clear the way for d5-b3-c4 to create a big central bind. }
11... Bb7
{ Any other move like   11...h6  allows White to execute his plan undeterred:  12.d5  Nb8  13.b3  c6  14.c4±  with a big space advantage. }
12. d5 Nb8 13. c4
{ An interesting approach that sets Black practical problems. } 13... bxc4
{ Black bites the bullet and goes for all the complications. } 14. Na3 c6
{ is practically forced. Black must create some breathing space by challenging the center. }
15. dxc6 Nxc6 16. Nxc4
{ The dust has settled and Black has been left with a backward pawn on d6 as well as weak squares on d5 and b6. Bd2 followed by Rc1 is on the way with a clear advantage. }
*

