1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3
{ This is the well-known Closed Spanish tabiya from which thousands upon thousands of games have been played. Many top players have ventured these waters and champions have been decided in the complexities of these structures. Mastering this structure is guaranteed to improve your chess understanding.   Black’s top three choices in this position are the Chigorin with  9...Na5  , the Breyer with  9...Nb8  and the Zaitsev with  9...Bb7  . In this chapter, we’ll examine all of Black’s other options on move 9. does have some other choices, which will be covered in this chapter. }
9... h6
{ This is yet another variation named after the 7th World Champion Vassily Smyslov. Rather than playing ...Qd7 and clear the d8 square in order to meet Ng5 with ...Nd8, Black stops this outright with ...h6. Compared to the Zaitsev, Black's bishop is still not on b7 meaning Black lacks sufficient pressure against the e4 pawn. This will allow us to quickly get our knight to f1. }
10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2
{ The lack of any central pressure by the 2nd player allows White to embark on the knight tour. }
11... Bf8 12. Nf1
{ This is made possible thanks to Black's light-squared bishop still being on c8.   12.Nf1  As such  12...exd4  13.cxd4  Nxe4??  is not possible due to  14.Bd5+-  winning material. }
12... Bb7
{ Now that White's knight is no longer on c2, the bishop isn't particularly well placed on b7. From g3, the knight will perfectly cover e4. }
13. Ng3
{ The knight has once again reached its prime outpost on g3. Black is starting to regret the tempo lost on h6. Moreover, with the bishop on b7, the f5 square is vulnerable.  More details can be found in the nextalternative variation that you can opt to train. }
