O-O 9. h3 Na5
{ The Chigorin variation of the Ruy Lopez is one of the oldest lines in chess history. It's named after Mikhail Chigorin, who refined the variation around 1907, and since then thousands of games have been played from this position.   Theory has evolved significantly over the last couple of years and Black has been moving away from the Chigorin in favor of other variations such as the Breyer with 9...Nb8. The reason for this is that Black is under pressure in the Chigorin with White having the option of playing for two results due to the first player's space advantage and strong center. As always, if White makes a mistake, Black can get some counterplay. In our repertoire, we'll be completely neutralizing any such chances.   The point of ...Na5 is to clear the way for ...c7-c5 with a tempo on the light-squared bishop. The downside of this approach is the a5 knight often finds itself lacking good squares on the queenside once White expands in the center with d4-d5. }
10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Nd7 12. a4
{ We remain flexible in the center, not committing to d5 and instead striking on the queenside. The knight on a5 suddenly isn't feeling so comfortable after a2-a4. Note that 12.a4 does not work in the 11...Qc7 line as Black has the option of going 12... Bd7 there - an option not available in the position on the diagram. }
12... Bb7
{ Black develops the bishop to the wrong square. Do you remember what to do? 😊 Close the position! }
13. d5
{ The inclusion of a4 and ...Bb7 is firmly in White's favor. As a rule of thumb, you should remember that the bishop is completely misplaced on b7 and can be shut down with d4-d5. }
13... Qc7
{ White can play it slow with b3 but, in this particular position, the first player can go for the kill with }
14. b4 Nc4 15. Nfd2
{ This is the right way to challenge the knight on c4. The queenside knight is kept on b1 so it can come out to a3 and pressure Black's queenside. }
15... f5
{ Black tries to create some breathing space by challenging the e4 pawn. } 16.
Nxc4 bxc4 17. Qe2
{ New and strong, covering the e4 pawn and clearing the d1 square for Rd1. White's main objective is to secure the d5 stronghold. }
17... fxe4 18. Rd1
{ Having secured d5, White will now pick off the e4 and c4 pawns. This will result in a clear advantage. }
