1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Na5
{ The Chigorin variation of the Ruy Lopez is one of the oldest lines in chess history. It's named after Mikhail Chigorin, who refined the variation around 1907, and since then thousands of games have been played from this position.   Theory has evolved significantly over the last couple of years and Black has been moving away from the Chigorin in favor of other variations such as the Breyer with 9...Nb8. The reason for this is that Black is under pressure in the Chigorin with White having the option of playing for two results due to the first player's space advantage and strong center. As always, if White makes a mistake, Black can get some counterplay. In our repertoire, we'll be completely neutralizing any such chances.   The point of ...Na5 is to clear the way for ...c7-c5 with a tempo on the light-squared bishop. The downside of this approach is the a5 knight often finds itself lacking good squares on the queenside once White expands in the center with d4-d5. }
10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5
{ The modern main line and objectively strongest move. White defines the center to gain a space advantage.   The more popular  12.Nbd2  can be rejected for two reasons: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ there's a lot more theory to learn and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ Black is in good theoretical shape after  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  Nc6  or even after 12...Bd7 }
12... Bd7 { is another good option. } 13. b3 g6 14. Be3 Nh5 15. Nbd2
{ This is our standard setup: bishop on e3, knights on f3 and d2, and the pawn on b3. White is now fully ready to start active play on the queenside with a4. }
15... Bf6 16. Bd3 Bg7 17. a4
{ Puts strong pressure on the b5 pawn, which is very hard for Black to meet. Trading on a4 only helps White to open the f1-a6 diagonal and also the b-file. The same goes for ...c4. Finally, ...b4 gives up the crucial c4 square.  White is undoubtedly for choice.   A sample continuation is  18...Rab8  19.Bf1  A useful waiting move, stepping out of any tactics involving the ...c4 push.  19...b4  20.Rc1  Qd8  21.Nc4  Nxc4  22.Bxc4  bxc3  23.Rxc3  Rb4  24.g4!?  Black has no way to exploit the weaknesses created by this move, so White should take the opportunity to gain space on the kingside.  24...Nf4  25.Bxf4  exf4  26.e5!  with a safe advantage. }
