1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 d5
{ is known as the Gajewski Gambit. It carries the surname of the Polish GM Grzegorz Gajewski, who first played it against the Russian IM Viktor Kuznetsov in 2007. While an interesting surprise back then, it's not up to the scrutiny of today's engines.   10...c5  transposes to theChigorin variation. }
11. d4
{ is White's most ambitious way of meeting Black's gambit. We blow up the center taking advantage of the fact that our pieces are better centralized.   And not  11.exd5  which allows Black to push ahead with  11...e4!  12.Bxe4  Nxe4  13.Rxe4  Bb7  and gives the second player exactly the sort of play he's looking for. }
11... dxe4 12. Nxe5 c5 13. Be3
{ is very logical. White develops the c1 bishop before playing Nd2 and reinforces the center in the process. }
13... Bb7 14. Nd2 Rc8
{ Despite being three times less popular than 14...Qc7, this is Black's only way of staying in the game. }
15. Qe2 { is White's strongest option, clearing the way for Rad1. } 15... Re8
{ 15...Qc7  is once again strongly met by  16.Bf4!  when the e4 pawn will drop. For example  16...cxd4  17.Nxe4!  Nd5  was reached in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Macak, S  @@StartBracket@@2361@@EndBracket@@ -Ivanov,M @@StartBracket@@2483@@EndBracket@@ Prague 2008. Now White could have got a big advantage with the novel  18.Bg3Ν  dxc3  19.Nxc3  Nxc3  20.bxc3  Bd6  21.Qd3±  Black is under considerable pressure. }
16. Ng4
{ is an improvement over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@65@@EndBracket@@ Anadkat,K @@StartBracket@@2088@@EndBracket@@-Saptarshi,R @@StartBracket@@2480@@EndBracket@@ Udaipur 2019, where White played the inferior 16. Rad1. It's far stronger to undermine the f6 knight, which is a key defender of the e4 pawn. }
16... Nd5
{ 16...Nxg4  17.Qxg4+-  leaves the e4 pawn without protection. White is already close to winning. }
17. Bxe4 Nxe3 18. Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Qxe3
{ Black has little to show for the pawn deficit. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
