[White "9...Nb8 | Breyer"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Nb8
{ The Breyer is one of the most popular variations in the Closed Spanish and overall Ruy Lopez complex. It is named after Gyula Breyer who first recommended this line in 1911. It would only gain traction 50 years later when it was adopted by Spassky and a whole host of top players in the 1960s. The 10th World Champion cemented the reputation of the Breyer as an elite weapon after scoring several wins versus Tal in Tbilisi, 1965.   Objectively speaking, Black can equalize everywhere in the Breyer, which has led many top players to favor it over the Zaitsev or Chigorin variations. We're not going to give Black an easy life and will be putting as much pressure as possible.   Now you may be wondering, what is the point of undeveloping the knight? Black's standard setup is ...Nbd7, ...Bb7, .. .Re8, and ...Bf8 almost independently of White's continuation. By retreating the knight, Black's bishop on b7 will be unobstructed allowing it to pressure the e4 pawn. What is more, the c-pawn is now free to move forward.   9...Nb8  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  A key point of Black's strategy is now revealed. By pressuring the e4 pawn with ...Bb7, Black rules out the immediate knight maneuver Nf1-g3. To get it in, White must first reinforce e4 with  12.Bc2  Re8  13.Nf1  Bf8  Black typically premoves this entire sequence pretty much against anything White does. He's now threatening to win a pawn with ...exd4.  14.Ng3  The knight reaches its destination while reinforcing e4. Black typically meets this with  14...g6  and we've reached one of the main tabiyas in the Breyer. White has three main options at his disposal:  15.a4  ,  15.b3  and  15.Bg5  Black is in good theoretical shape in all three cases. After extensive analysis, we settled on an earlier deviation, namely 13. a4. It can transpose to lines in the 15. a4 variation with the advantage of cutting out several of Black's main tries. }
10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ is by far the main move.   A modern and interesting approach we analyzed is  11.c4  c6  12.Nc3  b4  Here all three knight moves were considered:   @@StartBracket@@a@@EndBracket@@  13.Na4  is the most promising. I found the ensuing positions to be too closed to cause Black any serious problems.  13...c5  14.d5  Black will play ...a6-a5 while White will try to undermine Black's queenside pawn chain with a2-a3. This leads to a highly complex strategic battle where Black's chances are no worse than White's.   @@StartBracket@@b@@EndBracket@@  13.Nb1  isn't anything to write home about. Provoking ...b4 doesn't give White anything.   @@StartBracket@@c@@EndBracket@@  13.Ne2  is an interesting pawn sacrifice. Black is in good theoretical shape after  13...Nxe4  14.Qc2  Nef6  15.Ng3  c5  16.dxe5  Nxe5  17.Nxe5  dxe5  18.Rxe5  Bd6  19.Re2  Qc7=  I don't see any issues for Black. }
11... Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8
{ is the absolute mainline. Black lines the rook up against the e4 pawn and vacates the f8 square for ...Bf8. After extensive analysis, I opted to recommend 13.a4 - a very venomous sideline that is both highly practical and objectively stronger than more common alternatives. }
13. a4
{ is my recommendation. What's the idea? By immediately undermining the b5 pawn, White prevents ...c7-c5 as Black will be forced to reinforce the b5 pawn with ...c6. }
13... Bf8 14. Bd3 c6
{ White's most popular move is 15. b3 but I was unable to find a White advantage there. I concluded the much rarer 15. Nf1 gives White much better chances for an edge. }
15. Nf1
{ The previous moves were designed to force Black to block the b7 bishop's path to our e4-pawn, allowing us to retreat the knight to f1 without having to play Ng3 right away. We can take advantage of this added flexibility by flicking in g2-g4 in a variety of lines, reaching favorable versions of the typical Breyer mainlines.   The text hasn't had the best of reputations as it allows Black to break in the center with  15...d5  Correct, but we're going to see exactly how to neutralize it 😉.   15...c5  is a typical pawn break. We simply push ahead with  16.d5  c4  17.Bc2  Nc5  and exploit the fact that our knight is still on g1 to get in  18.g4  with an improved version of the usual Breyer mainlines.   If Black opts for the typical Breyer move  15...g6  we reach a variation of the @@StartFEN@@r2qrbk1/1bpn1p1p/p2p1np1/1p2p3/3PP3/2P2NNP/PPB2PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.a4  Bg7  16.Bd3  c6  complex with the advantage of bypassing  16...exd4!?  which liquidates into equalish positions. This is already a nice achievement for White. }
