14... cxb3 15. axb3 Qc7 16. Bb2 a5 { is Black's most popular continuation. }
17. b4
{ is the most challenging option.   17.Bd3  featured in the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Caruana, F @@StartBracket@@2828@@EndBracket@@ - Harikrishna, P @@StartBracket@@2726@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019 that continued  17...b4  18.Nc4  Nc5  19.cxb4  axb4  20.Bc2  Rxa1  21.Bxa1  Now the simple and strong is  21...Nfd7Ν  with full equality. }
17... axb4 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. cxb4 Nb6 20. Bd3 Nc4 21. Bc1
{ Keeping the bishop pair on the board. White can exchange the knight on c4 and then regroup his pieces with Bb2, Qc2, and Nf3-d2-c4. Conversely, it's not easy for Black to improve. Another important factor that tips the position in White's favor is that Black's b5 pawn is far weaker than the one on b4.   21.Qc2  was played in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Sasikiran, K @@StartBracket@@2661@@EndBracket@@ - Postny, E @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Stockholm 2017. I prefer the text, which preserves the bishop pair. }
