1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Nb8
{ The Breyer is one of the most popular variations in the Closed Spanish and overall Ruy Lopez complex. It is named after Gyula Breyer who first recommended this line in 1911. It would only gain traction 50 years later when it was adopted by Spassky and a whole host of top players in the 1960s. The 10th World Champion cemented the reputation of the Breyer as an elite weapon after scoring several wins versus Tal in Tbilisi, 1965.   Objectively speaking, Black can equalize everywhere in the Breyer, which has led many top players to favor it over the Zaitsev or Chigorin variations. We're not going to give Black an easy life and will be putting as much pressure as possible.   Now you may be wondering, what is the point of undeveloping the knight? Black's standard setup is ...Nbd7, ...Bb7, .. .Re8, and ...Bf8 almost independently of White's continuation. By retreating the knight, Black's bishop on b7 will be unobstructed allowing it to pressure the e4 pawn. What is more, the c-pawn is now free to move forward.   9...Nb8  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  A key point of Black's strategy is now revealed. By pressuring the e4 pawn with ...Bb7, Black rules out the immediate knight maneuver Nf1-g3. To get it in, White must first reinforce e4 with  12.Bc2  Re8  13.Nf1  Bf8  Black typically premoves this entire sequence pretty much against anything White does. He's now threatening to win a pawn with ...exd4.  14.Ng3  The knight reaches its destination while reinforcing e4. Black typically meets this with  14...g6  and we've reached one of the main tabiyas in the Breyer. White has three main options at his disposal:  15.a4  15. b3 and 15. Bg5. Black is in good theoretical shape in all three cases. After extensive analysis, we settled on an earlier deviation, namely 13. a4. It can transpose to lines in the 15. a4 variation with the advantage of cutting out several of Black's main tries. }
10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7
{ Black follows his typical development scheme and puts immediate pressure on the e4 pawn. }
12. Bc2 Re8
{ is the absolute mainline. Black lines the rook up against the e4 pawn and vacates the f8 square for ... Bf8. After extensive analysis, I opted to recommend 13.a4 - a very venomous sideline that is both highly practical and objectively stronger than more common alternatives. }
13. a4
{ What's the idea? By immediately undermining the b5 pawn, White prevents ...c7-c5 as Black will be forced to reinforce the b5 pawn with ...c6. }
13... Bf8 14. Bd3 c6
{ Pretty much the only move regularly played at this junction. Black firmly secures the b5 pawn and claims his position is very solid. White's most popular move is 15. b3 but I was unable to find a White advantage there. I concluded the much rarer 15. Nf1 gives White much better chances for an edge. }
15. Nf1
{ The whole point of our operation. The previous moves were designed to force Black to block the b7 bishop's path to our e4-pawn, allowing us to retreat the knight to f1 without having to play Ng3 right away. We can take advantage of this added flexibility by flicking in g2-g4 in a variety of lines, reaching favorable versions of the usual Breyer. The text hasn't had the best of reputations as it allows Black to break in the center with 15...d5. Correct, but we're going to see how to neutralize it 😉. }
15... g6 { is the old-ish approach, nowadays considered to be quite passive. }
16. Ng3 Bg7 17. Be3
{ Here Black has two main queen sorties, one is to c7 and the other is on e7. }
17... Qe7
{ Developing the queen to e7 as opposed to c7 does not change our approach. We'll be sliding the queen to d2, pushing b2 and then rerouting the bishop to b3. }
18. Qd2 Qf8
{ Gets the queen out of the way. Black's pieces are stepping on each other's toes and his position is overall very passive. }
19. b3
{ White reinforces the a4 pawn and is ready for Bc2, Rad1, b4, and eventually dxe5 will come.   19.b3  The only game to reach this position continued  19...h6  20.dxe5  Nxe5  21.Nxe5  dxe5  22.b4⩲  Black's queen is stuck on f8 covering the h6 pawn. Conversely, White can play Rad1 and then drop back the queen to c1 with a firm grip on the position. }
*

