{ is the most critical continuation, immediately trying to punish our sneaky move-order. The most critical choice! Immediately trying to punish White's sneaky move-order. }
16. Nxe5
{ is the point. This move gives White good chances for an advantage and was not considered by GM Michael Roiz in the database Complete Spanish Repertoire for Black - The Breyer System for Modern Chess.   16.Bg5  is White's most popular move. The mainline continues  16...dxe4  17.Rxe4  Be7  18.Bxf6  Bxf6  19.Nxe5  Nxe5  20.dxe5  Bxe5  21.Qe2  Bf6  22.Re1  Even here White's position is more pleasant. Black is nevertheless objectively fine. }
16... dxe4 17. Nxd7 Qxd7
{ GM Ivan Sokolov stopped here in the Chessable course Ruy Lopez: The Breyer Variation, claiming "This looks ok for Black." We analyzed this position several moves deeper and are about to show that White has the better chances. }
18. Bc2
{ Let's take stock. The e4 pawn is a target and Black's bishop on b7 is severely limited. Black's only chance to equalize is to undermine White's b2-c3-d4 pawn chain with ...b5-b4, but White is well equipped to handle this. It's objectively not much, but White's position is for sure easier to play. }
18... h6 { was Black's choice in the only two games to reach this position. }
19. Ng3 c5 20. dxc5 { White trades into a favorable endgame. } 20... Qxd1 21.
Rxd1 Bxc5 22. Nf5
{ improves over the game½-½ @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Kindermann,S @@StartBracket@@2520@@EndBracket@@-Smejkal,J @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ Germany 1987 where White played 22. Be3. With the e4-pawn well guarded, the knight has done its job on g3 and should seek greener pastures. We can follow up with Be3 and, if possible, land the knight on d6. }
