{ is Black's best option, which has yet to be played. The second player must put immediate pressure on the d4 pawn in order to maintain the balance. }
19. c4
{ White bypasses the b-pawn in order to prevent ...c6-c5. This weakens the d4 pawn, but we have sufficient resources to protect it. }
19... Rad8 20. Be3 { Reinforcing the d4 pawn. } 20... Bc8
{ may seem strange but it's hard to come up with an active plan for Black. }
21. Ng3
{ Slowly rounding up the e4-pawn. Next up is Bg5 with a sizeable advantage.   A sample line runs  21.Bd6  22.Bg5  There are other possibilities as well, but I quite like this enterprising approach.  22...Bxg3  23.fxg3  Qxd4  24.Qxd4  Rxd4  25.Be3  Black's extra pawn is largely irrelevant. The two bishops are very strong and Black's queenside pawns are likely to drop in the near future. White is for choice.  You can opt to train this sample variation in the nextalternative variation. }
