19... Rad8 20. Be3 { Reinforcing the d4 pawn. } 20... a5 21. Ng3
{ Simple and effective.   21.f3  is another interesting possibility that leads to complex play. Black needs to find  21...Qc7  so as to be able to meet  22.fxe4  with  22...Bc5!  when Black is doing well. }
21... Bd6
{ What else? It's hard to come up with a constructive move for Black so he might as well tickle the knight on g3. }
22. f4
{ It's important to always be aware of the opponent's resources.   22.Bg5  doesn't yield much after  22...Bxg3  23.fxg3  Qxd4+  24.Qxd4  Rxd4  25.Be3  c5!  This is the hidden resource!  26.Rad1  doesn't help due to  26...Red8  This was not possible in the 20...Bc8 variation as there the e4 pawn lacked protection. }
22... g6 { with the idea ...h5-h4 to kick the g3 knight. } 23. Qd2
{ The machine claims Black is very close to equality, but I don't think he's fully there. White has the straightforward plan of regroups his pieces with Qf2, Rad1 followed by f4-f5 at an opportune moment.   23...b3?!  may look tempting at first sight but the resulting position after  24.Bxb3  Bb4  25.Qf2  Bxe1  26.Rxe1±  is clearly better for White. ...g7-g6 has considerably weakened the dark-squares around Black's king and created a hook for f4-f5 - now a serious threat. }
