1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Bb7
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@In my opinion the only system @@StartSquare@@in the Closed Spanish@@EndSquare@@ that might fully equalize for Black is the so-called Zaitsev system - Vladimir Kramnik@@EndBlockQuote@@The @@StartBracket@@Flohr@@EndBracket@@-Zaitsev variation is named after Igor Zaitsev, who was Anatoly Karpov's trainer for many years. The 12th World Champion was a great specialist of this defense and can be credited to making the Zaitsev one of the most important variations in the Closed Spanish complex. Theory has developed in leaps and bounds since the variation was first discovered in the 1970s with today's analysis stretching well into the middlegame. As such, precise knowledge of the variations is required to fight for an opening advantage.   The Zaitsev is one of the most ambitious systems in the Ruy Lopez complex. Black puts his bishop on b7 and the f8 rook will soon come to e8 to pressure e4 all while keeping the knight on c6 flexible. }
10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2
{ One of Zaitsev's greatest discoveries was that  11.Ng5  Rf8  12.f4  is not a problem for Black as after  12...exf4  13.Bf4  Na5!  14.Bc2  Black now has the fantastic tactical resource  14...Nd5  uncovering an attack on the g5 knight. Following  15.exd5  Bxg5  16.Qh5  h6  Black is in great shape.   Black must, however, be content in accepting a draw after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1N1/3PP3/1BP4P/PP3PP1/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nf3  Re8  13.Ng5  Rf8  15.Nf3  should White want one. }
11... Bf8
{ The main point of Black's setup is that  12.Nf1  initiating the typical Spanish maneuver Nf1-g3 is no good given it drops the e4 pawn after  12...exd4  13.cxd4  Na5  14.Bc2  Nxe4∓ }
12. a3
{ is the modern mainline and my suggestion.   It's both far calmer and objectively stronger than the alternatives  12.a4  ,  12.d5  and  12.Bc2  .  With the text, White covers the b4 square and creates a square for the bishop on a2. This rules out many of Black's chances for counterplay, usually connected with ...exd4, ...Nb4, and a quick ...c5 to undermine White's center. }
