1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Bb7
{ The @@StartBracket@@Flohr@@EndBracket@@-Zaitsev variation is named after Igor Zaitsev, who was Anatoly Karpov's trainer for many years. The 12th World Champion was a great specialist of this defense and can be credited to making the Zaitsev one of the most important variations in the Closed Spanish complex. Theory has developed in leaps and bounds since the variation was first discovered in the 1970s with today's analysis stretching well into the middlegame. As such, precise knowledge of the variations is required to fight for an opening advantage.   This is one of the most ambitious systems in the Ruy Lopez complex. Black puts his bishop on b7 and f8 rook will soon come to e8 all while keeping the knight on c6 flexible.   Exciting, complex, and dynamic lines await you! Let's get started! }
10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2
{ We are obviously not going for  11.Ng5  Rf8  12.Nf3  a repetition which has led to thousands of games ending in a draw. }
11... Bf8
{ This is the main tabiya in the Zaitsev. Black's main ideas are to play ...g6 or ...h6 and/or ... Nb8-d7. }
12. a3
{ is the modern mainline and my suggestion.   It's both far calmer and objectively stronger than the alternatives  12.a4  ,  12.d5  and  12.Bc2  .  With the text, White covers the b4 square and creates a square for the bishop on a2. This rules out many of Black's chances for counterplay, usually connected with ...exd4, ...Nb4, and a quick ...c5 to undermine White's center. }
12... h6
{ Stopping any Ng5 business is by far Black's most popular and logical move. }
13. Bc2
{ With Ng5 ruled out, the bishop isn't doing much on the a2-g8 diagonal. As such, it makes sense to drop it back to c2 in order to reinforce the e4 pawn. }
13... d5
{ is the most direct approach, immediately fighting for the center. This sharp move was a favorite of Morozevich, who played a great role in popularizing it. White now needs to be accurate to emerge with an advantage. }
14. dxe5 Nxe5 { A forced sequence of moves now follows. } 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 16. Nf3
Re8 17. e5 Ne4
{ This position arose pretty much by force. White has several options and I spent many hours trying to find a path towards an advantage. }
18. Bf4
{ I came to the conclusion that this is White's strongest option. This move retains maximum flexibility, not yet committing the queen to e2. Since the bishop is best placed on this square, it makes sense to start with this move. }
18... c5
{ is Black's only logical continuation. Black takes control over the d4 square, thus ruling out Nd4, in preparation for ...f5. }
19. a4
{ By immediately undermining Black's queenside, we give the second player no time to get ...f5 in. }
19... Qb6
{ After this move, it becomes clear why we delayed Qe2.   19...Bc6  is well met by  20.Re2!?  f5  21.exf6  Qxf6  22.axb5  axb5  23.Rxa8  Bxa8  24.Bh2⩲  with a slight advantage. Black's queenside pawns are nothing but targets. }
20. Nd2
{ If our queen were already on e2, Black could have simply played f5. As it stands, his forced to part with the strong knight on e4. }
20... Nxd2
{ 20...f5?!  is no good due to  21.f3!  when Black is forced to take on d2.  21...c4+  22.Kh2  Nxd2  23.Qxd2± }
21. Qxd2
{ White the annoying knight exchanged, White can look to the future with confidence. Black's queenside pawns are overextended and the f8 bishop is very passive. }
