1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ It's now time to cover the Marshall defense,  which is arguably one of Black's best defenses against 1.e4. Rather than head for a solid line in the closed variations, Black meets   8.c3  with  8...d5  sacrificing a pawn in return for fantastic piece activity, drastically changing the character of the game. Thousands of games have been played in these lines with reams of theory and no White advantage in sight.   Rather than try and navigate this labyrinth of variations, I've chosen to recommend the practical  8.a4  Anti-Marshall variation. Yes, Black can equalize with precise play @@StartBracket@@it'll be hard though!@@EndBracket@@ but equal does not at all mean drawn. There's plenty of room to outplay your opponent in the variations I'm about to recommend. Provided you internalize the key ideas and plans explained throughout this chapter, there'll be good practical chances of putting pressure on your opponent. }
8. a4
{ is an interesting way of preventing the Marshall Gambit. The idea is to clarify the queenside pawn structure at an early stage and gain control over the c4 square, which can become a possible outpost for one of White's knights.   One of the main points behind  8.a4  is that  8...Rb8  is well met by  9.axb5  axb5  10.c3  d5  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Nxe5  when the control over the a-file gives White a superior version of the standard Marshall attack positions. }
*

