1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ It's now time to cover the Marshall,  which is arguably one of Black's best defenses against 1.e4. Rather than head for a solid line in the closed variations, Black meets 8. c3 with 8...d5 sacrificing a pawn in return for fantastic piece activity, drastically changing the character of the game.   Thousands of games have been played in these lines with reams of theory and no White advantage in sight. Rather than try and navigate this labyrinth of variations, I've chosen to recommend the practical 8. a4 Anti-Marshall variation. Yes, Black can equalize with precise play @@StartBracket@@it'll be hard though!@@EndBracket@@ but equal does not at all mean drawn. There's plenty of room to outplay your opponent in the variations I'm about to recommend. If you internalize the key ideas and plans explained throughout this chapter, you'll have good practical chances of putting pressure on your opponent. }
8. a4
{ is an interesting way of preventing the Marshall Gambit. The idea is to clarify the queenside pawn structure at an early stage and gain control over the c4 square, which can become a possible outpost for one of White's knights. }
8... Rb8
{ Black gets his rook out of the a-file, neutralizing the threat of axb5. His plan is to develop the light-squared along the c8-h3 diagonal instead of posting it on b7. The downside to this approach is that Black gives up control of the a-file. }
9. axb5 axb5 10. h3 { 10.c3  d5!  is great for Black. } 10... d6 11. c3
{ White is now threatening to take over the center with d2-d4, which Black should prevent by playing }
11... b4 12. d3
{ 12.d4?!  doesn't give White much after  12...bxc3  13.bxc3  exd4  14.cxd4  d5!  15.e5  Ne4=  when Black has a powerful knight on e4. }
12... bxc3
{ 12...Bd7  can simply be met by  13.Be3  h6  14.Nbd2  Re8  15.Qc2⩲  with a stable advantage. }
13. bxc3
{ White is now planning to complete development with Qc2 and reroute the b1 knight to f1, from where it can jump to e3 or g3. This is a typical maneuver to remember. }
13... d5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Ba4
{ While Black is objectively fine, White's position is easier to play due to the pressure on the e5 pawn.  Best play by both sides follows   15.Ba4  Ra8  16.Ba3  Ra6  17.Bb5  Rb6  18.Bxc6  Rxc6  19.Nxe5  Re6  20.d4=  when White is more comfortable. Black has good compensation for the pawn but hey, a pawn is still a pawn. }
