{ It's now time to cover the Marshall,  which is arguably one of Black's best defenses against 1.e4. Rather than head for a solid line in the closed variations, Black meets 8. c3 with 8...d5 sacrificing a pawn in return for fantastic piece activity, drastically changing the character of the game.   Thousands of games have been played in these lines with reams of theory and no White advantage in sight. Rather than try and navigate this labyrinth of variations, I've chosen to recommend the practical 8. a4 Anti-Marshall variation. Yes, Black can equalize with precise play @@StartBracket@@it'll be hard though!@@EndBracket@@ but equal does not at all mean drawn. There's plenty of room to outplay your opponent in the variations I'm about to recommend. If you internalize the key ideas and plans explained throughout this chapter, you'll have good practical chances of putting pressure on your opponent. }
8. a4
{ is an interesting way of preventing the Marshall Gambit. The idea is to clarify the queenside pawn structure at an early stage and gain control over the c4 square, which can become a possible outpost for one of White's knights. }
8... b4
{ is Black's second most popular move, gaining space on the queenside. } 9. a5
{ is a fashionable response. We follow suit expanding on the queenside while fixing Black's a6 pawn and isolating the b4 pawn. }
9... d6 10. d3
{ White's main plan is to expand in the center with c2-c3 and d3-d4. } 10...
Be6
{ is Black's most common and logical move. The second player develops his last minor piece and seeks to neutralize White's powerful light-squared bishop.   Worse is  10...Bg4?!  The pin only helps White, who is likely to get the useful h2-h3 move in with tempo.  11.c3  bxc3  12.bxc3  Rb8  13.Nbd2  d5  14.Qc2⩲  which gave White the upper hand in the game 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Bosiocic,M @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@-Srbis,J @@StartBracket@@2421@@EndBracket@@ Mali Losinj 2017. }
11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Nbd2 d5
{ is an interesting plan. Black immediately strikes in the center before White can get c3 and d4 in. The downside of this break is that the e5 pawn is weakened. }
13. Nb3
{ We first stop ...Bc5 before playing c2-c3. We're now threatening to win the e5 pawn with exd5.  The immediate   13.exd5  isn't nearly as strong as after  13...exd5  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.Rxe5  Bc5  Black gets excellent play along the f-file and has good pressure against the f2 pawn. We start with Nb3 exactly to prevent this move. }
13... d4
{ 13...Bd6  is well met by  14.Bg5!  intending to drop back the bishop with Bh4-g3 to target the e5 pawn, as seen in the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Nataf,I @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@-Del Rio,R @@StartBracket@@2422@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016. }
14. Rf1
{ is an interesting novelty. Rather than prepare the c3 break, it's stronger to try and engineer the f4 pawn lever. }
14... Qe8 15. Bg5
{ with a slight advantage. White is ready to drop back the knight back to d2  @@StartBracket@@which can later head to c4@@EndBracket@@ and then break with f2-f4. }
