1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ It's now time to cover the Marshall,  which is arguably one of Black's best defenses against 1.e4. Rather than head for a solid line in the closed variations, Black meets 8. c3 with 8...d5 sacrificing a pawn in return for fantastic piece activity, drastically changing the character of the game.   Thousands of games have been played in these lines with reams of theory and no White advantage in sight. Rather than try and navigate this labyrinth of variations, I've chosen to recommend the practical 8. a4 Anti-Marshall variation. Yes, Black can equalize with precise play @@StartBracket@@it'll be hard though!@@EndBracket@@ but equal does not at all mean drawn. There's plenty of room to outplay your opponent in the variations I'm about to recommend. If you internalize the key ideas and plans explained throughout this chapter, you'll have good practical chances of putting pressure on your opponent. }
8. a4
{ is an interesting way of preventing the Marshall Gambit. The idea is to clarify the queenside pawn structure at an early stage and gain control over the c4 square, which can become a possible outpost for one of White's knights. }
8... Bb7 { is the absolute mainline in the 8.a4 Anti-Marshall. } 9. d3 d5
{ has been played by several top-GMs, including Magnus Carlsen so it certainly deserves some attention. White is, however, well-equipped to meet this Marshall-like break. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. axb5
{ This option, coupled with the subsequent rook exchange, is a key difference to the true Marshall Gambit. This extra option favors White as Black's a8 rook usually adds fuel to Black's attack while our rook on a1 is typically passive. Another difference in White's favor is that Black's light-squared bishop is already committed to b7, while it'd be better placed for an attack if it were still on the c8-h3 diagonal. These small differences add up to a slight White edge after the following sequence.   11.Nc3!?  is also interesting. The availability of the c3 square for White's knight is another feature that's not present in the actual Marshall Gambit  @@StartBracket@@where White has a pawn on c3 instead@@EndBracket@@.  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bf6  13.Nd2=  Black was objectively fine in1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Dzhumaev,M @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ -Navin,K @@StartBracket@@2295@@EndBracket@@ Mumbai 2010. Still, I find White's position easier to play with Ba3 and Qg4 on the agenda.   11.Nbd2  is playable but I wasn't able to find much for White after  11...Qd7  12.Ne4  b4Ν  13.Ng3  a5  14.h3  f6=  Black will play ...Kh8 next with a good game. }
11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Nxe5 Nd4 14. c3
{ Black can maintain the balance with precise play, but White is up a pawn and has easier play.   I prefer the text to  14.Nd2  as after  14...Nxb3  15.Nxb3  White's knight isn't well placed on b3. }
