Bd2
{ 10.Nbd2  is White's most popular option, which has been played in thousands of games. I was unable to find any trace of a White advantage in those lines and thus opted to recommend this rarer move, which asks some interesting practical questions and is likely to surprise your opponents. The point of 10. Bd2 is to prevent ...Na5. }
10... Qd7
{ is a logical move, developing the last remaining piece and waiting for White to play Nc3 when ...Na5 will then be possible. The drawback is that the typical Marshall maneuver ...Bc8-e6 is no longer available. }
11. Nc3 Na5
{ Worse is  11...Nd4?!  12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Ne2  c5  14.Ng3⩲  There's no doubt White is better here. Black's d4 pawn can be undermined with c2-c3 while ...d6-d5 is well met by e4-e5. }
12. Ba2 b4 13. Ne2
{ Black is objectively fine, but White's position is easier to play with ideas of Ng3 and Nh4-f5. The lopsided 6/8 score in practice is good evidence. }
13... c5 14. Ng3 Rab8
{ Placing the rook on b8 to support ...b3 later on is a typical plan. } 15. Nh4
{ 15.h3  Qc7  16.Nf5  is another good option. } 15... g6
{ Black cannot allow our knight to land on f5, but this comes at the cost of weakening the dark-squares around the king. }
16. Bh6 Rfe8 17. Nhf5 { And the knight gets to f5 anyhow! } 17... Bd8
{ The knight is untouchable as  17...gxf5??  18.Nxf5+-  followed by Qf3-g3 is decisive. }
18. Ng7 Rf8
{ was all recommended in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: 1.e4 e5 by GM Jan Gustafsson. I don't think Black is out of the woods just yet and can suggest two interesting continuations not considered in the aforementioned course: }
19. N7h5
{ 19.h3  preventing ...Ng4 is also playable.  19...b3  20.Bxb3  Nxb3  21.cxb3  Bc6  22.Rf1∞  with the idea f2-f4. The knight on g7 is not trapped since the piece sacrifice N7f5 is on White's agenda. }
19... Nxh5 20. Nxh5 Re8 21. Re3
{ And here comes the Rover @@StartBracket@@rook up and over!@@EndBracket@@. While Black can maintain the balance with precise play, White's position is easier to play. }
