8. a4
{ is an interesting way of preventing the Marshall Gambit. The idea is to clarify the queenside pawn structure at an early stage and gain control over the c4 square, which can become a possible outpost for one of White's knights. }
8... Bb7 { is the absolute mainline in the 8.a4 Anti-Marshall. } 9. d3 d6 10.
Bd2
{ 10.Nbd2  is White's most popular option, which has been played in thousands of games. I was unable to find any trace of a White advantage in those lines and thus opted to recommend this rarer move, which asks some interesting practical questions and is likely to surprise your opponents. The point of 10. Bd2 is to prevent ...Na5. }
10... b4
{ is Black's most popular move. Having played Bd2, the b1 knight can no longer come out to d2 so it makes perfect sense to advance ...b4 and take away the c3 square. }
11. c3
{ After careful analysis, I came to the conclusion that immediately challenging Black's b4 pawn is the most promising continuation. We also have ideas of expanding with d3-d4 at an opportune moment. }
11... d5
{ is a risky pawn sacrifice.   11...a5?!  is too slow, allowing White to take over the center with  12.d4⩲ }
12. cxb4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Nd4
{ is an interesting tactical way of solving Black's problems, but White emerges with an advantage after   13...Bd6?!  is too passive.  14.h3  Nxb4  15.Nxe5  Bxe5  16.Bxb4⩲  leaves White with an extra pawn.   13...Bxb4?!  isn't much better due to  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.Bxb4⩲ }
14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Bc3 Qxd1 16. Rxd1
{ gave White the upper hand in the game1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ King,D @@StartBracket@@2475@@EndBracket@@ -Hebden,M @@StartBracket@@2475@@EndBracket@@ London 1988. Black's queenside pawn structure is compromised.   Note that  16...Nxe4  is well met by  17.Be1!  Rab8  18.Bc4⩲  with good practical chances. White has a favorable structure, with the 3 vs 2 on the queenside enabling the creation of a passed pawn.   @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bp1bppp/p7/4p3/PP2n3/1BB5/1P3PPP/RN1R2K1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Bxe5  Bxb4  18.Bxc7  Bc5  19.Bg3  Nxg3  20.hxg3  gives White very little. Black's two bishops offer sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit. }
