{ This position arose from the Bird's Defense @@StartBracket@@3...Nd4@@EndBracket@@. Do you recall how White should keep the initiative going? }
8. Qh5 { Attacking the f7-pawn, thus forcing Black to castle. } 8... O-O
{ 8...g6  creates too many holes in the queenside which can be exploited by  9.Qh6± }
9. Bg5 { If Black tries to kick the bishop with } 9... h6
{ it turns out White can just ignore it! } 10. Nd2
{ A smart way to develop the piece while not being afraid of dropping the bishop on g5.   10...hxg5?  fails due to  11.Nf3+-  and White's attack is overwhelming.   10...Be6  11.Bxe6  fxe6  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.a3±  13. g3 was also possible, but it's better to keep the ...Bb4 tricks off the board. Moreover, White may also choose to expand with b2-b4 later on.   Next, White can also start throwing his kingside pawns. With the bishop on c5 buried, White has a big advantage. }
