{ Where does White's queen belong? } 10. Qd3
{ 10.Qe2  is possible but the text is far tricker, giving Black more options of going wrong.  10...Ne7  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Rd1  Qc8  13.Be3  As we will see in the 10.Qd3!? variation Black will either have to play g7-g6 which will take away the g6-square from the knight or if he finds the best way, the queen would still be much better placed on d3. }
10... Ne7 11. Rd1 Qc8
{ is Black's best options. The alternatives below are inferior.   11...Ng6  is premature and allows White to strike with  12.h4!  disturbing the knight on g6.  12...h5  13.Nd5  c6  14.Ne3  Nf4  15.Qf1  Qc7  16.c4±  White's dream pawn break is in and he now has full control over the center. Moreover, the f4 knight will soon be kicked back.   11...g6  takes away the g6-square from the knight and after  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Qe2  Qc8  14.Be3  White can still think of going for the h4-h5 break, while Black's knight is now clumsily placed. White can also lock down the queenside with b3-b4 when the c5-square will be a nice outpost. }
12. Be3 Ng6 13. Nd5
{ is an interesting continuation. Taking on e5 or h4 were other good options. }
13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Be7 15. c4
{ White will either pick up the b5 pawn or establish a big pawn center. } *

