[SetUp "1"]

{ What was the important novelty that Sethuraman missed here? } 17. g4
{ A very deep and strong idea! As explained in the main section of the course:   This is an extremely strong novelty that I've had in my files for a while now. I discovered it when examining this line from Black's point of view. Sethuraman completely missed this strong idea, which makes his proposed repertoire practically unplayable OTB. The only way Black is surviving the upcoming complications is if he plays like an engine.   g2-g4 carries a very deep point. It may seem like White is preparing g4-g5 but this is NOT the case! It may sound funny, but g4 is a high-class waiting move that leaves Black almost in zugzwang.   How come you may be asking? If you look closely, you'll see that Black can barely move any of his pieces:   @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ The rook on a8 is protecting the a7-bishop. Moving it away allows White to push ahead with d4-d5;   @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ The bishops are stuck;   @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@ The knights can't really leave their posts;   @@StartBracket@@4@@EndBracket@@ The e8-rook is not doing much and has nowhere to go;   @@StartBracket@@5@@EndBracket@@ Finally, any pawn moves just weaken Black's position. For example, ... h6 only creates a hook for g4-g5.   As such, Black must bail out with a concrete move and the only possibility is to take on d4. }
*

